 my team so I decided to investigate the other companies before sizing the internal effort.\",\"index\":301,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Surprisingly, among the four existing network automation players, the company that we thought had the best product architecture, Rendition Networks, had the lowest revenues. This made some of our businesspeople skeptical of our technical evaluation. However, if I’d learned anything it was that conventional wisdom had nothing to do with the truth and the efficient market hypothesis was deceptive. How else could one explain Opsware trading at half of the cash we had in the bank when we had a $20 million a year contract and fifty of the smartest engineers in the world? No, markets weren’t “efficient” at finding the truth; they were just very efficient at converging on a conclusion—often the wrong conclusion.\",\"index\":302,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"After confirming that acquiring would be superior to building, we negotiated a deal to buy Rendition Networks for $33 million. Within three months of completing the acquisition, John negotiated a deal with Cisco Systems—the world’s largest networking company—to resell our product. The deal included an agreement to prepay us $30 million for advanced licenses. As a result, the Cisco deal alone paid more than 90 percent of the acquisition costs.\",\"index\":303,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Note to self: It’s a good idea to ask, “What am I not doing?”\",\"index\":304,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"Almost as soon as the EDS crisis was resolved, three expected clients began drifting away due to a formidable new competitor, BladeLogic, which led to losing deals, missing quarterly targets, and a plummeting stock price. Meanwhile, Marc focused on founding Ning, leaving Opsware's fate in our hands. Feeling defeated, I called an all-engineering meeting and bluntly stated our product was losing; our survival hinged on their dedication for the next six months. The team responded with extraordinary effort through the Darwin Project, ultimately leading to our success. Reflecting on this, I wished I had known their resilience earlier. Defining the product involved prioritizing innovation over existing customer requirements, which demanded courage and clear direction. Nine months later, we had a product ready to dominate. Mark Cranney, head of sales, revamped the sales process, enforcing thorough and strategic efforts. A sales rep’s oversight exposed the need for detailed engagement, and our competitive position improved with decisive action. In a meeting, I introduced “What Are We Not Doing?” which revealed our neglect of network automation. Despite lower revenues, we acquired Rendition Networks for its superior architecture, confirming markets often converge on incorrect conclusions. A $30 million prepayment deal with Cisco covered most acquisition costs. A key lesson: always ask, “What am I not doing?”\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**THE ULTIMATE DECISION**\",\"index\":305,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"As we fielded the broader product line, our momentum steadily grew. From the ashes, we’d built a software business that approached a $150 million revenue run rate. Along with our revenue, our stock price rose from its floor of $0.35 per share as well as we traded between $6 per share and $8 per share, sometimes trading at a market capitalization of more than $800 million.\",\"index\":306,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Still, everything was not rosy. Every quarter was tough, and the competitive and the technology landscapes changed rapidly. A technology called virtualization was taking the market by storm and changing the way customers thought about automating their environments. In fact, it looked to me like virtualization might be the technological breakthrough that finally enabled the cloud computing business model to work. Beyond that, being a public company was still never going to get easy. At one point, a shareholder activist named Rachel Hyman decided that my ego was out of control, and she demanded that the board remove me and sell the company immediately. This was despite the fact that we were trading at $7 per share, which was ten times the original price of her shares.\",\"index\":307,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Nonetheless, I was not looking for the exits. Whenever a potential acquirer approached us, I would always reply, “We are not for sale.” It was a great answer in that I wasn’t ready to sell and it conveyed that, but it also left the door open to a particularly aggressive buyer. “Not for sale” didn’t mean that we wouldn’t listen to offers—it just meant that we weren’t trying to sell the company. So, when EMC implied that it wanted to buy us, I thought nothing of it. We were trading at about $6.50 per share and I wasn’t planning to sell at anything close to that price. But this time the news of the offer leaked to the press and the stock shot up to $9.50 per share, changing the economic equation, especially since the stock was going up for all the wrong reasons.\",\"index\":308,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Ironically, the higher the stock price went up, the more companies wanted to buy us. Over the course of the next month, eleven companies expressed interest. Given the uncertainty in the business and the implied earnings multiple, their interest was too much to ignore.\",\"index\":309,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"To get things started, John and I called Michael Ovitz to get some advice. We felt one of the potential bidders, Oracle, would be the least likely to bid high, because it was extremely disciplined in its financial analysis. We conveyed this to Michael and questioned whether we should pursue Oracle at all. His reply was priceless: “Well, boys, if you are going to have a dog race, then you are going to need a rabbit. And Oracle will be one hell of a rabbit.”\",\"index\":310,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"With that strategy in hand, we generated a broad set of bids, all between $10 and $11 per share, with the highest bids representing a 38 percent premium over the current stock price. Although this was considered a good premium, I did not feel right selling the company for $11 per share. The team had worked too hard, we’d accomplished too much, and we were too good a company. The risks of staying stand-alone were substantial, but I still wanted to bet on the team. I recommended to the board that we not sell.\",\"index\":311,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"The board was surprised, but supportive. Still, they had a fiduciary responsibility to shareholders to ask the tough questions. “If you’re unwilling to sell at eleven dollars per share, is there a price at which you would sell?” I had to think about that one. I had promised the team that if we got to be the number-one company in a big market, we would not sell. We were number one, but how big was the market? Did the team really want to continue or was it just me who wanted to continue? How could I know without panicking the company? And thus began a series of very long talks with myself.\",\"index\":312,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"It was an argument to the death, and it was me against me. On the one hand, I argued that virtualization created an explosion of virtual server instances, making what we did more essential than ever. In the next breath, I retorted that while that may have been true, the architectural changes would make our market position vulnerable. I battled myself for weeks before concluding that things were changing fast enough that we’d need to make major changes to our product architecture in order to stay on top. The key to answering the ultimate question was knowing the state of the team. Were they up for yet another giant challenge or were they at the end of a very long road? I decided to bring my direct reports into the loop and ask them what they thought. The answers came back clear: Everyone, with the exception of one person who felt that the opportunity in front of us was still quite large, opted for the sale. Now it was just a matter of price. But what price?\",\"index\":313,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"After a long discussion with John O’Farrell, I decided that the right price to sell the company would be $14 per share, or about $1.6 billion. I took that number back to the board. They thought the number was extremely high and that it was unlikely we’d be able to generate a bid at that level, but they were supportive nonetheless. I called back all the potential acquirers and let them know that we would only entertain bids of $14 or more. There were no takers.\",\"index\":314,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"More than a month passed without a word, and I figured the M&A talks had ended. I began refocusing on how to make the necessary changes to keep us competitive. And then I received a call from Bob Beauchamp, the CEO of BMC Software. He offered $13.25 per share. I held firm: “Bob, that’s great, but the number is fourteen dollars per share.” Bob said that he’d have to think about it. He called back two days later and offered $14 per share. Wow. The dog had caught the bus.\",\"index\":315,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"John and I immediately called back all the other suitors to let them know that we had an offer that we planned to take. Hewlett-Packard was still interested and offered $13.50 per share in an effort to make sure that I wasn’t bluffing. I responded that as a public company CEO, I couldn’t take a lower offer. HP eventually offered $14.25 or $1.65 billion in cash. We had a deal.\",\"index\":316,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"When it finally ended—the long road from Loudcloud to Opsware—I couldn’t believe that I’d sold what it took eight years and all of my life force to build. How could I have done that? I was sick. I couldn’t sleep, I had cold sweats, I threw up, and I cried. And then I realized that it was the smartest thing that I’d ever done in my career. We’d built something from nothing, saw it go back to nothing again, and then rebuilt it into a $1.65 billion franchise.\",\"index\":317,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"At that point, it felt like my business life was kind of over. I had hired all the best people that I knew or could find, and I had gone through every step from founding to going public to sale. I definitely did not feel like doing any of that again. But I had learned so much. It seemed like such a waste to do something completely different. And then I got an idea to build a new kind of venture capital firm.\",\"index\":318,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"We will explore this idea in chapter 9, but first, chapters 4 through 8 will take you through most everything I learned to this point plus a few new war stories from my experiences running Loudcloud and Opsware.\",\"index\":319,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"As our software business surged to nearly $150 million in revenue, our stock rose sharply from $0.35 to between $6 and $8 per share, at times surpassing $800 million in market capitalization. Despite quarterly challenges and the impact of virtualization technology, shareholder pressures, such as Rachel Hyman's call to sell, intensified. An EMC interest leak boosted our stock to $9.50, drawing eleven potential buyers. Strategically leveraging Oracle, we saw bids between $10 and $11 per share but felt undervalued and advised against selling. The board, striving to balance growth and shareholder duties, questioned if any price would convince me to sell. Internal debates revealed most of the team preferred selling, except one optimist. Setting a $14 per share target, no bids came initially until BMC Software offered $13.25. Holding firm, we negotiated HP’s final offer of $14.25 per share, amounting to $1.65 billion. This concluded an intense eight-year journey, leading me to consider founding a new venture capital firm. Future chapters will detail my experiences and lessons from leading Loudcloud and Opsware.\",\"type\":\"section\"}],\"summary\":\"A few quarters into Opsware, our largest customer EDS, which accounted for 90% of our revenue, threatened to cancel their contract over technical issues, jeopardizing our company's future. With top lieutenants Jason and Anthony, we identified EDS's chaotic environment as a significant problem. Jason led the deployment while Anthony discerned EDS's unspoken needs, securing a 60-day window to resolve the issues. Anthony discovered EDS's dissatisfaction with a mandated software switch and proposed acquiring Tangram for $10 million. This acquisition, although risky, saved our relationship and proved highly profitable. We also covered medical costs for Tangram’s former CFO, demonstrating compassion. After the EDS crisis, we faced fierce competition from BladeLogic, leading to client losses, missed targets, and plummeting stock prices. I rallied the engineering team with the Darwin Project, focusing on innovation over existing customer demands, and revamped our sales process, leading to a triumphant product nine months later. Addressing \\\"What Are We Not Doing?\\\", we acquired Rendition Networks, enhancing our competitive edge. Our revenue surged to nearly $150 million, with our stock peaking at over $800 million in market cap. Interest from potential buyers, including a final $14.25 per share offer from HP, concluded our journey. This successful sale led me to ponder founding a new venture capital firm, promising future insights from my experiences with Loudcloud and Opsware.\",\"type\":\"section\"}],\"summary\":\"\\\"I move onward, the only direction / Can’t be scared to fail in search of perfection.\\\" —JAY Z, “ON TO THE NEXT ONE”\\n\\nOnce the EDS sale concluded, I felt good about Opsware’s future, but shareholders had other concerns as the stock fell to $0.35 per share. To reignite belief, I took 80 employees to Santa Cruz, laid out our dire situation, issued new stock grants, and asked for their commitment. Only four employees left before we sold to Hewlett-Packard five years later. My immediate focus was raising the stock above $1 to avoid NASDAQ delisting. With $60 million in the bank, a $20 million EDS contract, and promising IP, we shared our story, and the stock rebounded. We released a flawed Opsware product to learn and adapt, and rebuilt the executive team for our new direction. By executing our cohesive strategy, our stock rose from $0.35 to over $7, facing new challenges when EDS, our major revenue source, threatened to cancel over technical issues. Jason led deployment, and Anthony identified EDS’s unspoken needs, eventually proposing a $10 million Tangram acquisition, which saved our relationship and proved profitable. We even covered medical costs for Tangram’s former CFO. Surviving the EDS crisis, competition from BladeLogic hit us hard, but I motivated the engineering team with the Darwin Project, leading to a triumphant product and a revamped sales process. Our acquisition of Rendition Networks restored our edge, with revenues nearing $150 million and a market cap over $800 million. HP’s offer of $14.25 per share led to a successful sale and inspired me to launch a new venture capital firm.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**[— CHAPTER 4 —]()**\",\"index\":320,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"**[WHEN THINGS FALL APART]()**\",\"index\":321,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"type\":\"clump\",\"summary\":\"**[— CHAPTER 4 —]()** \\n\\n **[WHEN THINGS FALL APART]()**\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"“There are several different frameworks one could use to get a handle on the indeterminate vs. determinate question. The math version is calculus vs. statistics. In a determinate world, calculus dominates. You can calculate specific things precisely and deterministically. When you send a rocket to the moon, you have to calculate precisely where it is at all times. It’s not like some iterative startup where you launch the rocket and figure things out step by step. Do you make it to the moon? To Jupiter? Do you just get lost in space? There were lots of companies in the ’90s that had launch parties but no landing parties.\",\"index\":322,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"“But the indeterminate future is somehow one in which probability and statistics are the dominant modality for making sense of the world. Bell curves and random walks define what the future is going to look like. The standard pedagogical argument is that high schools should get rid of calculus and replace it with statistics, which is really important and actually useful. There has been a powerful shift toward the idea that statistical ways of thinking are going to drive the future.”\",\"index\":323,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"**—PETER THIEL**\",\"index\":324,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"type\":\"clump\",\"summary\":\"“There are several different frameworks one could use to get a handle on the indeterminate vs. determinate question. The math version is calculus vs. statistics. In a determinate world, calculus dominates. You can calculate specific things precisely and deterministically. When you send a rocket to the moon, you have to calculate precisely where it is at all times. It’s not like some iterative startup where you launch the rocket and figure things out step by step. Do you make it to the moon? To Jupiter? Do you just get lost in space? There were lots of companies in the ’90s that had launch parties but no landing parties. \\n\\n “But the indeterminate future is somehow one in which probability and statistics are the dominant modality for making sense of the world. Bell curves and random walks define what the future is going to look like. The standard pedagogical argument is that high schools should get rid of calculus and replace it with statistics, which is really important and actually useful. There has been a powerful shift toward the idea that statistical ways of thinking are going to drive the future.” \\n\\n **—PETER THIEL**\"},{\"content\":\"**W**hen I was attempting to sell the cloud computing services part of the Loudcloud business, I met with Bill Campbell to update him on where I was with the deal. The deal was critical, because without it, the company would almost certainly go bankrupt.\",\"index\":325,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"After I carefully briefed him on where we were with both interested parties, IBM and EDS, Bill paused for a moment. He looked me in the eyes and said, “Ben, you need to do something in addition to working on this deal. You need to do it alone with your general counsel. You need to prepare the company for bankruptcy.” To an objective observer, this might sound like Bill was prudently advising me to build my contingency plan. But something in his voice and his eyes said something different. They said that he believed the contingency plan was going to be *the* plan.\",\"index\":326,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"The conversation brought to mind a story that a friend told me about his brother, a young doctor. A thirty-five-year-old man came to see my friend’s brother. The man looked awful. His eyes were hollow and his skin was ashen. The young doctor knew something was wrong, but he could not figure out what, so he brought in an elder colleague to help with the diagnosis. The more experienced doctor examined the man and then sent him on his way. The old doctor then turned to the young doctor and said, “He’s dead.” The young doctor was flabbergasted: “What are you talking about? He just walked out of here alive!” The older doctor replied, “He doesn’t know it yet, but he’s dead. He’s had a heart attack and when people that young have heart attacks their bodies are not yet pliable enough to recover. He won’t recover. He’s dead.” Three weeks later the patient died.\",\"index\":327,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"I felt that Bill was telling me, although I was walking around trying to get the deal done, that I was already dead and that I did not know it. It was a very hard thing for him to say and only the best of friends will muster the courage to break news that horrible. It was an even harder thing for me to hear. He told me so that I could emotionally prepare myself and financially prepare the company for the inevitable funeral. The odds of landing a company-saving deal during the technology industry’s nuclear winter were close to nil. Chances were, I was dead.\",\"index\":328,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"I never built that contingency plan. Through the seemingly impossible Loudcloud series C and IPO processes, I learned one important lesson: Startup CEOs should not play the odds. When you are building a company, you must believe there is an answer and you cannot pay attention to your odds of finding it. You just have to find it. It matters not whether your chances are nine in ten or one in a thousand; your task is the same.\",\"index\":329,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"In the end, I did find the answer, we completed the deal with EDS, and the company did not go bankrupt. I was not mad at Bill. To this day, I sincerely appreciate his telling me the truth about the odds. But I don’t believe in statistics. I believe in calculus.\",\"index\":330,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\" \",\"index\":331,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"**P**eople always ask me, “What’s the secret to being a successful CEO?” Sadly, there is no secret, but if there is one skill that stands out, it’s the ability to focus and make the best move when there are no good moves. It’s the moments where you feel most like hiding or dying that you can make the biggest difference as a CEO. In the rest of this chapter, I offer some lessons on how to make it through the struggle without quitting or throwing up too much.\",\"index\":332,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"While most management books focus on how to do things correctly, so you don’t screw up, these lessons provide insight into what you must do after you have screwed up. The good news is, I have plenty of experience at that and so does every other CEO.\",\"index\":333,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"I put this section first even though it deals with some serious endgame issues such as how to fire an executive and how to lay people off. In doing so, I follow the first principle of the Bushido—the way of the warrior: keep death in mind at all times. If a warrior keeps death in mind at all times and lives as though each day might be his last, he will conduct himself properly in all his actions. Similarly, if a CEO keeps the following lessons in mind, she will maintain the proper focus when hiring, training, and building her culture.\",\"index\":334,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"\",\"index\":335,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\" \",\"index\":336,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**[THE STRUGGLE]()**\",\"index\":337,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Every entrepreneur starts her company with a clear vision for success. You will create an amazing environment and hire the smartest people to join you. Together you will build a beautiful product that delights customers and makes the world just a little bit better. It’s going to be absolutely awesome.\",\"index\":338,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Then, after working night and day to make your vision a reality, you wake up to find that things did not go as planned. Your company did not unfold like the Jack Dorsey keynote that you listened to when you started. Your product has issues that will be very hard to fix. The market isn’t quite where it was supposed to be. Your employees are losing confidence and some of them have quit. Some of the ones who quit were quite smart and have the remaining ones wondering if staying makes sense. You are running low on cash and your venture capitalist tells you that it will be difficult to raise money given the impending European economic catastrophe. You lose a competitive battle. You lose a loyal customer. You lose a great employee. The walls start closing in. Where did you go wrong? Why didn’t your company perform as envisioned? Are you good enough to do this? As your dreams turn into nightmares, you find yourself in *the Struggle*.\",\"index\":339,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**ABOUT THE STRUGGLE**\",\"index\":340,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"“Life is struggle.”\",\"index\":341,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"**—KARL MARX**\",\"index\":342,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"type\":\"clump\",\"summary\":\"“Life is struggle.” \\n\\n **—KARL MARX**\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"The Struggle is when you wonder why you started the company in the first place.\",\"index\":343,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"The Struggle is when people ask you why you don’t quit and you don’t know the answer.\",\"index\":344,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"The Struggle is when your employees think you are lying and you think they may be right.\",\"index\":345,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"The Struggle is when food loses its taste.\",\"index\":346,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"The Struggle is when you don’t believe you should be CEO of your company. The Struggle is when you know that you are in over your head and you know that you cannot be replaced. The Struggle is when everybody thinks you are an idiot, but nobody will fire you. The Struggle is where self-doubt becomes self-hatred.\",\"index\":347,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"The Struggle is when you are having a conversation with someone and you can’t hear a word that they are saying because all you can hear is the Struggle.\",\"index\":348,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"The Struggle is when you want the pain to stop. The Struggle is unhappiness.\",\"index\":349,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"The Struggle is when you go on vacation to feel better and you feel worse.\",\"index\":350,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"The Struggle is when you are surrounded by people and you are all alone. The Struggle has no mercy.\",\"index\":351,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"The Struggle is the land of broken promises and crushed dreams. The Struggle is a cold sweat. The Struggle is where your guts boil so much that you feel like you are going to spit blood.\",\"index\":352,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"The Struggle is not failure, but it causes failure. Especially if you are weak. Always if you are weak.\",\"index\":353,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"type\":\"clump\",\"summary\":\"The Struggle is when you wonder why you started the company in the first place. \\n\\n The Struggle is when people ask you why you don’t quit and you don’t know the answer. \\n\\n The Struggle is when your employees think you are lying and you think they may be right. \\n\\n The Struggle is when food loses its taste. \\n\\n The Struggle is when you don’t believe you should be CEO of your company. The Struggle is when you know that you are in over your head and you know that you cannot be replaced. The Struggle is when everybody thinks you are an idiot, but nobody will fire you. The Struggle is where self-doubt becomes self-hatred. \\n\\n The Struggle is when you are having a conversation with someone and you can’t hear a word that they are saying because all you can hear is the Struggle. \\n\\n The Struggle is when you want the pain to stop. The Struggle is unhappiness. \\n\\n The Struggle is when you go on vacation to feel better and you feel worse. \\n\\n The Struggle is when you are surrounded by people and you are all alone. The Struggle has no mercy. \\n\\n The Struggle is the land of broken promises and crushed dreams. The Struggle is a cold sweat. The Struggle is where your guts boil so much that you feel like you are going to spit blood. \\n\\n The Struggle is not failure, but it causes failure. Especially if you are weak. Always if you are weak.\"},{\"content\":\"Most people are not strong enough.\",\"index\":354,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Every great entrepreneur from Steve Jobs to Mark Zuckerberg went through the Struggle and struggle they did, so you are not alone. But that does not mean that you will make it. You may not make it. That is why it is the Struggle.\",\"index\":355,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"The Struggle is where greatness comes from.\",\"index\":356,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"\\\"Life is struggle.\\\" — **Karl Marx**\\n\\nThe Struggle is the doubt and questioning why you started your company in the first place. It's the moment when you can't explain why you don't quit. It's when your employees doubt your honesty, and you wonder if they might be right. The Struggle makes food tasteless and shatters your confidence as a CEO. It’s knowing you’re overwhelmed but irreplaceable, feeling like an idiot without being fired, and when self-doubt morphs into self-hatred. The Struggle drowns out others' voices with its relentless noise, makes you crave relief from pain, and brings profound unhappiness. It ruins vacations and leaves you isolated in a crowd. The Struggle is merciless, filled with broken promises and crushed dreams, inducing a cold sweat and churning your insides with fear. It's not failure itself but leads to it, particularly if you’re weak. Many, including Steve Jobs and Mark Zuckerberg, have faced the Struggle, so you are not alone, yet survival is uncertain. The Struggle is the crucible where greatness is forged.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**SOME STUFF THAT MAY OR MAY NOT HELP**\",\"index\":357,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"There is no answer to the Struggle, but here are some things that helped me:\",\"index\":358,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"* *Don’t put it all on your shoulders.* It is easy to think that the things that bother you will upset your people more. That’s not true. The opposite is true. Nobody takes the losses harder than the person most responsible. Nobody feels it more than you. You won’t be able to share every burden, but share every burden that you can. Get the maximum number of brains on the problems even if the problems represent existential threats. When I ran Opsware and we were losing too many competitive deals, I called an all hands and told the whole company that we were getting our asses kicked, and if we didn’t stop the bleeding, we were going to die. Nobody blinked. The team rallied, built a winning product, and saved my sorry ass.\\n\\n* *This is not checkers; this is motherfuckin’ chess.* Technology businesses tend to be extremely complex. The underlying technology moves, the competition moves, the market moves, the people move. As a result, like playing three-dimensional chess on *Star Trek*, there is always a move. You think you have no moves? How about taking your company public with $2 million in trailing revenue and 340 employees, with a plan to do $75 million in revenue the next year? I made that move. I made it in 2001, widely regarded as the worst time ever for a technology company to go public. I made it with six weeks of cash left. There is always a move.\\n\\n* *Play long enough and you might get lucky.* In the technology game, tomorrow looks nothing like today. If you survive long enough to see tomorrow, it may bring you the answer that seems so impossible today.\\n\\n* *Don’t take it personally.* The predicament that you are in is probably all your fault. You hired the people. You made the decisions. But you knew the job was dangerous when you took it. Everybody makes mistakes. Every CEO makes thousands of mistakes. Evaluating yourself and giving yourself an F doesn’t help.\\n\\n* *Remember that this is what separates the women from the girls.* If you want to be great, this is the challenge. If you don’t want to be great, then you never should have started a company.\",\"index\":359,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"There is no single answer to the Struggle, but here are some things that helped me: First, don't bear all burdens alone; share what you can with your team as nobody feels losses more than you do. When I faced challenges at Opsware, I openly discussed our issues, and the team rallied to turn things around. Second, remember that running a technology business is like playing three-dimensional chess—there's always a move, even in dire situations. I took my company public in 2001 with minimal revenue and only weeks of cash left, showing there's always a move. Third, if you survive long enough, luck might kick in and change your dire circumstances. Next, don't take failures personally; they are part of the journey, and every CEO makes mistakes. Lastly, understand that enduring these challenges distinguishes the great leaders from the rest; if you aspire to greatness, embrace the Struggle, for it defines the path to success.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**THE END**\",\"index\":360,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"When you are in the Struggle, nothing is easy and nothing feels right. You have dropped into the abyss and you may never get out. In my own experience, but for some unexpected luck and help, I would have been lost.\",\"index\":361,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"So to all of you in it, may you find strength and may you find peace.\",\"index\":362,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"\",\"index\":363,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\" \",\"index\":364,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"When you're in the Struggle, everything feels off and insurmountable—as if you've plunged into an abyss with no escape. Speaking from personal experience, if not for some unexpected luck and help, I might have been lost forever. So, to everyone enduring it, I wish you strength and peace.\",\"type\":\"section\"}],\"summary\":\"\\\"Life is struggle,\\\" said Karl Marx. The Struggle is the relentless doubt and persistent questioning of why you started your company. It's the inexplicable force that keeps you from quitting despite overwhelming challenges. It's when your own employees question your honesty, shattering your confidence as a CEO. The Struggle drains the flavor from food, leaves you feeling irreplaceable yet overwhelmed, and amplifies self-doubt to self-hatred. It drowns out others' support, makes you yearn for relief, and brings deep unhappiness. It ruins vacations, isolates you in crowds, and fills you with cold sweats and fear. Despite not being failure itself, it certainly steers you towards it, especially if you're weak. Even greats like Steve Jobs and Mark Zuckerberg have endured it, proving you’re not alone, but survival is uncertain. The Struggle forges greatness. \\n\\nHere are some strategies that helped me: Don't shoulder burdens alone—share with your team, as they too feel the losses. At Opsware, openly discussing setbacks galvanized us to overcome. Running a tech business is like three-dimensional chess—there's always a move. In 2001, I took my company public under dire conditions, proving there’s always a move. Survive long enough, and luck might turn things around. Don't take failures personally; they are part of the journey and every CEO makes mistakes. Lastly, enduring these challenges is what separates great leaders from the rest. Embrace the Struggle—it defines the path to success. \\n\\nWhen in the depths of the Struggle, everything feels insurmountable, like a dark abyss with no escape. Speaking from personal experience, I might have been lost without some luck and help. To all enduring it, I wish you strength and peace.\",\"type\":\"section\"}],\"summary\":\"Every entrepreneur starts with a clear vision of success, aiming to create an amazing environment, hire the smartest people, and build a product that delights customers and improves the world. However, reality often unfolds differently. After intense effort, you may find your product facing tough issues, your employees losing confidence, and funds running low with investors wary due to economic concerns. You lose battles, customers, and essential team members, leaving you overwhelmed. This is *the Struggle*, a term echoed by Karl Marx's \\\"Life is struggle.\\\" It’s the relentless doubt and questioning why you started your company, pushing you to the brink but keeping you from quitting. It drains joy, amplifies self-doubt, and isolates you despite support. Even leaders like Steve Jobs and Mark Zuckerberg have faced it, though survival isn't guaranteed. The Struggle, however, forges greatness. Share your burdens with your team—they feel the losses too. Embrace the endless chess game of a tech business; there’s always a move. Survive long enough for luck to intervene, and don’t take failures personally—they're part of the journey. Enduring these challenges separates great leaders from the rest, so embrace the Struggle as it defines the path to success. To those in the depths of the Struggle, I wish you strength and peace.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**[CEOS SHOULD TELL IT LIKE IT IS]()**\",\"index\":365,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"One of the most important management lessons for a founder/CEO is totally unintuitive. My single biggest personal improvement as CEO occurred on the day when I stopped being too positive.\",\"index\":366,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"As a young CEO, I felt the pressure—the pressure of employees depending on me, the pressure of not really knowing what I was doing, the pressure of being responsible for tens of millions of dollars of other people’s money. As a consequence of this pressure, I took losses extremely hard. If we failed to win a customer or slipped a date or shipped a product that wasn’t quite right, it weighed heavily on me. I thought that I would make the problem worse by transferring that burden to my employees. Instead, I thought I should project a positive, sunny demeanor and rally the unburdened troops to victory. I was completely wrong.\",\"index\":367,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"I realized my error during a conversation with my brother in-law, Cartheu. At the time, Cartheu worked for AT&T as a telephone lineman (he is one of those guys who climb the poles). I had just met a senior executive at AT&T, whom I’ll call Fred, and I was excited to find out if Cartheu knew him. Cartheu said, “Yeah, I know Fred. He comes by about once a quarter to blow a little sunshine up my ass.” At that moment, I knew that I’d been screwing up my company by being too positive.\",\"index\":368,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"In my mind, I was keeping everyone in high spirits by accentuating the positive and ignoring the negative. But my team knew that reality was more nuanced than I was describing it. And not only did they see for themselves the world wasn’t as rosy as I was describing it; they still had to listen to me blowing sunshine up their butts at every company meeting.\",\"index\":369,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"How did I make such a mistake and why was it such a big mistake?\",\"index\":370,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**THE POSITIVITY DELUSION**\",\"index\":371,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"As the highest-ranking person in the company, I thought that I would be best able to handle bad news. The opposite was true: Nobody took bad news harder than I did. Engineers easily brushed off things that kept me awake all night. After all, I was the founding CEO. I was the one “married” to the company. If things went horribly wrong, they could walk away, but I could not. As a consequence, the employees handled losses much better.\",\"index\":372,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Even more stupidly, I thought that it was my job and my job only to worry about the company’s problems. Had I been thinking more clearly, I would have realized that it didn’t make sense for me to be the only one to worry about, for example, the product not being quite right—because I wasn’t writing the code that would fix it.\",\"index\":373,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"A much better idea would have been to give the problem to the people who could not only fix it, but who would also be personally excited and motivated to do so. Another example: If we lost a big prospect, the whole organization needed to understand why, so that we could together fix the things that were broken in our products, marketing, and sales process. If I insisted on keeping the setbacks to myself, there was no way to jump-start that process.\",\"index\":374,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"As the highest-ranking person in the company, I assumed I could handle bad news best. Surprisingly, nobody took bad news harder than I did. While engineers shrugged off issues that haunted me at night, I was the founding CEO, deeply connected to the company. If things went south, they could leave, but I couldn’t. Consequently, employees managed losses better than I did. Foolishly, I also believed it was solely my responsibility to worry about the company’s problems. In hindsight, it was irrational for me to stress about, say, product issues since I wasn’t the one writing the code to fix them. A smarter approach would have been to delegate problems to those capable of solving them and who would be motivated to do so. For instance, when losing a big prospect, the entire organization needed to understand why so we could collectively address the flaws in our products, marketing, and sales processes. If I kept setbacks to myself, we couldn’t initiate that critical improvement process.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**WHY IT’S IMPERATIVE TO TELL IT LIKE IT IS**\",\"index\":375,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"There are three key reasons why being transparent about your company’s problems makes sense:\",\"index\":376,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**1. Trust.**\",\"index\":377,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Without trust, communication breaks. More specifically:\",\"index\":378,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"In any human interaction, the required amount of communication is inversely proportional to the level of trust.\",\"index\":379,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Consider the following: If I trust you completely, then I require no explanation or communication of your actions whatsoever, because I know that whatever you are doing is in my best interests. On the other hand, if I don’t trust you at all, then no amount of talking, explaining, or reasoning will have any effect on me, because I do not trust that you are telling me the truth.\",\"index\":380,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"In a company context, this is a critical point. As a company grows, communication becomes its biggest challenge. If the employees fundamentally trust the CEO, then communication will be vastly more efficient than if they don’t. Telling things as they are is a critical part of building this trust. A CEO’s ability to build this trust over time is often the difference between companies that execute well and companies that are chaotic.\",\"index\":381,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"Without trust, communication falters. In any human interaction, the need for communication is inversely proportional to the level of trust. If I trust you completely, no explanations are needed because I believe your actions are in my best interest. Conversely, without trust, no amount of communication can convince me of your intentions. In a company, this is vital: as it grows, communication becomes its biggest challenge. Employees' trust in the CEO means more efficient communication, whereas lack of trust leads to chaos. A CEO’s ability to build and maintain trust can differentiate well-executed companies from disorganized ones.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**2. The more brains working on the hard problems, the better.**\",\"index\":382,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"In order to build a great technology company, you have to hire lots of incredibly smart people. It’s a total waste to have lots of big brains but not let them work on your biggest problems. A brain, no matter how big, cannot solve a problem it doesn’t know about. As the open-source community would explain it, “Given enough eyeballs, all bugs are shallow.”\",\"index\":383,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"In order to build a great technology company, you have to hire lots of incredibly smart people. It’s a total waste to have lots of big brains but not let them work on your biggest problems. A brain, no matter how big, cannot solve a problem it doesn’t know about. As the open-source community would explain it, “Given enough eyeballs, all bugs are shallow.”\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**3. A good culture is like the old RIP routing protocol: Bad news travels fast; good news travels slow.**\",\"index\":384,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"If you investigate companies that have failed, you will find that many employees knew about the fatal issues long before those issues killed the company. If the employees knew about the deadly problems, why didn’t they say something? Too often the answer is that the company culture discouraged the spread of bad news, so the knowledge lay dormant until it was too late to act.\",\"index\":385,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"A healthy company culture encourages people to share bad news. A company that discusses its problems freely and openly can quickly solve them. A company that covers up its problems frustrates everyone involved. The resulting action item for CEOs: Build a culture that rewards—not punishes—people for getting problems into the open where they can be solved.\",\"index\":386,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"As a corollary, beware of management maxims that stop information from flowing freely in your company. For example, consider the old management standard: “Don’t bring me a problem without bringing me a solution.” What if the employee cannot solve an important problem? For example, what if an engineer identifies a serious flaw in the way the product is being marketed? Do you really want him to bury that information? Management truisms like these may be good for employees to aspire to in the abstract, but they can also be the enemy of free-flowing information—which may be critical for the health of the company.\",\"index\":387,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"Many company failures can be traced back to employees who knew about fatal issues long before they became catastrophic but felt discouraged from sharing bad news due to the company culture. This silence often leads to unresolved problems festering until it's too late. Healthy company cultures promote the sharing of bad news, allowing issues to be addressed promptly and preventing frustration among staff. CEOs should foster an environment that rewards transparency and problem-solving rather than punishing those who bring up inconvenient truths. Management maxims like \\\"Don't bring me a problem without a solution\\\" can stifle the flow of crucial information. If an engineer spots a serious marketing flaw they can't resolve, discouraging them from speaking up is detrimental. Open communication is vital for a company's health, as barriers to information flow can undermine its success.\",\"type\":\"section\"}],\"summary\":\"Without trust, communication falters, and the need for explanations grows. In any interaction, high trust means actions are believed to be in each other's best interest without the need for constant communication. Conversely, lack of trust makes communication ineffective. This is critical in companies where employee trust in the CEO ensures efficient communication, whereas mistrust leads to chaos. For a technology company to thrive, hiring smart people is essential, but their brilliance is wasted if they're unaware of the company's biggest problems. Like the open-source community says, “Given enough eyeballs, all bugs are shallow.” Failures often arise when employees, knowing about issues, feel discouraged from sharing due to the company culture. This silence allows problems to worsen. Healthy cultures promote the sharing of bad news, enabling timely resolution and preventing frustration. CEOs must foster transparency and problem-solving instead of punishing inconvenient truths. Management maxims that discourage presenting problems without solutions can suppress vital information flow. Open communication is crucial for a company's success, and barriers to it can lead to failure.\",\"type\":\"section\"}],\"summary\":\"Being transparent about your company’s problems is vital for three main reasons: Firstly, trust is essential for effective communication. When trust is high, people believe in each other's actions without needing constant clarification. Without trust, communication breaks down, making it inefficient. Secondly, in a tech company, hiring smart people is crucial, but their intelligence is wasted if they're unaware of the company's major issues. Transparency allows everyone to contribute to problem-solving, akin to the open-source principle: \\\"Given enough eyeballs, all bugs are shallow.\\\" Lastly, a healthy company culture encourages the sharing of bad news, which helps resolve issues promptly and prevents frustration. CEOs should promote transparency and problem-solving without punishing those who bring up inconvenient truths. Management practices that discourage presenting problems without solutions can stifle critical information. Open communication is the key to a company's success; barriers to it can lead to failure.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**FINAL THOUGHT**\",\"index\":388,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"If you run a company, you will experience overwhelming psychological pressure to be overly positive. Stand up to the pressure, face your fear, and tell it like it is.\",\"index\":389,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"\",\"index\":390,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\" \",\"index\":391,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"Running a company brings immense psychological pressure to maintain an overly positive outlook. Resist this pressure, confront your fears, and be honest about the situation.\",\"type\":\"section\"}],\"summary\":\"As the founding CEO, I underestimated how deeply bad news would affect me compared to my employees, who could leave if things went south. Foolishly, I believed I alone should worry about the company's issues, even though I wasn't solving them directly. A smarter approach would have been delegating problems to those equipped to address them and involving everyone in understanding setbacks to improve collectively. Transparency in a company is critical for three main reasons: it builds trust, ensuring efficient communication; it enables smart employees to address significant issues effectively, following the open-source principle that \\\"given enough eyeballs, all bugs are shallow\\\"; and it fosters a culture where sharing bad news leads to prompt resolution and less frustration. CEOs should encourage open communication and resist the pressure to maintain an overly positive outlook. Confronting fears and being honest is vital for the company’s success.\",\"type\":\"section\"}],\"summary\":\"One of the most important management lessons for a founder/CEO is incredibly unintuitive: stop being overly positive. I learned this when I felt immense pressure as a young CEO responsible for my employees and millions of dollars. My instinct was to shield my team from setbacks and maintain a sunny demeanor, but this was a mistake. A conversation with my brother-in-law, Cartheu, who worked as a lineman for AT&T, made me realize I was merely \\\"blowing sunshine.\\\" My employees could see the reality and my unwarranted optimism only created frustration. Unlike my team, who had the option to leave, I bore the company’s burdens deeply. I mistakenly thought I had to solve all problems myself, when I should have delegated and involved my team in resolving setbacks. Transparency is crucial because it builds trust, leverages collective intelligence to tackle issues efficiently, and encourages a culture where bad news is addressed quickly. CEOs should avoid the pressure to stay overly positive and instead foster open communication and honesty for the company’s success.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**[THE RIGHT WAY TO LAY PEOPLE OFF]()**\",\"index\":392,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Shortly after we sold Opsware to Hewlett-Packard, I had a conversation with the legendary venture capitalist Doug Leone of Sequoia Capital. He wanted me to recount the story of how we went from doomed in the eyes of the world to a $1.6 billion outcome with no recapitalization.\",\"index\":393,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"After I took him through the details—including several near bankruptcies, a stock price of $0.35 per share, unlimited bad press, and three separate layoffs where we lost a total of four hundred employees—he was most amazed by the layoffs. During more than twenty years in the venture capital business, he’d never seen a company recover from consecutive layoffs and achieve a billion-dollar-plus outcome. He confessed that he’d bet against that every time. Since my only experience was the great exception, I needed more information. I asked him why all the other startups failed. He replied that the layoffs inevitably broke the company’s culture. After seeing their friends laid off, employees were no longer willing to make the requisite sacrifices needed to build a company. He said that although it was possible to survive an isolated layoff, it was hugely unlikely that a company would experience great success. Building a highly valuable business, he added, after three consecutive giant layoffs accompanied by horrible prominent press coverage (we got taken apart with cover stories in both the *Wall Street Journal* and *BusinessWeek*), was a complete violation of the laws of venture capital physics. He wanted to know how we did it. After thinking about this question, here’s my answer.\",\"index\":394,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"In retrospect, we were able to keep cultural continuity and retain our best employees despite multiple massive layoffs because we laid people off the right way. This may sound nutty—how can you do something that’s fundamentally wrong in “the right way”? Here’s how.\",\"index\":395,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**STEP 1: GET YOUR HEAD RIGHT**\",\"index\":396,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"When a company fails to hit its financial plan so severely that it must fire the employees it went to great time and expense to hire, it weighs heavily on the chief executive. During the first layoff at our company, I remember being forwarded an email exchange among a group of employees. In the exchange, one of our smarter employees wrote, “Ben is either lying or stupid or both.” I remember reading that and thinking, “definitely stupid.” During a time like this, it is difficult to focus on the future, because the past overwhelms you—but that’s exactly what you must do.\",\"index\":397,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"When a company fails to hit its financial plan so severely that it must fire the employees it went to great time and expense to hire, it weighs heavily on the chief executive. During the first layoff at our company, I remember being forwarded an email exchange among a group of employees. In the exchange, one of our smarter employees wrote, “Ben is either lying or stupid or both.” I remember reading that and thinking, “definitely stupid.” During a time like this, it is difficult to focus on the future, because the past overwhelms you—but that’s exactly what you must do.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**STEP 2: DON’T DELAY**\",\"index\":398,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Once you decide that you will have to lay people off, the time elapsed between making that decision and executing that decision should be as short as possible. If word leaks (which it will inevitably if you delay), then you will be faced with an additional set of issues. Employees will question managers and ask whether a layoff is coming. If the managers don’t know, they will look stupid. If the managers do know, they will either have to lie to their employees, contribute to the leak, or remain silent, which will create additional agitation. At Loudcloud/Opsware, we badly mismanaged this dynamic with our first round of layoffs, but sharply corrected things on the next two.\",\"index\":399,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"Once you decide that you will have to lay people off, the time elapsed between making that decision and executing that decision should be as short as possible. If word leaks (which it will inevitably if you delay), then you will be faced with an additional set of issues. Employees will question managers and ask whether a layoff is coming. If the managers don’t know, they will look stupid. If the managers do know, they will either have to lie to their employees, contribute to the leak, or remain silent, which will create additional agitation. At Loudcloud/Opsware, we badly mismanaged this dynamic with our first round of layoffs, but sharply corrected things on the next two.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**STEP 3: BE CLEAR IN YOUR OWN MIND ABOUT WHY YOU ARE LAYING PEOPLE OFF**\",\"index\":400,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Going into a layoff, board members will sometimes try to make you feel better by putting a positive spin on things. They might say, “This gives us a great opportunity to deal with some performance issues and simplify the business.” That may be true, but do not let that cloud your thinking or your message to the company. You are laying people off because the company failed to hit its plan. If individual performance were the only issue, then you’d be taking a different measure. *Company* performance failed. This distinction is critical, because the message to the company and the laid-off individuals should not be “This is great, we are cleaning up performance.” The message must be “The company failed and in order to move forward, we will have to lose some excellent people.” Admitting to the failure may not seem like a big deal, but trust me, it is. “Trust me.” That’s what a CEO says every day to her employees. Trust me: This will be a good company. Trust me: This will be good for your career. Trust me: This will be good for your life. A layoff breaks that trust. In order to rebuild trust, you have to come clean.\",\"index\":401,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"Going into a layoff, board members will sometimes try to make you feel better by putting a positive spin on things. They might say, “This gives us a great opportunity to deal with some performance issues and simplify the business.” That may be true, but do not let that cloud your thinking or your message to the company. You are laying people off because the company failed to hit its plan. If individual performance were the only issue, then you’d be taking a different measure. *Company* performance failed. This distinction is critical, because the message to the company and the laid-off individuals should not be “This is great, we are cleaning up performance.” The message must be “The company failed and in order to move forward, we will have to lose some excellent people.” Admitting to the failure may not seem like a big deal, but trust me, it is. “Trust me.” That’s what a CEO says every day to her employees. Trust me: This will be a good company. Trust me: This will be good for your career. Trust me: This will be good for your life. A layoff breaks that trust. In order to rebuild trust, you have to come clean.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**STEP 4: TRAIN YOUR MANAGERS**\",\"index\":402,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"The most important step in the whole exercise is training the management team. If you send managers into this super-uncomfortable situation with no training, most of them will fail.\",\"index\":403,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Training starts with a golden rule: *Managers must lay off their own people*. They cannot pass the task to HR or to a more sadistic peer. You cannot hire an outsourcing firm like the one in the movie *Up in the Air*. Every manager must lay off his own people.\",\"index\":404,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Why so strict? Why can’t the more confrontational managers just handle this task for everyone? Because people won’t remember every day they worked for your company, but they will surely remember the day you laid them off. They will remember every last detail about that day and the details will matter greatly. The reputations of your company and your managers depend on you standing tall, facing the employees who trusted you and worked hard for you. If you hired me and I busted my ass working for you, I expect you to have the courage to lay me off yourself.\",\"index\":405,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"Once you make it clear that managers must lay off their own people, be sure to prepare them for the task:\",\"index\":406,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"**1.** They should explain briefly what happened and that it is a company rather than a personal failure.\",\"index\":407,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"**2.** They should be clear that the employee is impacted and that the decision is nonnegotiable.\",\"index\":408,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"**3.** They should be fully prepared with all of the details about the benefits and support the company plans to provide.\",\"index\":409,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"type\":\"clump\",\"summary\":\"Once you make it clear that managers must lay off their own people, be sure to prepare them for the task: \\n\\n **1.** They should explain briefly what happened and that it is a company rather than a personal failure. \\n\\n **2.** They should be clear that the employee is impacted and that the decision is nonnegotiable. \\n\\n **3.** They should be fully prepared with all of the details about the benefits and support the company plans to provide.\"}],\"summary\":\"The most important step in executing layoffs is training the management team. Without proper training, most managers will fail in this uncomfortable situation. The golden rule is simple: *Managers must lay off their own people*. They cannot delegate this task to HR, outsource it as in the movie *Up in the Air*, or pass it to a more confrontational peer. The reason for this strict rule is that employees will always remember the day they were laid off, down to every detail, which will significantly impact the reputations of your company and managers. If an employee has worked hard for you, they deserve the respect of being laid off by their own manager. To prepare managers, ensure they can clearly explain that the layoff is a company decision, not a personal failure, communicate that the decision is final, and provide comprehensive details on the benefits and support available.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**STEP 5: ADDRESS THE ENTIRE COMPANY**\",\"index\":410,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Prior to executing the layoff, the CEO must address the company. The CEO must deliver the overall message that provides the proper context and air cover for the managers. If you do your job right, the managers will have a much easier time doing their jobs. Keep in mind what former Intuit CEO Bill Campbell told me—*The message is for the people who are staying*. The people who stay will care deeply about how you treat their colleagues. Many of the people whom you lay off will have closer relationships with the people who stay than you do, so treat them with the appropriate level of respect. Still, the company must move forward, so be careful not to apologize too much.\",\"index\":411,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"Prior to executing the layoff, the CEO must address the company. The CEO must deliver the overall message that provides the proper context and air cover for the managers. If you do your job right, the managers will have a much easier time doing their jobs. Keep in mind what former Intuit CEO Bill Campbell told me—*The message is for the people who are staying*. The people who stay will care deeply about how you treat their colleagues. Many of the people whom you lay off will have closer relationships with the people who stay than you do, so treat them with the appropriate level of respect. Still, the company must move forward, so be careful not to apologize too much.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**STEP 6: BE VISIBLE, BE PRESENT**\",\"index\":412,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"After you make the speech telling your company that you will be letting many of them go, you will not feel like hanging out and talking to people. You will probably feel like going to a bar and drinking a fifth of tequila. Do not do this. Be present. Be visible. Be engaging. People want to see you. They want to see whether you care. The people whom you laid off will want to know if they still have a relationship with you and the company. Talk to people. Help them carry their things to their cars. Let them know that you appreciate their efforts.\",\"index\":413,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"\",\"index\":414,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\" \",\"index\":415,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"After delivering the tough news of layoffs, you might be tempted to escape to a bar with a fifth of tequila. Resist this urge. Instead, stay present, visible, and engaging. People need to see you care. Those being let go will want reassurance that they still matter to you and the company. Interact with them, help them with their belongings, and show genuine appreciation for their efforts.\",\"type\":\"section\"}],\"summary\":\"When a company fails to hit its financial targets and is forced to fire employees it took great time and expense to hire, it profoundly impacts the CEO. I remember an email during our first layoff where one employee harshly criticized me, making it hard to focus on the future. However, swift execution of the layoff decision is crucial to avoid leaks and confusion among employees. During our first round at Loudcloud/Opsware, we mishandled this but improved in subsequent layoffs. Board members may attempt to put a positive spin on layoffs, but it's vital to communicate that layoffs happen due to company performance failure, not individual performance issues. The message must be clear: the company failed, and losing excellent people is necessary to move forward. Rebuilding trust post-layoff requires honesty. Managers must lay off their own people and be well-trained to handle the situation with respect and clarity, explaining that the layoff is a company decision and detailing benefits and support. The CEO must address the entire company to provide context and support for managers, ensuring the message focuses on those staying. After delivering the news, remain present and visible, showing care and appreciation for those departing to maintain trust and demonstrate leadership.\",\"type\":\"section\"}],\"summary\":\"After selling Opsware to Hewlett-Packard, I discussed with Doug Leone of Sequoia Capital how we turned a seemingly doomed situation into a $1.6 billion success without recapitalization. He was particularly astonished by our recovery following multiple layoffs, a rare occurrence in his twenty years in venture capital. Most companies falter after consecutive layoffs because it breaks their culture, demotivating employees. Our success, despite three major layoffs and harsh media scrutiny, seemed a violation of venture capital norms. Upon reflection, we managed to maintain cultural continuity by handling layoffs properly. While layoffs inherently are tough, executing them swiftly and transparently, communicating that company failure—not individual performance—necessitated them, and rebuilding trust and morale are vital. Managers should personally handle layoffs, explaining decisions empathetically and ensuring employees understand the context and support available. Post-layoffs, visible and caring leadership is essential to sustaining trust and navigating through tough times.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**[PREPARING TO FIRE AN EXECUTIVE]()**\",\"index\":416,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"When you recruit an executive, you paint a beautiful picture of her future in your company. You describe in great depth and in vibrant color how awesome it will be for her to accept your offer and how much better it will be than joining that other company. Then one day you realize you must fire her. Reconcile that, Ms. CEO.\",\"index\":417,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"It turns out that the actual act of firing an executive can be relatively easy compared with any other firing. Executives have experience being on the other side of the conversation and tend to be quite professional. Firing an executive correctly is a bit more complicated and extremely important. If you do not learn the right lessons, you will be doing it again soon.\",\"index\":418,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Like so many things, the key to correctly firing an executive is preparation. Here is a four-step process that will treat the executive fairly and improve your company.\",\"index\":419,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**STEP 1: ROOT CAUSE ANALYSIS**\",\"index\":420,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"While it’s possible to fire an executive for bad behavior, incompetence, or laziness, those cases are rare and relatively easy. Unfortunately, unless you have a horribly deficient hiring process, those are probably not the reasons why you got to this point. At this level, almost every company screens for the proper skill set, motivation, and track record. Yes, the reason that you have to fire your head of marketing is not because he sucks; it’s because *you* suck.\",\"index\":421,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"In other words, the wrong way to view an executive firing is as an executive failure; the correct way to view an executive firing is as an interview/integration process system failure. Therefore, the first step to properly firing an executive is figuring out why you hired the wrong person for your company.\",\"index\":422,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"You may have blown it for a variety of reasons:\",\"index\":423,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"* *You did a poor job defining the position in the first place.* If you don’t know what you want, you will be unlikely to get it. Far too often, CEOs hire executives based on an abstract notion of what they think and feel the executive should be like. This error often leads to the executive not bringing the key, necessary qualities to the table.\\n\\n* *You hired for lack of weakness rather than for strengths.* This is especially common when you run a consensus-based hiring process. The group will often find the candidate’s weaknesses, but they won’t place a high enough value on the areas where you need the executive to be a world-class performer. As a result, you hire an executive with no sharp weaknesses, but who is mediocre where you need her to be great. If you don’t have world-class strengths where you need them, you won’t be a world-class company.\\n\\n* *You hired for scale too soon.* The most consistently wrong advice that venture capitalists and executive recruiters give CEOs is to hire someone “bigger” than required. “Think about the next three to five years and how you will be a large company” is how the bad advice usually sounds. It’s great to hire people who can run a large-scale organization if you have one. It’s also great to hire people who know how to grow an organization very fast if you are ready to grow your organization very fast. However, if you do not or you are not, then you need someone who can do the job for the next eighteen months. If you hire someone who will be great *in* eighteen months but will be poor for the next eighteen months, the company will reject her before she ever gets a chance to show her stuff. Your other employees will wonder: Why did we give her all those stock options when she’s not contributing anything? Those kinds of questions are impossible to recover from. It turns out that venture capitalists and executive recruiters are not stupid; they just learned the wrong lessons from previous failures. To learn the right lesson, see the *special case of scaling* and *the special case of fast growth* as explained below.\\n\\n* *You hired for the generic position.* There is no such thing as a great CEO, a great head of marketing, or a great head of sales. There is only a great head of sales for your company for the next twelve to twenty-four months. That position is not the same as the same position at Microsoft or Facebook. Don’t look for the candidate out of central casting. This is not a movie.\\n\\n* *The executive had the wrong kind of ambition.* In chapter 6, I will describe the difference between ambition for the company and ambition for oneself. If an executive has the wrong kind of ambition, then despite her skills, the company may reject her.\\n\\n* *You failed to integrate the executive.* Bringing a new person into your company in an important role is difficult. Other employees will be quick to judge, her expectations may be different from yours, and the job may be largely undefined. Be sure to review and improve your integration plan after you fire an executive.\",\"index\":424,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**The special case of scaling**\",\"index\":425,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"A fairly common reason for firing an executive is that when the company quadruples in size, the executive no longer does the job effectively at the new size. The reason is that when a company multiplies in size, the management jobs become brand-new jobs. As a result, everybody needs to requalify for the new job, because the new job and the old job are not the same. Running a two-hundred-person global sales organization is not the same job as running a twenty-five-person local sales team. If you get lucky, the person you hired to run the twenty-five-person team will have learned how to run the two-hundred-person team. If not, you need to hire the right person for the new job. This is neither an executive failure nor a system failure; it is life in the big city. Do not attempt to avoid this phenomenon, as you will only make things worse.\",\"index\":426,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"A fairly common reason for firing an executive is that when the company quadruples in size, the executive no longer does the job effectively at the new size. The reason is that when a company multiplies in size, the management jobs become brand-new jobs. As a result, everybody needs to requalify for the new job, because the new job and the old job are not the same. Running a two-hundred-person global sales organization is not the same job as running a twenty-five-person local sales team. If you get lucky, the person you hired to run the twenty-five-person team will have learned how to run the two-hundred-person team. If not, you need to hire the right person for the new job. This is neither an executive failure nor a system failure; it is life in the big city. Do not attempt to avoid this phenomenon, as you will only make things worse.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**The special case of fast growth**\",\"index\":427,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"If you build a great product and the market wants it, you will find yourself needing to grow your company extremely quickly. Nothing will ensure your success like hiring the right executive who has grown an organization like yours very quickly and successfully before. Note that this is not the same as inheriting a very large organization or working your way up to running a very large organization. Make sure you hire the right kind of fast-growth executive. Also, do not hire this person if you are not ready to give them lots of budget to grow their organization; expect them to do what they do. The successful fast-growth executive is so important to building successful startups that recruiters and venture capitalists often advise CEOs to bring them in before the company is ready.\",\"index\":428,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"If you build a great product and the market wants it, you will find yourself needing to grow your company extremely quickly. Nothing will ensure your success like hiring the right executive who has grown an organization like yours very quickly and successfully before. Note that this is not the same as inheriting a very large organization or working your way up to running a very large organization. Make sure you hire the right kind of fast-growth executive. Also, do not hire this person if you are not ready to give them lots of budget to grow their organization; expect them to do what they do. The successful fast-growth executive is so important to building successful startups that recruiters and venture capitalists often advise CEOs to bring them in before the company is ready.\",\"type\":\"section\"}],\"summary\":\"A common reason for firing an executive is that when a company quadruples in size, the executive may no longer manage effectively because the job evolves significantly. For example, running a twenty-five-person local sales team is vastly different from managing a two-hundred-person global sales organization. As companies grow, everyone needs to requalify for their new roles. If the initial hire doesn't adapt to the changing scope, it's necessary to find someone who can. This shift is neither an executive nor a system failure—it's a natural part of business growth. Trying to avoid this will only exacerbate the problem. When your company grows rapidly due to a great product, success hinges on hiring an executive experienced in scaling organizations quickly. This is distinct from executives who either inherited large teams or gradually ascended into their roles. Make sure to provide the fast-growth executive with ample budget and autonomy to expand the organization. Recruiters and venture capitalists often recommend hiring such executives early, even before the company feels fully prepared.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"content\":\"Once you identify the problem, then you create the basis for the next steps.\",\"index\":429,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"Firing an executive is rarely about their incompetence or laziness but rather a failure in your hiring and integration processes. Executives at this level are generally well-vetted for skills, motivation, and track records. So, if you're firing your head of marketing, the fault likely lies in a flawed hiring process. Common mistakes include poorly defining the position, hiring to avoid weaknesses rather than for strengths, hiring too soon for scale, targeting generic roles instead of company-specific needs, selecting candidates with the wrong type of ambition, and failing to properly integrate the executive. Another reason might be that as your company grows, the executive can no longer manage effectively due to the evolving scope of their role. Thus, it's crucial to review and improve your hiring and integration processes, ensuring future hires are suited for both their current role and anticipated company growth. Identifying these issues is the first step in creating a strong foundation for future success.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**STEP 2: INFORMING THE BOARD**\",\"index\":430,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Informing the board is tricky and many issues can further complicate the task:\",\"index\":431,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"* This is the fifth or sixth executive that you had to fire.\\n\\n* This is the third executive that you fired in this role.\\n\\n* The candidate was referred by a board member who recommended the executive as a superstar.\",\"index\":432,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Realize that in any of these cases the board will be at least somewhat alarmed and there is nothing that you can do about that. But keep in mind that your choices are: (a) alarm the board or (b) enable an ineffective executive to remain in her position. While choice (a) is not great, it’s a heck of a lot better than choice (b). Leaving a failing leader in place will cause an entire department in your company to slowly rot. Let that happen and the board will be more than alarmed.\",\"index\":433,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"You should have three goals with the board:\",\"index\":434,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"* *Get their support and understanding for the difficult task that you will execute.* You should start by making sure that they understand the root cause and your plan to remedy the situation. This will give them confidence in your ability to hire and manage outside executives in the future.\\n\\n* *Get their input and approval for the separation package.* This will be critical for the next step. Executive packages are larger than regular severance packages and rightly so. It takes about ten times longer for an executive to find a new job than it does for an individual contributor.\\n\\n* *Preserve the reputation of the fired executive.* The failure was very likely a team effort, and it’s best to portray it that way. You don’t make yourself look good by trashing someone who worked for you. A mature approach to this issue will help keep the board confident in your ability to be CEO. It’s also the fair and decent thing to do.\",\"index\":435,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Finally, firing an executive turns out to be a piece of news that’s handled better with individual phone calls than in dramatic fashion during a board meeting. It takes a bit longer, but it’s well worth the effort. Individual conversations will be particularly important if one of the board members introduced the executive to the company. Once everyone agrees individually, you can finalize the details in a board meeting or call.\",\"index\":436,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"Informing the board about firing an executive is challenging, especially when it’s the fifth or sixth termination and the third in the same role, compounded by the executive being recommended by a board member as a superstar. The board will likely be alarmed, but it’s crucial to choose between alarming them or retaining an ineffective executive. Leaving a failing leader in place will have dire consequences for the company. Your goals with the board should include gaining their support and understanding by clearly explaining the root cause and your remedy plan, securing their input and approval for the executive’s separation package, and preserving the fired executive’s reputation to maintain your credibility and fairness. Communicating this news via individual phone calls is more effective than addressing it dramatically during a board meeting, as it allows for detailed and personal discussions, especially when a board member had vouched for the executive. Once all members are individually informed and in agreement, you can finalize the details in a board setting.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**STEP 3: PREPARING FOR THE CONVERSATION**\",\"index\":437,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"After you know what went wrong and have informed the board, you should tell the executive as quickly as possible. In preparation for that meeting, I recommend scripting or rehearsing what you plan to say so that you do not misspeak. The executive will remember the conversation for a very long time, so you need to get it right.\",\"index\":438,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"As part of your preparation, you should review any performance reviews or written performance conversations to understand any inconsistencies in your prior communication.\",\"index\":439,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"Three keys to getting it right:\",\"index\":440,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"**1.** *Be clear on the reasons.* You have thought about this long and hard; don’t equivocate or sugarcoat it. You owe it to them to be clear about what you think happened.\",\"index\":441,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"**2.** *Use decisive language.* Do not leave the discussion open-ended. This is not a performance review; it’s a firing. Use words and phrases like “I have decided” rather than “I think.”\",\"index\":442,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"**3.** *Have the severance package approved and ready.* Once the executive hears the news, she will stop caring about the company and its issues; she will be highly focused on herself and her family. Be ready to provide specific details of the severance package.\",\"index\":443,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"type\":\"clump\",\"summary\":\"Three keys to getting it right: \\n\\n **1.** *Be clear on the reasons.* You have thought about this long and hard; don’t equivocate or sugarcoat it. You owe it to them to be clear about what you think happened. \\n\\n **2.** *Use decisive language.* Do not leave the discussion open-ended. This is not a performance review; it’s a firing. Use words and phrases like “I have decided” rather than “I think.” \\n\\n **3.** *Have the severance package approved and ready.* Once the executive hears the news, she will stop caring about the company and its issues; she will be highly focused on herself and her family. Be ready to provide specific details of the severance package.\"},{\"content\":\"Finally, the executive will be keenly interested in how the news will be communicated to the company and to the outside world. It is best to let her decide. Bill Campbell once gave me a critical bit of advice when I was preparing to fire an executive. He said, “Ben, you cannot let him keep his job, but you absolutely can let him keep his respect.”\",\"index\":444,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"After identifying what went wrong and informing the board, communicate with the executive promptly. Prepare for the meeting by scripting or rehearsing to avoid misspeaking, as the executive will remember the conversation for a long time. Review performance reviews or prior communications to identify any inconsistencies. Here are three keys to getting it right:\\n\\n**1.** *Be clear on the reasons.* Be honest and straightforward about what you believe happened.\\n**2.** *Use decisive language.* Make it clear it's a termination, not a performance review, using phrases like “I have decided” instead of “I think.”\\n**3.** *Have the severance package ready.* After hearing the news, the executive will focus on personal and family concerns, so be prepared with specific details of the severance package.\\n\\nAdditionally, the executive will be interested in how the news will be communicated internally and externally; it's best to let her decide. Remember Bill Campbell's advice: while you can't let her keep her job, you can let her keep her respect.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**STEP 4: PREPARING THE COMPANY COMMUNICATION**\",\"index\":445,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"After you have informed the executive, you must quickly update the company and your staff on the change. The correct order for informing the company is (1) the executive’s direct reports—because they will be most impacted; (2) the other members of your staff—because they will need to answer questions about it; and (3) the rest of the company. All of these communications should happen on the same day and preferably within a couple of hours. When disclosing the firing to the direct reports, make sure that you have a plan for whom they will report to in the meantime and what’s next (executive search, reorganization, internal promotion, or something else). Generally, it’s smart for the CEO to act in the executive role in the meanwhile. If you do act in the role, you must really act—staff meetings, one-on-ones, objective setting, etc. Doing so will provide excellent continuity for the team and greatly inform your thinking on whom to hire next.\",\"index\":446,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"As you did when you updated the board, keep the message positive and refrain from throwing the executive under the bus. The best employees in the organization will likely be the ones closest to the executive. If you trash her, you will put all her best employees on notice that they are next. Is that a message you want to send?\",\"index\":447,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"When you update the company, you might worry about employees misinterpreting the news and thinking the company is in trouble. Do not try to maneuver around such a reaction. When you expect your employees to act like adults, they generally do. If you treat them like children, then get ready for your company to turn into one big *Barney* episode.\",\"index\":448,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"After informing the executive, promptly update the company and staff about the change in the following order: (1) the executive’s direct reports, as they are most impacted; (2) other members of your staff, who will need to answer questions; and (3) the rest of the company. These communications should occur on the same day, ideally within a few hours. When informing direct reports, have a clear plan for interim reporting lines and next steps, like an executive search, reorganization, internal promotion, or another option. It’s wise for the CEO to temporarily take on the executive role, fully engaging in meetings, one-on-ones, and setting objectives to ensure continuity and to better understand future hiring needs. Maintain a positive message without criticizing the outgoing executive, as the top employees closest to them may feel uncertain about their own job security otherwise. Address concerns directly to prevent employees from misinterpreting the news as indicative of company trouble. Treat your employees like adults to avoid creating an environment reminiscent of a *Barney* episode.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**IN THE END**\",\"index\":449,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Every CEO likes to say she runs a great company. It’s hard to tell whether the claim is true until the company or the CEO has to do something really difficult. Firing an executive is a good test.\",\"index\":450,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"\",\"index\":451,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\" \",\"index\":452,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"Every CEO likes to claim she runs a great company, but the true test of this claim emerges when the company or the CEO faces a challenging situation. Firing an executive is an excellent measure.\",\"type\":\"section\"}],\"summary\":\"Firing an executive often highlights flaws in your hiring and integration processes rather than issues with the executive's competence or work ethic. When a head of marketing fails, it's usually due to an inadequately defined role, hiring to counter weaknesses instead of for strengths, premature scaling, targeting generic instead of company-specific needs, or ineffective integration. Additionally, as the company evolves, an executive may struggle with the expanding scope. To address these issues, review and refine your hiring and integration processes to ensure future hires align with both current and future company growth. Informing the board about a termination, especially if it's recurrent or involves a board-recommended \\\"superstar,\\\" is challenging but necessary to avoid retaining an ineffective leader. Aim to gain the board's support by clearly explaining the root cause, outlining your remedy, securing their input on the separation package, and preserving the executive’s reputation. Communicate this news individually to board members for detailed, personal discussions before formalizing it in a board meeting. When firing an executive, be clear, use decisive language, and have the severance package ready as the executive will focus on personal concerns. Allow the outgoing executive to decide how the news is communicated internally and externally to help maintain their respect. Subsequently, inform the company promptly, starting with the executive’s direct reports, followed by other staff, and then the rest of the company—all ideally within a few hours. Clearly outline interim measures and future steps to ensure continuity, avoiding criticism of the outgoing executive to prevent uncertainty among top employees. Address concerns head-on to reassure staff about job security and company stability. Handling such situations adeptly tests your claim of running a great company.\",\"type\":\"section\"}],\"summary\":\"Recruiting an executive involves painting a vibrant picture of their future at your company, making it seem far superior to joining the competition. However, when you face the reality of needing to fire them, it becomes a challenging test of your leadership. Surprisingly, the act of firing an executive is often easier than firing other employees, as executives typically handle such conversations with professionalism. Yet, doing it right is crucial and complex. Preparation is key; you need to follow a meticulous four-step process to ensure fairness to the executive and improvement for your company. Often, the failure of an executive like a head of marketing points to flaws in your hiring and integration processes rather than their competence. Clearly defining roles, hiring for strengths, avoiding premature scaling, and ensuring effective integration are critical. As the company grows, executives may also struggle with increased scope. Review these processes to align future hires with both current and future growth. Communicating a termination to the board is delicate but necessary, especially if recurrent or involving a \\\"superstar\\\" they recommended. Gain the board’s support by clearly explaining the root cause and your remedy, seeking their input on the separation package, and preserving the executive’s reputation. Have personal discussions with board members before formalizing the news in a board meeting. When firing an executive, be clear, decisive, and have the severance package ready. Allow the outgoing executive to decide how to communicate the news internally and externally. Inform the company promptly, starting with the executive’s direct reports, and outline interim measures to ensure continuity. Avoid criticizing the outgoing executive to maintain stability and reassure employees about their job security. Handling this process adeptly is a true test of your leadership and your claim of running a great company.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**[DEMOTING A LOYAL FRIEND]()**\",\"index\":453,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"When I started Loudcloud, I hired the best people I knew—people whom I respected, trusted, and liked. Like me, many of them did not have deep experience in the jobs that I gave them, but they worked night and day to learn, and they made great contributions to the company. Nevertheless, the day came when I needed to hire someone else, someone with more experience, to run the function that I had previously entrusted to my loyal friend. Damn. How do you do that?\",\"index\":454,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**SHOULD YOU DO IT AT ALL?**\",\"index\":455,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"The first question that always comes to mind is “Do I really need to do this? Who could I possibly hire who will work this hard and bleed the company colors like this?” Sadly, if you’re asking the question, you very likely already know the answer. If you need to build a worldwide sales organization, your buddy who did the first few deals is almost certainly not the best choice. As hard as it may be, you need to take a Confucian approach. You must consider first all of the other employees and second your friend. The good of the individual must be sacrificed for the good of the whole.\",\"index\":456,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"The first question that always comes to mind is “Do I really need to do this? Who could I possibly hire who will work this hard and bleed the company colors like this?” Sadly, if you’re asking the question, you very likely already know the answer. If you need to build a worldwide sales organization, your buddy who did the first few deals is almost certainly not the best choice. As hard as it may be, you need to take a Confucian approach. You must consider first all of the other employees and second your friend. The good of the individual must be sacrificed for the good of the whole.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**HOW DO YOU BREAK THE NEWS?**\",\"index\":457,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Once you make the decision, breaking the news will not be easy. It’s important to consider two deep emotions your friend will feel:\",\"index\":458,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"* **Embarrassment** Do not underestimate what a large factor this will be in his thinking. All of his friends, relatives, and colleagues know his current position. They know how hard he’s worked and how much he’s sacrificed for the company. How will he possibly explain to them that he will no longer be part of the executive team?\\n\\n* **Betrayal** Your friend will undoubtedly feel something like this: I’ve been there from the beginning, I’ve worked side by side with you. How could you do this? It’s not like you’re perfect in your job, either. How can you be so comfortable selling me out?\",\"index\":459,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Those are some powerful emotions, so get ready for an intense discussion. Ironically, the key to an emotional discussion is to take the emotion out of it. To do that, you must be very clear in your mind about what you’ve decided and what you want to do.\",\"index\":460,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"The most important thing to decide is that you really want to do this. If you walk into a demotion discussion with an open decision, you will walk out with a mess: a mess of a situation and a mess of a relationship. As part of the decision, you must get comfortable with the thought that the employee may quit the company. Given the intense emotions he will feel, there is no guarantee that he will want to stay. If you cannot afford to lose him, you cannot make this change.\",\"index\":461,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Finally, you must decide the best role for him in your company. The obvious thing is to have him continue under his new boss, but this may not be the best thing for him, his boss, or his career. Your loyal employee will continue to have lots of knowledge about your company, competition, customers, and market that his new boss lacks. On the one hand, this can be a good thing—he can help get the new boss up to speed. On the other hand, when mixed with the intense emotions of embarrassment and betrayal, you might end up with a sabotage cocktail.\",\"index\":462,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Another problem with this approach is that from a career path perspective there is no way to paint a picture of him reporting to his new boss as anything but a demotion. An alternative, if appropriate, would be to move him to another area of the company where his skills, talent, and knowledge will help. This kind of move will give him a chance to develop a new set of skills and help the company while he’s doing it. For young employees, getting experience in different areas can be highly valuable.\",\"index\":463,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Sadly, this option may not be a silver bullet. He might not want to work in another job; he might be hell-bent on keeping his current job, so prepare for that as well.\",\"index\":464,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Once you’ve decided to hire someone above your friend and decided on the alternatives that you’d like to offer him, you can have the conversation. Keep in mind that you cannot let him keep his old job, but you can be fair and you can be honest. Some keys to doing that:\",\"index\":465,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"* *Use appropriate language.* Make clear with your language that you’ve decided. As previously discussed, use phrases like “I have decided” rather than “I think” or “I’d like.” By doing this, you will avoid putting the employee in the awkward position of wondering whether he should lobby for his old job. You can’t tell him what he wants to hear, but you can be honest.\\n\\n* *Admit reality.* If you are a founder-CEO like I was, it probably won’t be lost on the employee that you are just as underskilled for your job as he is for his. Don’t dodge this fact. In fact, admit that if you were a more experienced CEO, you might be able to develop him into the role, but two people who don’t know what they are doing is a recipe for failure.\\n\\n* *Acknowledge the contributions.* If you want him to stay in the company, you should say that and make it crystal clear that you want to help him develop his career and contribute to the company. Let him know that you appreciate what he’s done and that your decision results from a forward-looking examination of what the company needs, not a review of his past performance. The best way to do this, if appropriate, is to couple the demotion with an *increase* in compensation. Doing so will let him know that he’s both appreciated and valued going forward.\",\"index\":466,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Through all of this, keep in mind that it is what it is and nothing you can say will change that or stop it from being deeply upsetting. Your goal should not be to take the sting out of it, but to be honest, clear, and effective. Your friend may not appreciate that in the moment, but he will appreciate it over time.\",\"index\":467,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"\",\"index\":468,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\" \",\"index\":469,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"Breaking the news of a demotion to a friend is challenging, often stirring feelings of embarrassment and betrayal, especially given the investment and loyalty your friend has shown to the company. Understand that your friend will struggle with explaining this to his social circle. Approach the situation with clarity and resolve, knowing precisely what needs to be done to avoid a damaged relationship and a messy outcome. Consider the possibility that he may decide to leave the company, and if his departure would be too detrimental, re-evaluate the decision. Deciding where he fits best post-demotion is crucial; merely reporting to a new boss could lead to resentment and potential sabotage. Instead, transferring him to a different department where his skills and knowledge can still benefit the company might be a more suitable solution, offering him valuable new experiences. However, he might be determined to keep his current job, so be prepared for that as well. Once you've decided to hire someone above your friend, use clear and decisive language like \\\"I have decided\\\" to avoid misunderstandings. Address the reality that both of you might lack certain experience and that bringing in skilled personnel is necessary for the company's progress. Make it clear that your decision is forward-looking and not a critique of his past performance. Express your appreciation for his contributions, intent to help him grow within the company, and consider offering increased compensation to reinforce his value. While the conversation will be difficult and likely upsetting, aim to be honest, clear, and effective, which he may come to appreciate over time.\",\"type\":\"section\"}],\"summary\":\"When deciding whether to demote a friend, the hard truth often points to the necessity of doing so for the company's greater good. If you're building a worldwide sales organization, your initial go-to person might not be the best fit anymore. Prioritize all employees' welfare over one individual's. Breaking this news to a friend is tough and can feel like betrayal, given their loyalty and investment. Understand the social challenges your friend will face and approach the situation with clarity to prevent misunderstandings and resentment. Avoid just reporting them to a new boss; instead, transfer them to a department where their skills can be valuable. Be prepared for resistance and express your decision with clear language like \\\"I have decided.\\\" Emphasize the need for skilled personnel for the company's growth without undermining past contributions. Show appreciation, offer support for growth within the company, and perhaps increase compensation to underline their value. Though the conversation will be difficult, aim for honesty, clarity, and effectiveness, which may eventually be appreciated.\",\"type\":\"section\"}],\"summary\":\"When I started Loudcloud, I hired the best people I knew—those I respected, trusted, and liked. Many lacked deep experience in their roles but worked tirelessly to learn and made significant contributions. Eventually, the time came when I had to hire someone more experienced to take over a function from a loyal friend. This is tough but often necessary for the company's greater good. Prioritize the welfare of all employees over one individual. Breaking the news to a loyal friend feels like betrayal due to their loyalty and investment. Understand the social challenges they'll face and approach the situation with clarity to avoid resentment. Instead of reporting them to a new boss, transfer them where their skills are valuable. Be ready for resistance and use clear language like \\\"I have decided.” Emphasize the need for skilled personnel for growth without diminishing their past contributions. Show appreciation, offer support for their growth within the company, and perhaps increase compensation to underline their value. Although the conversation will be difficult, aim for honesty and clarity, which might eventually be appreciated.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**[LIES THAT LOSERS TELL]()**\",\"index\":470,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"When a company starts to lose its major battles, the truth often becomes the first casualty. CEOs and employees work tirelessly to develop creative narratives that help them avoid dealing with the obvious facts. Despite their intense creativity, many companies often end up with the same false explanations.\",\"index\":471,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**SOME FAMILIAR LIES**\",\"index\":472,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"“She left, but we were going to fire her, or give her a bad performance review.” High-tech companies tend to track employee attrition in three categories:\",\"index\":473,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"**1.** People who quit\",\"index\":474,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"**2.** People who got fired\",\"index\":475,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"**3.** People who quit, but it’s okay because the company didn’t want them anyway\",\"index\":476,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"type\":\"clump\",\"summary\":\"“She left, but we were going to fire her, or give her a bad performance review.” High-tech companies tend to track employee attrition in three categories: \\n\\n **1.** People who quit \\n\\n **2.** People who got fired \\n\\n **3.** People who quit, but it’s okay because the company didn’t want them anyway\"},{\"content\":\"Fascinatingly, as companies begin to struggle, the third category always seems to grow much faster than the first. In addition, the sudden wave of “semi-performance-related attrition” usually happens in companies that claim to have a “super-high talent bar.” How do all these superstar employees suddenly go from great to crap? How is it possible that when you lose a top-rated employee before you can say “unwanted attrition,” the manager carefully explains how her performance fell off?\",\"index\":477,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"“We would have won, but the other guys gave the deal away.” “The customer selected us technically and thinks we are the better company, but our competitor just gave the product away. We would never sell so cheaply as it would hurt our reputation.” Anybody who has ever run an enterprise sales force has heard this lie before. You go into an account, you fight hard, and you lose. The sales rep, not wanting to shine the light on himself, blames the “used car dealer” rep from the other company. The CEO, not wanting to believe that she’s losing product competitiveness, believes the rep. If you hear this lie, try to validate the claim with the actual customer. I’ll bet you can’t.\",\"index\":478,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"“Just because we missed the intermediate milestones doesn’t mean we won’t hit our product schedule.” In engineering meetings where there is great pressure to ship on time—a customer commitment, a quarter that depends on it, or a competitive imperative—everybody hopes for good news. When the facts don’t align with the good news, a clever manager will find the narrative to make everybody feel better—until the next meeting.\",\"index\":479,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"“We have a very high churn rate, but as soon as we turn on email marketing to our user base, people will come back.” Yes, of course. The reason that people leave our service and don’t come back is that we have not been sending them enough spam. That makes total sense to me, too.\",\"index\":480,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Where do lies come from?\",\"index\":481,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"To answer that question, I thought back to a conversation I had years ago with the incomparable Andy Grove.\",\"index\":482,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Back at the tail end of the Great Internet Bubble in 2001, as all the big technology companies began missing their quarters by giant amounts, I found myself wondering how none of them saw it coming. One would think that after the dot-com crash of April 2000, companies like Cisco, Siebel, and HP would realize that they would soon face a slowdown as many of their customers hit the wall. But despite perhaps the most massive and public early warning system ever, each CEO reiterated strong guidance right up to the point where they dramatically whiffed their quarters.\",\"index\":483,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"I asked Andy why these great CEOs would lie about their impending fate.\",\"index\":484,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"He said they were not lying to investors, but rather, they were lying to themselves.\",\"index\":485,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Andy explained that humans, particularly those who build things, only listen to leading indicators of good news. For example, if a CEO hears that engagement for her application increased an incremental 25 percent beyond the normal growth rate one month, she will be off to the races hiring more engineers to keep up with the impending tidal wave of demand. On the other hand, if engagement decreases 25 percent, she will be equally intense and urgent in explaining it away: “The site was slow that month, there were four holidays, and we made a UI change that caused all the problems. For gosh sakes, let’s not panic!”\",\"index\":486,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Both leading indicators may have been wrong, or both may have been right, but our hypothetical CEO—like almost every other CEO—only took action on the positive indicator and only looked for alternative explanations on the negative leading indicator.\",\"index\":487,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"If this advice sounds too familiar. and you find yourself wondering why your honest employees are lying to you, the answer is they are not. They are lying to themselves.\",\"index\":488,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"And if you believe them, you are lying to yourself.\",\"index\":489,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"\",\"index\":490,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\" \",\"index\":491,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"High-tech companies track employee attrition in three categories: those who quit, those who were fired, and those who quit but weren't indispensable. The third category grows when companies struggle, especially those with high talent standards, as they rationalize \\\"superstar\\\" departures. In sales, deflecting blame with excuses like competitors undercutting prices is common, and CEOs might avoid addressing product competitiveness. Engineering managers spin optimistic narratives despite setbacks, while the efficacy of email marketing is often overstated. These rationalizations stem from a reluctance to face harsh truths. During the Great Internet Bubble burst in 2001, CEOs of major tech companies like Cisco and HP ignored clear warning signs and maintained overly optimistic outlooks. Andy Grove explained to me that these CEOs didn't lie to investors but to themselves, as they prioritized positive indicators and rationalized negative ones. This tendency leads to self-deception, where employees and leaders alike ignore reality, risking further disconnection from the truth.\",\"type\":\"section\"}],\"summary\":\"When a company starts losing major battles, the truth often becomes the first casualty as CEOs and employees create narratives to avoid confronting obvious facts. High-tech firms categorize employee attrition into those who quit, those who were fired, and those who quit but weren't indispensable—the last category growing notably when companies struggle. In sales, blame is commonly deflected onto competitors; CEOs may dodge addressing product competitiveness, and engineering managers often promote optimistic spins despite setbacks. These rationalizations, highlighted during events like the burst of the Great Internet Bubble in 2001 with tech giants like Cisco and HP, stem from a reluctance to face harsh truths. As Andy Grove pointed out, such CEOs lie to themselves first by prioritizing positive signs and rationalizing negatives, leading to a disconnection from reality and further risks.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**[LEAD BULLETS]()**\",\"index\":492,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Early in my tenure at Netscape, when we realized that Microsoft’s new Web server had every feature that ours had, but was also five times faster and was to be given away for free, I immediately went to work trying to pivot our server product line to something that we could sell for money. The late, great Mike Homer and I worked furiously on a set of partnerships and acquisitions that would broaden the product line and surround the Web server with enough functionality that we would be able to survive the attack.\",\"index\":493,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"I excitedly reviewed the plan with my engineering counterpart, Bill Turpin, who looked at me as though I were a little kid who had much to learn. Bill was a longtime veteran of battling Microsoft from his time at Borland and understood what I was trying to do, but he was not persuaded. He said, “Ben, those silver bullets that you and Mike are looking for are fine and good, but our Web server is five times slower. There is no silver bullet that’s going to fix that. No, we are going to have to use a lot of lead bullets.” Oh snap.\",\"index\":494,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"As a result of Bill’s advice, we focused our engineering team on fixing the performance issues while working on the other things in the background. We eventually beat Microsoft’s performance and grew the server line to become a $400 million business, and we would never have done it without those lead bullets.\",\"index\":495,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"I carried that lesson with me for many years. Six years later, when I was CEO of Opsware, our toughest competitor, BladeLogic, started to consistently beat us in large deals. We were a public company, and the losses were all too visible. To make matters worse, we needed to win those deals in order to beat Wall Street’s projections, so the company felt tremendous pressure. Many of our smartest people came to me with ideas for avoiding the battle:\",\"index\":496,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"* “Let’s build a lightweight version of the product and go down-market.”\\n\\n* “Let’s acquire a company with a simpler architecture.”\\n\\n* “Let’s focus on service providers.”\",\"index\":497,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"All these approaches reinforced to me was that we weren’t facing a market problem. The customers were buying; they just weren’t buying *our* product. This was not a time to pivot. So I said the same thing to every one of them: “There are no silver bullets for this, only lead bullets.” They did not want to hear that, but it made things clear: We had to build a better product. There was no other way out. No window, no hole, no escape hatch, no back door. We had to go through the front door and deal with the big, ugly guy blocking it. Lead bullets.\",\"index\":498,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"After nine months of hard work on an extremely rugged product cycle, we regained our product lead and eventually built a company that was worth $1.6 billion. Without the lead bullets, I suspect we would have ended at about one-tenth that value.\",\"index\":499,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"There may be nothing scarier in business than facing an existential threat. So scary that many in the organization will do anything to avoid facing it. They will look for any alternative, any way out, any excuse not to live or die in a single battle. I see this often in startup pitches. The conversations go something like this:\",\"index\":500,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"Entrepreneur: “We have the best product in the market by far. All the customers love it and prefer it to competitor X.”\",\"index\":501,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Me: “Why does competitor X have five times your revenue?”\",\"index\":502,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Entrepreneur: “We are using partners and OEMs, because we can’t build a direct channel like competitor X.”\",\"index\":503,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Me: “Why not? If you have the better product, why not knuckle up and go to war?”\",\"index\":504,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Entrepreneur: “Ummm.”\",\"index\":505,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Me: “Stop looking for the silver bullet.”\",\"index\":506,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"type\":\"clump\",\"summary\":\"Entrepreneur: “We have the best product in the market by far. All the customers love it and prefer it to competitor X.” \\n\\n Me: “Why does competitor X have five times your revenue?” \\n\\n Entrepreneur: “We are using partners and OEMs, because we can’t build a direct channel like competitor X.” \\n\\n Me: “Why not? If you have the better product, why not knuckle up and go to war?” \\n\\n Entrepreneur: “Ummm.” \\n\\n Me: “Stop looking for the silver bullet.”\"},{\"content\":\"There comes a time in every company’s life where it must fight for its life. If you find yourself running when you should be fighting, you need to ask yourself, “If our company isn’t good enough to win, then do we need to exist at all?”\",\"index\":507,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"\",\"index\":508,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\" \",\"index\":509,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"Early during my time at Netscape, we found that Microsoft's new Web server outperformed ours significantly and was free. In response, Mike Homer and I intensely strategized ways to enhance our product line through partnerships and acquisitions. When I shared our plan with Bill Turpin, my engineering counterpart, he bluntly pointed out that our server's poor performance needed core fixes, not quick solutions. Following his advice, we focused on resolving the performance issues, ultimately surpassing Microsoft's product and turning our server line into a $400 million business. Years later, as CEO of Opsware, we faced a similar challenge against BladeLogic. Despite various suggestions to avoid direct competition, I insisted that the only solution was to improve our product. After nine months of intense effort, we regained our lead and built a company worth $1.6 billion. This taught me that in business, facing existential threats often requires direct confrontation and hard work, not easy solutions or pivots.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**[NOBODY CARES]()**\",\"index\":510,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"“Just win, baby.”\",\"index\":511,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"**—AL DAVIS**\",\"index\":512,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"type\":\"clump\",\"summary\":\"“Just win, baby.” \\n\\n **—AL DAVIS**\"},{\"content\":\"Back in those bad old days at Loudcloud, I often thought to myself: How could I have possibly prepared for this? How could I know that half our customers would go out of business? How could I know that it would become impossible to raise money in the private markets? How could I have figured out that there would be 221 IPOs in 2000 and 19 in 2001? Could anybody expect me to achieve a reasonable outcome given those circumstances?\",\"index\":513,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"As I was feeling sorry for myself, I randomly watched an interview with famous football coach Bill Parcells. He was telling the story of how he had a similar dilemma when he began his head coaching career. In his very first season, Parcells’s team, the New York Giants, was hit with a rash of injuries. He worried incessantly about the impact of the injuries on his team’s fortunes, as it is difficult enough to win with your best players, let alone a bunch of substitutes. When his friend and mentor, Raiders owner Al Davis, called Parcells to check in, Parcells relayed his injury issues.\",\"index\":514,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"Parcells: “Al, I am just not sure how we can win without so many of our best players. What should I do?”\",\"index\":515,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Davis: “Bill, nobody cares, just coach your team.”\",\"index\":516,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"type\":\"clump\",\"summary\":\"Parcells: “Al, I am just not sure how we can win without so many of our best players. What should I do?” \\n\\n Davis: “Bill, nobody cares, just coach your team.”\"},{\"content\":\"That might be the best CEO advice ever. Because, you see, nobody cares. When things go wrong in your company, nobody cares. The media don’t care, your investors don’t care, your board doesn’t care, your employees don’t care, and even your mama doesn’t care.\",\"index\":517,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Nobody cares.\",\"index\":518,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"And they are right not to care. A great reason for failing won’t preserve one dollar for your investors, won’t save one employee’s job, or get you one new customer. It especially won’t make you feel one bit better when you shut down your company and declare bankruptcy.\",\"index\":519,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"All the mental energy you use to elaborate your misery would be far better used trying to find the one seemingly impossible way out of your current mess. Spend zero time on what you could have done, and devote all of your time on what you might do. Because in the end, nobody cares; just run your company.\",\"index\":520,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"\",\"index\":521,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"\\\"Just win, baby.\\\" —AL DAVIS\\n\\nDuring the turbulent times at Loudcloud, I often questioned how I could have prepared for unforeseen crises: customer failures, the drying up of private market funding, and the drastic drop in IPOs from 221 in 2000 to just 19 in 2001. Was success even reasonable in such conditions? In my despair, I stumbled upon an interview with Bill Parcells, who, during his challenging first season as a head coach for the New York Giants, sought advice from Al Davis. Davis bluntly told him: \\\"Bill, nobody cares, just coach your team.\\\" This is arguably the best CEO advice ever. When things go wrong, nobody cares—the media, investors, board, employees, and even your closest supporters. Valid excuses don’t recover investor losses, save jobs, attract customers, or ease the pain of shutting down your company. Instead of wallowing in self-pity, use your mental energy to find that one seemingly impossible way out of your mess. Stop wasting time on what you could have done and focus entirely on what you might do. In the end, nobody cares; just run your company.\",\"type\":\"section\"}],\"summary\":\"Every entrepreneur starts with a vision to build an incredible environment, hire brilliant minds, and create a revolutionary product. Yet, reality soon introduces *the Struggle*—a phase marked by self-doubt, financial challenges, and setbacks that sap joy and isolate you despite available support. This ordeal, endured by legends like Steve Jobs and Mark Zuckerberg, shapes greatness. Sharing burdens with your team, fostering transparency, and leveraging collective intelligence can efficiently tackle issues. As a young CEO, I learned that isolating employees from setbacks only breeds frustration. Transparency builds trust and a culture that addresses bad news swiftly. Handling layoffs requires quick, clear communication and visible leadership to sustain trust. Recruiting and firing executives tests leadership skills, demanding decisiveness and empathy, focusing on process improvement rather than criticism. Addressing failures directly rather than deflecting blame is vital, as shown by my experiences at Netscape and Opsware. Embracing *the Struggle*, facing reality, involving your team in problem-solving is key to navigating the entrepreneurial journey. For those in the depths, I wish you strength and peace. \\n\\n\\\"Just win, baby.\\\" —AL DAVIS\\n\\nDuring Loudcloud's turbulent times, questioning my preparedness for unforeseen crises seemed futile—success appeared impossible amid falling IPOs and dried-up funding. An interview with Bill Parcells, who sought Al Davis's advice during his challenging first season, revealed the best CEO counsel: \\\"Bill, nobody cares, just coach your team.\\\" Valid excuses don’t recover investor losses, save jobs, attract customers, or prevent company shutdowns. Instead of dwelling on past actions, focus on finding that one improbable solution. In the end, nobody cares; just run your company.\",\"type\":\"section\"}],\"summary\":\"Navigating the balance between determinate and indeterminate perspectives, calculus and statistics provide useful tools for understanding our world—whether in the precision of rocket science or the probabilities of an uncertain future. This shift has moved educational priorities from calculus to statistics as practical tools for the future. Selling Loudcloud’s cloud computing services vividly illustrated this indeterminate framework when Bill Campbell advised me to prepare for bankruptcy, not as a precaution, but as an impending certainty, akin to a doctor diagnosing a latent ailment. This harsh climate underscored the near-zero odds of survival. However, despite never building a contingency plan and facing daunting Series C and IPO processes, I understood that startup CEOs must believe in solutions beyond statistical odds. I secured a life-saving deal with EDS, avoiding bankruptcy, embracing Bill’s advice yet trusting in calculus over statistics. A successful CEO must focus on making the best decisions in tough times, be transparent with their team, and use collective intelligence during crises. Handling layoffs demands clear, swift communication while recruiting and firing executives requires decisiveness and empathy. Facing failures directly with team involvement shapes success, embodying *the Struggle*. For those facing entrepreneurial challenges, remember Al Davis’s words: “Just win, baby.” Instead of worrying about preparedness, focus on finding unlikely solutions. Run your company with determination; past excuses don't save the future.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**[— CHAPTER 5 —]()**\",\"index\":522,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":