l that counts. I was at war and I needed a wartime general. I needed Mark Cranney.\",\"index\":565,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"As a final step in making the hire, I needed to explain it to Marc Andreessen. As cofounder and chairman of the board, Marc’s opinion mattered deeply to the board and Marc was still uncomfortable with Cranney. Marc trusted me enough that he would let me make the hire whether he liked the candidate or not, but it was important to me that Marc be fully on board.\",\"index\":566,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"I let Marc open the conversation, because despite consistently being the smartest person in the room and possibly the world, Marc is so humble that he never believes that other people think he is smart, which makes him sensitive to being ignored. He opened the conversation by listing his issues with Cranney: doesn’t look or sound like a head of sales, went to a weak school, makes him uncomfortable. I listened very carefully and replied, “I agree with every single one of those issues. However, Mark Cranney is a sales savant. He has mastered sales to a level that far exceeds anybody that I have ever known. If he didn’t have the things wrong with him that you enumerated, he wouldn’t be willing to join a company that just traded at thirty-five cents per share; he’d be CEO of IBM.”\",\"index\":567,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Marc’s reply came quickly: “Got it. Let’s hire him!”\",\"index\":568,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"And that’s how I took the key step in building a world-class software team out of the Loudcloud rubble. As I got to know Mark over the years, everything that I learned in the interview and the reference check proved out. He wasn’t an easy cultural fit, but he was a genius. I needed his genius and worked with him on the fit. I don’t know that every member of the team ever became totally comfortable with Mark, but in the end they all agreed that he was the best person possible for the job.\",\"index\":569,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\" \",\"index\":570,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"**M**y old boss Jim Barksdale was fond of saying, “We take care of the people, the products, and the profits—in that order.” It’s a simple saying, but it’s deep. “Taking care of the people” is the most difficult of the three by far and if you don’t do it, the other two won’t matter. Taking care of the people means that your company is a good place to work. Most workplaces are far from good. As organizations grow large, important work can go unnoticed, the hardest workers can get passed over by the best politicians, and bureaucratic processes can choke out the creativity and remove all the joy.\",\"index\":571,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"When everything went wrong from the dot-com crash to NASDAQ threatening to delist the company, the thing that saved us were the techniques developed in this chapter. If your company is a good place to work, you too may live long enough to find your glory.\",\"index\":572,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"\",\"index\":573,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\" \",\"index\":574,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**[A GOOD PLACE TO WORK]()**\",\"index\":575,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"At Opsware I used to teach a management expectations course because I deeply believed in training. I made it clear that I expected every manager to meet with her people on a regular basis. I even gave instructions on how to conduct a one-on-one meeting so there could be no excuses.\",\"index\":576,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Then one day, while I happily went about my job, it came to my attention that one of my managers hadn’t had a one-on-one meeting with any of his employees in more than six months. While I knew to “expect what I inspect,” I did not expect this. No one-on-one in more than six months? How was it possible for me to invest so much time thinking about management, preparing materials, and personally training my managers and then get no one-on-ones for six months? Wow, so much for CEO authority. If that’s how the managers listen to me, then why do I even bother coming to work?\",\"index\":577,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"I thought that leading by example would be the sure way to get the company to do what I wanted. Lord knows the company picked up all of my bad habits, so why didn’t they pick up my good habits? Had I lost the team? I recalled a conversation I’d had with my father many years ago regarding Tommy Heinsohn, the Boston Celtics basketball coach at the time. Heinsohn had been one of the most successful coaches in the world, including being named coach of the year and winning two NBA championships.\",\"index\":578,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"However, he had gone downhill fast and now had the worst record in the league. I asked my father what happened. He said, “The players stopped paying attention to his temper tantrums. Heinsohn used to yell at the team and they’d respond. Now they just ignore him.” Was the team now ignoring me? Had I yelled at them one time too many?\",\"index\":579,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"The more I thought about it, the more I realized that while I had told the team “what” to do, I had not been clear about “why” I wanted them to do it. Clearly, my authority alone was not enough to get them to do what I wanted. Given the large number of things that we were trying to accomplish, managers couldn’t get to everything and came up with their own priorities. Apparently, this manager didn’t think that meeting with his people was all that important and I hadn’t explained to him why it was so important.\",\"index\":580,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"So why did I force every manager through management training? Why did I demand that managers have one-on-ones with employees? After much deliberation with myself, I settled on an articulation of the core reason and I called up the offending manager’s boss—I’ll call him Steve—and told him that I needed to see him right away.\",\"index\":581,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"When Steve came into my office I asked him a question: “Steve, do you know why I came to work today?”\",\"index\":582,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Steve: “What do you mean, Ben?”\",\"index\":583,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Me: “Why did I bother waking up? Why did I bother coming in? If it was about the money, couldn’t I sell the company tomorrow and have more money than I ever wanted? I don’t want to be famous, in fact just the opposite.”\",\"index\":584,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Steve: “I guess.”\",\"index\":585,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Me: “Well, then why did I come to work?”\",\"index\":586,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Steve: “I don’t know.”\",\"index\":587,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Me: “Well, let me explain. I came to work because it’s personally very important to me that Opsware be a good company. It’s important to me that the people who spend twelve to sixteen hours a day here, which is most of their waking life, have a good life. It’s why I come to work.”\",\"index\":588,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Steve: “Okay.”\",\"index\":589,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Me: “Do you know the difference between a good place to work and a bad place to work?”\",\"index\":590,\"type\":\"mark