ense venture capital but lost nearly all of it before being sold to AT&T in 1994 for almost nothing. Despite this apparent failure, the employees of GO, including notable figures like Mike Homer, Danny Shader, Frank Chen, and Stratton Sclavos, considered their time there as one of their greatest work experiences. They valued this time highly even though their careers didn't advance, they earned no money, and the company was deemed a failure. This highlighted Bill’s exceptional capability as a CEO, something John Doerr recognized when he recommended Bill to lead Intuit. Bill’s legacy was about building good companies, and if you do nothing else, strive to be like Bill—build a good company.\",\"type\":\"section\"}],\"summary\":\"You might argue that no matter how well-managed a company is, it could fail without product/market fit, while poorly managed companies with great product/market fit still thrive. And you'd be right. So, was my dramatic speech and threat to one of my executives necessary? I believe it was, for three reasons: being a good company may not matter when things are good, but it's crucial when things go wrong, and things always go wrong; being a good company is an end in itself. Employee retention through tough times hinges on genuine job satisfaction rather than superficial perks. No company has ever had a monotonously increasing stock price; when bad companies falter, employees leave, sparking a difficult-to-reverse downward spiral. Bill Campbell exemplified the importance of building good companies through his time at GO Corporation. Despite its failure, former employees cherished their experience, underscoring Bill’s ability to foster a positive work environment. If you do nothing else, strive to build a good company like Bill did.\",\"type\":\"section\"}],\"summary\":\"At Opsware, I prioritized training and mandated regular one-on-one meetings between managers and their teams, providing detailed guidelines to ensure compliance. However, I discovered that one manager had not conducted any such meetings for over six months, which left me questioning my effectiveness as a CEO. I realized my failure lay in not clearly communicating the importance of these meetings and relying instead on authority. Determined to fix this, I discussed the issue with Steve, the manager's boss, emphasizing that my motivation wasn't money or fame but creating a company where people enjoyed their work life. I explained that good organizations enable employees to focus on their work with clarity and confidence, while poor ones suffer from bureaucracy and confusion. Highlighting that Tim hadn't met with his team in half a year, I issued a 24-hour ultimatum for Steve and Tim to correct this or face termination. This tough stance underscored that a well-managed company can endure hardships and retain its workforce, unlike poorly managed ones that fall apart under pressure. Bill Campbell’s experience at GO Corporation highlighted that fostering a positive work environment is crucial for sustaining a company, so always strive to build that kind of company.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**[WHY STARTUPS SHOULD TRAIN THEIR PEOPLE]()**\",\"index\":620,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"I learned about why startups should train their people when I worked at Netscape. People at McDonald’s get trained for their positions, but people with far more complicated jobs don’t. It makes no sense. Would you want to stand on the line of the untrained person at McDonald’s? Would you want to use the software written by the engineer who was never told how the rest of the code worked? A lot of companies think their employees are so smart that they require no training. That’s silly.\",\"index\":621,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"When I first became a manager, I had mixed feelings about training. Logically, training for high-tech companies made sense, but my personal experience with training programs at the companies where I had worked was underwhelming. The courses were taught by outside firms who didn’t really understand our business and were teaching things that weren’t relevant. Then I read chapter 16 of Andy Grove’s management classic, *High Output Management*, titled “Why Training Is the Boss’s Job,” and it changed my career. Grove wrote, “Most managers seem to feel that training employees is a job that should be left to others. I, on the other hand, strongly believe that the manager should do it himself.”\",\"index\":622,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"When I was director of product management at Netscape, I was feeling frustrated by how little value most product managers added to the business. Based on Andy’s guidance, I wrote a short document called “Good Product Manager/Bad Product Manager,” which I used to train the team on my basic expectations. (That document follows on page 111.) I was shocked by what happened next. The performance of my team instantly improved. Product managers whom I had almost written off as hopeless became effective. Pretty soon I was managing the highest-performing team in the company. Based on this experience, after starting Loudcloud, I heavily invested in training. I credit that investment with much of our eventual success. And the whole thing started with a simple decision to train my people and an even simpler training document. So, I will now pay forward my debt to Andy Grove and explain why, what, and how you should do the same in your company.\",\"index\":623,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**WHY YOU SHOULD TRAIN YOUR PEOPLE**\",\"index\":624,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Almost everyone who builds a technology company knows that people are the most important asset. Properly run startups place a great deal of emphasis on recruiting and the interview process in order to build their talent base. Too often the investment in people stops there. There are four core reasons why it shouldn’t:\",\"index\":625,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**1. Productivity**\",\"index\":626,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"I often see startups keep careful statistics of how many candidates they’ve screened, how many have made it to the full interview process, and how many people they’ve hired. All of these statistics are interesting, but the most important statistic is missing: How many fully productive employees have they added? By failing to measure progress toward the actual goal, they lose sight of the value of training. If they measured productivity, they might be horrified to find that all those investments in recruiting, hiring, and integration were going to waste. Even if they were made aware of low productivity among new employees, most CEOs think that they don’t have time to invest in training. Andy Grove does the math and shows that the opposite is true:\",\"index\":627,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"*Training is, quite simply, one of the highest-leverage activities a manager can perform. Consider for a moment the possibility of your putting on a series of four lectures for members of your department. Let’s count on three hours preparation for each hour of course time—twelve hours of work in total. Say that you have ten students in your class.*\",\"index\":628,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"*Next year they will work a total of about twenty thousand hours for your organization. If your training efforts result in a 1 percent improvement in your subordinates’ performance, your company will gain the equivalent of two hundred hours of work as the result of the expenditure of your twelve hours.*\",\"index\":629,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"Startups often track various recruitment statistics but miss the most critical one: the number of fully productive employees added. This oversight neglects the value of training, which, if measured, might reveal significant inefficiencies. Many CEOs mistakenly believe they lack the time for training, but Andy Grove's analysis proves otherwise. He demonstrates that training is a high-leverage activity for managers. For instance, preparing twelve hours of lectures for ten employees could result in a mere 1 percent performance improvement, yielding an extra two hundred hours of work annually for the company. This clearly shows the substantial return on investment that effective training can provide.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**2. Performance management**\",\"index\":630,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"When people interview managers, they often like to ask, Have you fired anyone? Or how many people have you fired? Or how would you go about firing someone? These are all fine questions, but often the right question is the one that isn’t asked: When you fired the person, how did you know with certainty that the employee both understood the expectations of the job and was still missing them? The best answer is that the manager clearly set expectations when she trained the employee for the job. If you don’t train your people, you establish no basis for performance management. As a result, performance management in your company will be sloppy and inconsistent.\",\"index\":631,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"When people interview managers, they often like to ask, Have you fired anyone? Or how many people have you fired? Or how would you go about firing someone? These are all fine questions, but often the right question is the one that isn’t asked: When you fired the person, how did you know with certainty that the employee both understood the expectations of the job and was still missing them? The best answer is that the manager clearly set expectations when she trained the employee for the job. If you don’t train your people, you establish no basis for performance management. As a result, performance management in your company will be sloppy and inconsistent.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**3. Product quality**\",\"index\":632,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Often founders start companies with visions of elegant, beautiful product architectures that will solve so many of the nasty issues that they were forced to deal with in their previous jobs. Then, as their company becomes successful, they find that their beautiful product architecture has turned into a Frankenstein. How does this happen? As success drives the need to hire new engineers at a rapid rate, companies neglect to train the new engineers properly. As the engineers are assigned tasks, they figure out how to complete them as best they can. Often this means replicating existing facilities in the architecture, which leads to inconsistencies in the user experience, performance problems, and a general mess. And you thought training was expensive.\",\"index\":633,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"Often founders start companies with visions of elegant, beautiful product architectures that will solve so many of the nasty issues that they were forced to deal with in their previous jobs. Then, as their company becomes successful, they find that their beautiful product architecture has turned into a Frankenstein. How does this happen? As success drives the need to hire new engineers at a rapid rate, companies neglect to train the new engineers properly. As the engineers are assigned tasks, they figure out how to complete them as best they can. Often this means replicating existing facilities in the architecture, which leads to inconsistencies in the user experience, performance problems, and a general mess. And you thought training was expensive.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**4. Employee retention**\",\"index\":634,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"During a time of particularly high attrition at Netscape, I decided to read all of the exit interviews for the entire company to better understand why people quit high-tech companies. After putting economics aside, I found that there were two primary reasons why people quit:\",\"index\":635,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"* They hated their manager; generally the employees were appalled by the lack of guidance, career development, and feedback they were receiving.\\n\\n* They weren’t learning anything: The company wasn’t investing resources in helping employees develop new skills.\",\"index\":636,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"An outstanding training program can address both issues head-on.\",\"index\":637,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"During a time of particularly high attrition at Netscape, I delved into all of the exit interviews to understand why people were leaving the company. Beyond economic reasons, two primary causes emerged: employees detested their managers due to a severe lack of guidance, career development, and feedback, and they felt they weren't learning anything because the company wasn't investing in developing their skills. Implementing an outstanding training program can tackle both of these issues directly.\",\"type\":\"section\"}],\"summary\":\"Startups often track various recruitment statistics but miss the most critical one: the number of fully productive employees added, neglecting the value of training that could significantly improve efficiencies. Many CEOs mistakenly believe they lack the time for training, but Andy Grove's analysis illustrates that it is a high-leverage activity, offering substantial returns on investment. For instance, twelve hours of lectures for ten employees could yield an extra two hundred hours of work annually with a mere 1% performance improvement. Effective training sets clear performance expectations, avoids managerial inconsistencies, and prevents firing missteps. Founders often dream of elegant product architectures for their startups, but success-driven rapid hiring without proper training turns these visions into convoluted messes, resulting in performance and consistency issues. At Netscape, high attrition stemmed from employees' disdain for unhelpful managers and the lack of skill development, problems that can be mitigated with an excellent training program.\",\"type\":\"section\"}],\"summary\":\"In technology startups, people are the most critical asset, and while much emphasis is placed on recruiting, investment often halts too early. This oversight is detrimental for four key reasons: startups may track recruitment metrics but ignore the critical measure of fully productive employees, undervaluing the efficiency boost that training can provide. Many CEOs mistakenly view training as a time-consuming process, despite Andy Grove's analysis showing its high return on investment, such as twelve hours of training yielding significant yearly productivity gains. Proper training clarifies performance expectations, avoids managerial inconsistencies, and prevents poor firing decisions. Furthermore, rapid hiring without adequate training can turn a startup's envisioned product architectures into unmanageable complications, affecting performance and consistency. Netscape's high attrition, driven by ineffective managers and a lack of skill development, highlights the importance of comprehensive training programs.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**WHAT SHOULD YOU DO FIRST?**\",\"index\":638,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"The best place to start is with the topic that is most relevant to your employees: the knowledge and skill that they need to do their job. I call this functional training. Functional training can be as simple as training a new employee on your expectations for them (see “Good Product Manager/Bad Product Manager”) and as complex as a multiweek engineering boot camp to bring new recruits completely up to speed on all of the historical architectural nuances of your product. The training courses should be tailored to the specific job. If you attempt the more complex-style course, be sure to enlist the best experts on the team as well as the manager. As a happy side effect, this type of effort will do more to build a powerful, positive company culture than a hundred culture-building strategic off-site meetings.\",\"index\":639,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"The other essential component of a company’s training program is management training. Management training is the best place to start setting expectations for your management team. Do you expect them to hold regular one-on-one meetings with their employees? Do you expect them to give performance feedback? Do you expect them to train their people? Do you expect them to agree on objectives with their team? If you do, then you’d better tell them, because the management state of the art in technology companies is extremely poor. Once you’ve set expectations, the next set of management courses has already been defined; they are the courses that teach your managers how to do the things you expect (how to write a performance review or how to conduct a one-on-one).\",\"index\":640,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Once you have management training and functional training in place, there are other opportunities as well. One of the great things about building a tech company is the amazing people that you can hire. Take your best people and encourage them to share their most developed skills. Training in such topics as negotiating, interviewing, and finance will enhance your company’s competency in those areas as well as improve employee morale. Teaching can also become a badge of honor for employees who achieve an elite level of competence.\",\"index\":641,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"Start with functional training that equips your employees with the knowledge and skills essential for their roles. This can range from basic training for new employees on your expectations (like in “Good Product Manager/Bad Product Manager”) to complex, multiweek engineering boot camps to cover the nuances of your product. Tailor the courses to fit specific jobs, enlisting top team experts and the manager for more intensive programs. Interestingly, such training efforts can significantly enhance company culture better than numerous off-site meetings. Alongside functional training, implement management training to set clear expectations for your management team on holding one-on-ones, giving performance feedback, and more. This helps address the generally poor management practices observed in tech companies. Once these are in place, explore further opportunities by encouraging your top talent to share their skills in areas like negotiating, interviewing, and finance, which boosts both competence and morale. Plus, teaching can become a prestigious achievement for elite employees.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**IMPLEMENTING YOUR TRAINING PROGRAM**\",\"index\":642,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Now that we understand the value of the training and what to train on, how do we get our organization to do what we want? The first thing to recognize is that no startup has time to do optional things. Therefore, training must be mandatory. The first two types of training (functional and management) can be easily enforced as follows:\",\"index\":643,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"* Enforce functional training by withholding new employee requisitions. As Andy Grove writes, there are only two ways for a manager to improve the output of an employee: motivation and training. Therefore, training should be the most basic requirement for all managers in your organization. An effective way to enforce this requirement is by withholding new employee requisitions from managers until they’ve developed a training program for the TBH, “To Be Hired.”\\n\\n* Enforce management training by teaching it yourself. Managing the company is the CEO’s job. While you won’t have time to teach all of the management courses yourself, you should teach the course on management expectations, because they are, after all, *your* expectations. Make it an honor to participate in these sessions by selecting the best managers on your team to teach the other courses. And make that mandatory, too.\",\"index\":644,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Ironically, the biggest obstacle to putting a training program in place is the perception that it will take too much time. Keep in mind that there is no investment that you can make that will do more to improve productivity in your company. Therefore, being too busy to train is the moral equivalent of being too hungry to eat. Furthermore, it’s not that hard to create basic training courses.\",\"index\":645,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\" \",\"index\":646,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"**W**hen I ran the server product management group at Netscape, I became extremely frustrated that everybody on the team I inherited had a completely unique and different interpretation of their job. Finally, I had an epiphany that nobody in the industry had ever defined the product management job. What follows was my attempt to do that and bring down my blood pressure. Amazingly, people still read it today. This taught me the importance of training.\",\"index\":647,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"To get your organization to do what’s needed, training must be mandatory since startups can't afford optional activities. Enforce functional training by withholding new employee requisitions until managers develop a training program for future hires, emphasizing that motivation and training are key to improving output. Enforce management training by teaching it yourself or having top managers teach, ensuring these sessions reflect your expectations and are seen as an honor. The main barrier to implementing training is the misperception of time commitment; however, investing in training is crucial for productivity improvement. When I managed product group at Netscape, I realized the importance of defining roles and training after seeing varied job interpretations among team members, an experience that underscored training’s value.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**GOOD PRODUCT MANAGER/BAD PRODUCT MANAGER**\",\"index\":648,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Good product managers know the market, the product, the product line, and the competition extremely well and operate from a strong basis of knowledge and confidence. A good product manager is the CEO of the product. Good product managers take full responsibility and measure themselves in terms of the success of the product.\",\"index\":649,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"They are responsible for right product/right time and all that entails. A good product manager knows the context going in (the company, our revenue funding, competition, etc.), and they take responsibility for devising and executing a winning plan (no excuses).\",\"index\":650,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Bad product managers have lots of excuses. Not enough funding, the engineering manager is an idiot, Microsoft has ten times as many engineers working on it, I’m overworked, I don’t get enough direction. Our CEO doesn’t make these kinds of excuses and neither should the CEO of a product.\",\"index\":651,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Good product managers don’t get all of their time sucked up by the various organizations that must work together to deliver the right product at the right time. They don’t take all the product team minutes; they don’t project manage the various functions; they are not gofers for engineering. They are not part of the product team; they manage the product team. Engineering teams don’t consider good product managers a “marketing resource.” Good product managers are the marketing counterparts to the engineering manager.\",\"index\":652,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Good product managers crisply define the target, the “what” (as opposed to the “how”), and manage the delivery of the “what.” Bad product managers feel best about themselves when they figure out “how.” Good product managers communicate crisply to engineering in writing as well as verbally. Good product managers don’t give direction informally. Good product managers gather information informally.\",\"index\":653,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Good product managers create collateral, FAQs, presentations, and white papers that can be leveraged by salespeople, marketing people, and executives. Bad product managers complain that they spend all day answering questions for the sales force and are swamped. Good product managers anticipate the serious product flaws and build real solutions. Bad product managers put out fires all day.\",\"index\":654,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Good product managers take written positions on important issues (competitive silver bullets, tough architectural choices, tough product decisions, and markets to attack or yield). Bad product managers voice their opinions verbally and lament that the “powers that be” won’t let it happen. Once bad product managers fail, they point out that they predicted they would fail.\",\"index\":655,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Good product managers focus the team on revenue and customers. Bad product managers focus the team on how many features competitors are building. Good product managers define good products that can be executed with a strong effort. Bad product managers define good products that can’t be executed or let engineering build whatever they want (that is, solve the hardest problem).\",\"index\":656,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Good product managers think in terms of delivering superior value to the marketplace during product planning and achieving market share and revenue goals during the go-to-market phase. Bad product managers get very confused about the differences among delivering value, matching competitive features, pricing, and ubiquity. Good product managers decompose problems. Bad product managers combine all problems into one.\",\"index\":657,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Good product managers think about the story they want written by the press. Bad product managers think about covering every feature and being absolutely technically accurate with the press. Good product managers ask the press questions. Bad product managers answer any press question. Good product managers assume members of the press and the analyst community are really smart. Bad product managers assume that journalists and analysts are dumb because they don’t understand the subtle nuances of their particular technology.\",\"index\":658,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Good product managers err on the side of clarity. Bad product managers never even explain the obvious. Good product managers define their job and their success. Bad product managers constantly want to be told what to do.\",\"index\":659,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Good product managers send their status reports in on time every week, because they are disciplined. Bad product managers forget to send in their status reports on time, because they don’t value discipline.\",\"index\":660,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"\",\"index\":661,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\" \",\"index\":662,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"A good product manager acts as the CEO of their product, thoroughly understanding their market, product line, and competition. They take full responsibility for the product's success, devising and executing plans confidently without excuses, ensuring timely delivery. Unlike bad product managers, who lack discipline and rely on excuses, good product managers set clear targets, communicate effectively with engineering teams, gather information informally, and create valuable collateral for sales and marketing. They focus on revenue and customer needs over just features, anticipate flaws, and build solutions proactively. Good product managers articulate and execute coherent market strategies, maintain discipline, handle media interactions smartly, and consistently deliver on their responsibilities, setting themselves apart from those who fail to take responsibility and lack direction.\",\"type\":\"section\"}],\"summary\":\"In technology startups, people are the most critical asset, yet investment in them often stops too early, which can be detrimental. Startups may track recruitment but overlook training, which is crucial for productivity. CEOs often see training as time-consuming; however, Andy Grove's analysis indicates significant ROI, such as twelve hours of training yielding yearly productivity gains. Proper training sets performance expectations, prevents managerial inconsistencies, and avoids poor firing decisions. Rapid hiring without adequate training can complicate product architecture, as seen with Netscape's high attrition caused by ineffective managers and lack of skill development. Begin with functional training to equip employees with necessary skills and knowledge, and ensure management training to set clear expectations for holding one-on-ones and giving feedback. Encourage top talent to share their skills, making training a prestigious achievement. Training must be mandatory; withhold new hire requisitions until managers develop training programs. Overcome the misperception of time commitment, as training is essential for productivity improvement. A good product manager acts as the CEO of their product, understanding the market, competition, and taking full responsibility for the product's success, unlike bad managers who lack discipline and rely on excuses. They set clear targets, communicate effectively, gather information informally, and focus on revenue and customer needs, maintaining discipline and executing strategies coherently.\",\"type\":\"section\"}],\"summary\":\"At Netscape, I realized the critical importance of training employees, a lesson underscored by Andy Grove's *High Output Management*. Many companies mistakenly believe their employees are too smart to need training, but even high-tech roles require guidance. Initially, training in other companies seemed ineffective due to generic courses by external firms. Inspired by Grove's view that training should be a manager’s responsibility, I created a concise training document, “Good Product Manager/Bad Product Manager.” This straightforward guide dramatically improved my team's performance, turning underperforming product managers into valuable assets. This experience at Netscape, coupled with Grove's insights, convinced me to prioritize training when I later founded Loudcloud, contributing significantly to our success. For technology startups, continuous investment in people is crucial. Training boosts productivity, sets clear expectations, and prevents mismanagement. Begin with functional training and ensure management training to standardize key practices. Encourage top talent to lead training, adding prestige to the process. Make training mandatory and overcome the misconception that it is too time-consuming; it is essential for long-term productivity. Good product managers should understand their product's market, competition, and take full responsibility for its success, maintaining discipline and clear communication, unlike bad managers who make excuses and lack focus.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**[IS IT OKAY TO HIRE PEOPLE FROM YOUR FRIEND’S COMPANY?]()**\",\"index\":663,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Every good technology company needs great people. The best companies invest time, money, and sweat equity into becoming world-class recruiting machines. But how far should you take your quest to build the world’s greatest team? Is it fair game to hire employees from your friend’s company? Will you still be friends?\",\"index\":664,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"First, what do I mean by “friends”? There are two relevant categories:\",\"index\":665,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"* Important business partners\\n\\n* Friends\",\"index\":666,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"For this discussion, friends and important business partners are roughly the same.\",\"index\":667,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Most CEOs would never target a friend’s company as a source of talent. As CEO, one generally doesn’t have many true friends in business, and raiding your friend’s company is a sure way to lose one. Nevertheless, almost every CEO will be faced with the decision of whether to hire an employee out of her friend’s company. How does it happen? When is it okay? When will it cost you a friend?\",\"index\":668,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**BUT THEY WERE ALREADY LOOKING**\",\"index\":669,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"It always starts in the same way. Your friend Cathy has a great engineer working for her named Mitchell. Mitchell happens to be friends with one of your top engineers. Your engineer brings Mitchell in for an interview, unbeknownst to you, and he naturally sails through the process. The final step is the interview with you, the CEO. You immediately notice that Mitchell currently works at your good friend Cathy’s company. You check with your people to make sure that they did not approach Mitchell first, and they assure you that Mitchell was already looking and will go to another company if not yours. Now what?\",\"index\":670,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"At this point, you might be thinking, “If Mitchell is leaving, then logically my friend Cathy should want him to go to my company rather than to a competitor or a company with a CEO whom she doesn’t like.” Maybe Cathy will see it that way, but probably not.\",\"index\":671,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"People generally leave companies when things are not going well, so you should assume that Cathy is fighting for her company’s life. In this situation, nothing will cut her deeper than losing a great employee, because she knows that the other employees will see that as a leading indicator of the company’s demise. Even more damaging for Cathy is the fact that her employees will perceive your move as an act of betrayal—Cathy’s so-called friend is raiding her company. They will think, “Cathy is such an ineffective CEO that she cannot even keep her friends from hiring her people.” In this way, a logical issue quickly becomes an emotional one.\",\"index\":672,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"You don’t want to lose Cathy as a friend, so you assure her that Mitchell is the exception and that he came to you and that he will be the first and only one of her employees that joins your company. Generally, this explanation will work and Cathy will understand and appreciate the gesture. She will forgive, but rest assured, she will not forget.\",\"index\":673,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Her memory of Mitchell will be important, because Mitchell will be just the first step in the demise of your relationship. Since Mitchell is a stellar hire, Cathy’s other strong employees will likely call Mitchell to understand why he left and where he is going. He will explain his reasoning and his reasons will be compelling. And suddenly they will want to follow Mitchell’s path and join your company, too. By the time you become aware of the situation, promises will have been made to prospective employees who approached Mitchell and offers may be out.\",\"index\":674,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"In each case, your employees will assure you that they were approached by Cathy’s employees and not vice versa. They will point out that the candidates have offers from other companies as well, so they will definitely leave and you might as well benefit from their restlessness. Cathy’s managers will almost certainly tell a different story. They will plead with her to get her friend to stop raiding their stable of employees or else they will never be able to meet their commitments. This will embarrass and enrage Cathy. In the end, social pressure will trump all your brilliant countervailing logic.\",\"index\":675,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Here’s an easy way to think about the dynamic. If your husband left you, would you want your best friend to date him? He’s going to date somebody, so wouldn’t you want your friend to have him? It seems logical, but this situation is far from logical and you just lost one friend.\",\"index\":676,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"It always starts with a simple setup: your engineer brings Mitchell, a great talent from your friend Cathy’s company, in for an interview. He sails through the process, and you, the CEO, must decide if you should hire him despite the potential strain on your friendship with Cathy. You reason that Cathy might prefer Mitchell joining your company over a competitor’s, but it’s likely she won’t see it that way. Losing a top employee is demoralizing and signals trouble to the remaining team, making it an emotionally charged issue rather than a logical one. You assure Cathy that Mitchell was an exception, and while she might forgive, she won’t forget. When Mitchell joins your team, other strong employees at Cathy’s company may want to follow, leading to a perception of betrayal and social pressure mounting against you. Just as you wouldn’t want your best friend dating your ex, Cathy will feel hurt and betrayed, ultimately damaging your friendship.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**SO WHAT SHOULD YOU DO?**\",\"index\":677,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"First, keep in mind that the employees are either extremely good or you probably won’t want them in your company anyway. So, you will either be recruiting top-notch employees from your friend’s company or you will be adding mediocre people. Do not assume the people you are taking will not be missed.\",\"index\":678,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"A good rule of thumb is my Reflexive Principle of Employee Raiding, which states, “If you would be shocked and horrified if Company X hired several of your employees, then you should not hire any of theirs.” The number of such companies should be small and may very well be zero.\",\"index\":679,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"In order to avoid these sticky situations, many companies employ written or unwritten policies that name companies where it is not okay to hire without CEO (or senior executive) approval. With such a policy in place, you will be able to give your friend one last chance to save their employee or to object prior to you hiring them.\",\"index\":680,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"With that in mind, the best way to deal with these situations is openly and transparently. Once you become aware of the conflict between hiring the superstar employee and double-crossing your valued friend, you should get the issue onto the table by informing the employee that you have an important business relationship with his existing company and you will have to complete a reference check with the CEO prior to extending the offer. Let him know that if he does not want that to happen, then you will stop the process now and keep the process to date confidential. By speaking with your friend before making the hire, you will be able to better judge the relationship impact of hiring her employee. In addition, you may avoid making a bad hire, as often candidates who do well in interviews turn out to be bad employees.\",\"index\":681,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"Keep in mind that employees are either extremely good or probably not worth hiring, so you will either recruit top talent from a friend's company or end up with mediocre people. This principle, my Reflexive Principle of Employee Raiding, advises: “If you would be shocked if Company X hired several of your employees, then you shouldn’t hire any of theirs.” Companies often have policies requiring CEO or senior executive approval before hiring from certain companies to avoid conflicts. It's best to handle these situations openly; inform the candidate of your business relationship with their current company and your need to complete a reference check with their CEO. If the candidate objects, terminate the process confidentially. Speaking with your friend before hiring their employee helps judge the relationship impact and might prevent a bad hire, as interview performance can be misleading.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**CLOSING THOUGHTS**\",\"index\":682,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"In the classic movie *The Good, the Bad and the Ugly*, Clint Eastwood “The Good” and Eli Wallach “The Ugly” are partners in crime. Wallach, a known criminal, has a bounty on his head and the two of them run a scam to collect the reward money. Eastwood turns Wallach in and collects the reward. Then Wallach is sentenced to death by hanging. As Wallach sits on a horse, hands tied behind his back and about to be hanged with a rope around his neck, Eastwood shoots the rope from a distance and frees Wallach and they split the reward money. This scheme works brilliantly, until one day Eastwood frees Wallach but informs Wallach: “I don’t think you’ll ever be worth more than three thousand dollars.” Wallach retorts, “What do you mean?” Eastwood informs him, “I mean, our partnership is untied. Oh no, not you. You remain tied. I’ll keep the money, and you can have the rope.” What follows is one of the great revenge pursuits in motion picture history.\",\"index\":683,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"So, when you tell your CEO friend that you don’t think she’ll ever be worth more than this employee, don’t expect to stay friends.\",\"index\":684,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"\",\"index\":685,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\" \",\"index\":686,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"In the classic movie *The Good, the Bad and the Ugly*, Clint Eastwood (The Good) and Eli Wallach (The Ugly) execute a cynical scheme to make money off Wallach's bounty. Wallach, an infamous criminal, gets turned in by Eastwood, who then collects the reward money. Just before Wallach is hanged, Eastwood shoots the rope, freeing him, and they split the money. This routine succeeds until Eastwood tells Wallach he’ll never be worth more than three thousand dollars and ends their partnership, keeping the money and leaving Wallach to fend for himself. This betrayal sparks an epic revenge pursuit, one of the greatest in cinem