":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"The most important thing to understand is that the job of a big company executive is very different from the job of a small company executive. When I was managing thousands of people at Hewlett-Packard after the sale of Opsware, there was an incredible number of incoming demands on my time. Everyone wanted a piece of me. Little companies wanted to partner with me or sell themselves to me, people in my organization needed approvals, other business units needed my help, customers wanted my attention, and so forth. As a result, I spent most of my time optimizing and tuning the existing business. Most of the work that I did was “incoming.” In fact, most skilled big company executives will tell you that if you have more than three new initiatives in a quarter, you are trying to do too much. As a result, big company executives tend to be interrupt-driven.\",\"index\":691,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"In contrast, when you are a startup executive, nothing happens unless you make it happen. In the early days of a company, you have to take eight to ten new initiatives a day or the company will stand still. There is no inertia that’s putting the company in motion. Without massive input from you, the company will stay at rest.\",\"index\":692,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"Fast-forward six months, and everyone in the company is scratching their heads over why the sales (or marketing, finance, or product) guy who has delivered nothing received such a massive stock option package, while the people doing all the work have much fewer options. To make matters worse, missing your numbers is now a norm because your highly paid executive is unproductive. What gives? The key difference lies in the roles of big company executives versus startup executives. When I was at Hewlett-Packard after selling Opsware, my time was bombarded with incoming demands. Partnership offers, internal approvals, customer attention—they all needed my time, making my job largely about optimizing and maintaining the existing business. Big company executives, who often handle no more than three new initiatives a quarter, operate in an interrupt-driven mode. On the flip side, startup executives generate momentum from scratch, needing to undertake eight to ten new initiatives daily to keep the company progressing. Without their proactive drive, the company stagnates.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**SO WHAT HAPPENS?**\",\"index\":693,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Once you hire one of these big company executives, there are two dangerous mismatches that you will face:\",\"index\":694,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**1.** **Rhythm mismatch** Your executive has been conditioned to wait for the emails to come in, wait for the phone to ring, and wait for the meetings to get scheduled. In your company, he will be waiting a long time. If your new executive waits (as per his training), your other employees will become suspicious. You’ll hear things like “What does that guy do all day long?” and “Why did he get so many options?”\",\"index\":695,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"**2.** **Skill set mismatch** Running a large organization requires very different skills than creating and building an organization. When you run a large organization, you tend to become very good at tasks such as complex decision-making, prioritization, organizational design, process improvement, and organizational communication. When you are building an organization, there is no organization to design, there are no processes to improve, and communicating with the organization is simple. On the other hand, you have to be very adept at running a high-quality hiring process, have terrific domain expertise (you are personally responsible for quality control), know how to create process from scratch, and be extremely creative about initiating new directions and tasks.\",\"index\":696,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"type\":\"clump\",\"summary\":\"**1.** **Rhythm mismatch** Your executive has been conditioned to wait for the emails to come in, wait for the phone to ring, and wait for the meetings to get scheduled. In your company, he will be waiting a long time. If your new executive waits (as per his training), your other employees will become suspicious. You’ll hear things like “What does that guy do all day long?” and “Why did he get so many options?” \\n\\n **2.** **Skill set mismatch** Running a large organization requires very different skills than creating and building an organization. When you run a large organization, you tend to become very good at tasks such as complex decision-making, prioritization, organizational design, process improvement, and organizational communication. When you are building an organization, there is no organization to design, there are no processes to improve, and communicating with the organization is simple. On the other hand, you have to be very adept at running a high-quality hiring process, have terrific domain expertise (you are personally responsible for quality control), know how to create process from scratch, and be extremely creative about initiating new directions and tasks.\"}],\"summary\":\"When you hire executives from large companies, you may encounter two significant mismatches: rhythm and skill set. **1. Rhythm mismatch**: These executives are accustomed to waiting for emails, phone calls, and scheduled meetings, which won't happen as frequently in a smaller company. This can lead to suspicion among other employees, who might question the executive's contributions and compensation. **2. Skill set mismatch**: Managing a large organization demands skills like complex decision-making and process improvement, which differ from the skills needed to build a company. Building a company requires talents in sourcing top talent, possessing domain expertise, creating processes from scratch, and innovatively initiating new tasks and directions.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**HOW CAN YOU STOP THINGS FROM GOING HORRIBLY WRONG?**\",\"index\":697,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"There are two key steps to avoiding disaster:\",\"index\":698,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**1.** Screen for devastating mismatches in the interview process.\",\"index\":699,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"**2.** Take integration as seriously as interviewing.\",\"index\":700,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"type\":\"clump\",\"summary\":\"**1.** Screen for devastating mismatches in the interview process. \\n\\n **2.** Take integration as seriously as interviewing.\"}],\"summary\":\"To avoid disaster, follow these crucial steps: **1.** Screen for devastating mismatches during the interview process. **2.** Take integration as seriously as interviewing.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**SCREEN FOR MISMATCHES**\",\"index\":701,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"How do you tell if the rhythm mismatch or the skill set mismatch will be too much to overcome? Here are some interview questions that I found very helpful:\",\"index\":702,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"**What will you do in your first month on the job?**\",\"index\":703,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Beware of answers that overemphasize learning. This may indicate that the candidate thinks there is more to learn about your organization than there actually is. More specifically, he may think that your organization is as complex as his current organization.\",\"index\":704,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Beware of any indication that the candidate needs to be interrupt-driven rather than setting the pace personally. The interrupts will never come.\",\"index\":705,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Look for candidates who come in with more new initiatives than you think are possible. This is a good sign.\",\"index\":706,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**How will your new job differ from your current job?**\",\"index\":707,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Look for self-awareness of the differences here. If they have the experience in what you need, they will be articulate on this point.\",\"index\":708,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Beware of candidates who think that too much of their experience is immediately transferable. It may pay off down the line, but likely not tomorrow.\",\"index\":709,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"Look for self-awareness of differences here. Candidates with relevant experience will articulate this clearly. Be cautious of those who assume too much of their experience is instantly transferable. It might benefit later, but likely not right away.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**Why do you want to join a small company?**\",\"index\":710,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Beware of equity being the primary motivation. One percent of nothing is nothing. That’s something that big company executives sometimes have a hard time understanding.\",\"index\":711,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"It’s much better if they want to be more creative. The most important difference between big and small companies is the amount of time running versus creating. A desire to do more creating is the right reason to want to join your company.\",\"index\":712,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"Beware of letting equity be the main driver. One percent of nothing is still nothing, a concept often misunderstood by big company executives. It's far more beneficial if they have a genuine desire to be more creative. The key difference between big and small companies lies in the balance between running the business and creating. Aspiring to spend more time on creative endeavors is the right reason to join your company.\",\"type\":\"section\"}],\"summary\":\"Focus on candidates who demonstrate self-awareness of their differences and can articulate how their experience is relevant. Be wary of those who assume their experience will be immediately transferable—it might help later, but not right away. Don't let equity be the main motivator; remember that one percent of nothing is still nothing, a point often missed by big company executives. It's more beneficial if they genuinely desire to be creative. The key distinction between big and small companies lies in balancing business operations with creative efforts. Aspiring to spend more time on creativity is the right reason to join your company.\",\"type\":\"section\"}],\"summary\":\"To assess if the rhythm or skill set mismatch will be too much to overcome, consider using the following interview questions: **What will you do in your first month on the job?** Look out for answers that overemphasize learning, as this may signal that the candidate perceives your organization as more complex than it is. Beware of candidates who prefer to be interrupt-driven instead of setting their own pace as such interruptions rarely occur. Ideal candidates will propose more new initiatives than you expect and show self-awareness of their differences while explaining how their experience is applicable. Be cautious of those who believe their skills are immediately transferable. Don't let equity be their main motivator because one percent of nothing is still nothing, a concept often missed by big company executives. Instead, value candidates who genuinely wish to be creative—balancing business operations with creative efforts is key in a small company.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**AGGRESSIVELY INTEGRATE THE CANDIDATE ONCE ON BOARD**\",\"index\":713,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Perhaps the most critical step is integration. You should plan to spend a huge amount of time integrating any new executive. Here are some things to keep in mind:\",\"index\":714,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"* *Force them to create.* Give them monthly, weekly, and even daily objectives to make sure that they produce immediately. The rest of the company will be watching and this will be critical to their assimilation.\\n\\n* *Make sure that they “get it.”* Content-free executives have no value in startups. Every executive must understand the product, the technology, the customers, and the market. Force your newbie to learn these things. Consider scheduling a daily meeting with your new executive. Require them to bring a comprehensive set of questions about everything they heard that day but did not completely understand. Answer those questions in depth; start with first principles. Bring them up to speed fast. If they don’t have any questions, consider firing them. If in thirty days you don’t feel that they are coming up to speed, definitely fire them.\\n\\n* *Put them in the mix.* Make sure that they initiate contact and interaction with their peers and other key people in the organization. Give them a list of people they need to know and learn from. Once they’ve done that, require a report from them on what they learned from each person.\",\"index\":715,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"Integration is the most critical step when bringing on a new executive, and you should plan to dedicate significant time to this process. Here are key points to consider: \\n\\n* **Force them to create.** Assign immediate monthly, weekly, and daily objectives to ensure they start producing right away, as the rest of the company will be observing them closely. This is vital for their assimilation.\\n* **Make sure they “get it.”** Content-free executives are worthless in startups. They must understand the product, technology, customers, and market. Ensure your new executive learns these thoroughly. Schedule daily meetings where they bring comprehensive questions about things they don’t understand and provide in-depth answers from first principles. If they don’t have questions or aren’t up to speed in 30 days, consider firing them.\\n* **Put them in the mix.** Encourage them to engage with peers and key organizational figures. Provide a list of critical contacts they need to interact with and learn from, and then require them to report back on their learnings from each person.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**FINAL THOUGHTS**\",\"index\":716,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Nothing will accelerate your company’s development like hiring someone who has experience building a very similar company at larger scale. However, doing so can be fraught with peril. Make sure to pay attention to the important leading indicators of success and failure.\",\"index\":717,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"\",\"index\":718,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\" \",\"index\":719,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"Nothing will accelerate your company’s development like hiring someone with experience building a similar company at a larger scale. However, this move can be fraught with peril. Focus on the crucial leading indicators of both success and failure to navigate this path effectively.\",\"type\":\"section\"}],\"summary\":\"Fast-forward six months, and confusion arises over why an unproductive executive received a massive stock option package while the hardworking employees received far fewer. The answer lies in the different roles of big company versus startup executives. At a large company like Hewlett-Packard, executives are often reactive, managing fewer initiatives and focusing on maintaining the status quo. In contrast, startup executives must proactively generate momentum, undertaking numerous new initiatives daily. Hiring executives from large companies can lead to mismatches in rhythm and skill set, potentially causing stagnation and dissatisfaction. To avoid disaster, thoroughly screen for mismatches during interviews and prioritize integration. Crucial steps include: ensuring new hires immediately start producing by assigning objectives, confirming they understand the product and market, and encouraging engagement with key figures. Ideal candidates demonstrate self-awareness and propose more initiatives than expected. Value those motivated by creativity over equity. Remember, integration is critical—new executives should bring questions and learn quickly. Observing these leading indicators will help navigate the challenges of scaling with experienced hires.\",\"type\":\"section\"}],\"summary\":\"You've achieved product-market fit and are ready to scale up. The board urges you to hire experienced executives to provide financial, sales, and marketing expertise, but suggested candidates may not always be the right fit. For instance, while a VC might favor a highly accomplished head of sales from a big company due to an impressive résumé, this can lead to issues. Big company executives are often accustomed to maintaining the status quo and may not thrive in the proactive, multifaceted environment of a startup. This mismatch can cause frustration over unproductive executives receiving substantial stock options compared to hardworking employees. To avoid this, thoroughly screen candidates for fit by ensuring they understand the rapid pace and creative challenges of a startup. Assign them objectives immediately, and prioritize those who engage proactively and blend well with the team culture. Observing these factors will help ensure successful integration and avoid disruptions during your company's growth phase.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**[HIRING EXECUTIVES: IF YOU’VE NEVER DONE THE JOB, HOW DO YOU HIRE SOMEBODY GOOD?]()**\",\"index\":720,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"The biggest difference between being a great functional manager and being a great general manager—and particularly a great CEO—is that as a general manager, you must hire and manage people who are far more competent at their jobs than you would be at their jobs. In fact, often you will have to hire and manage people to do jobs that you have never done. How many CEOs have been head of HR, engineering, sales, marketing, finance, and legal? Probably none.\",\"index\":721,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"So, with no experience, how do you hire someone good?\",\"index\":722,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**STEP 1: KNOW WHAT YOU WANT**\",\"index\":723,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Step 1 is definitely the most important step in the process and also the one that gets skipped most often. As the great self-help coach Tony Robbins says, “If you don’t know what you want, the chances that you’ll get it are extremely low.” If you have never done the job, how do you know what to want?\",\"index\":724,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"First, you must realize how ignorant you are and resist the temptation to educate yourself simply by interviewing candidates. While the interview process can be highly educational, using that as the sole information source is dangerous. Doing so will make you susceptible to the following traps:\",\"index\":725,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"* **Hiring on look and feel** It may seem silly to think that anyone would hire an executive based on the way they look and sound in an interview, but in my experience, look and feel are the top criteria for most executive searches. When you combine a CEO who doesn’t know what she wants and a board of directors that hasn’t thought much about the hire, what do you think the criteria will be?\\n\\n* **Looking for someone out of central casting** If I had followed this path, I would never have hired Mark Cranney and you probably would not be reading this now. This wrongheaded approach is the moral equivalent of looking for the Platonic ideal for a head of sales. You imagine what the perfect sales executive might be like, and then you attempt to match real-world candidates to your model. This is a bad idea for several reasons. First, you are not hiring an abstract executive to work at an arbitrary company. You must hire the right person for your company at this particular point in time. The head of sales at Oracle in 2010 would likely have failed in 1989. The VP of engineering at Apple might be exactly the wrong choice for Foursquare. The details and the specifics matter. Second, your imaginary model is almost certainly wrong. What is your basis for creating this model? Finally, it will be incredibly difficult to educate an interview team on such an abstract set of criteria. As a result, everybody will be looking for something different.\\n\\n* **Valuing lack of weakness rather than strength** The more experience you have, the more you realize that there is something seriously wrong with every employee in your company (including you). Nobody is perfect.\",\"index\":726,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"The very best way to know what you want is to act in the role. Not just in title, but in real action. In my career, I’ve been acting VP of HR, CFO, and VP of sales. Often CEOs resist acting in functional roles, because they worry that they lack the appropriate knowledge. This worry is precisely why you should act—to get the appropriate knowledge. Indeed, acting is really the only way to get all the knowledge that you need to make the hire, because you are looking for the right executive for your company today, not a generic executive.\",\"index\":727,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"In addition to acting in the role, it helps greatly to bring in domain experts. If you know a great head of sales, interview them first and learn what they think made them great. Figure out which of those strengths most directly match the needs of your company. If possible, include the domain expert in the interview process. However, be aware that the domain expert only has part of the knowledge necessary to make the hire. Specifically, she has very little knowledge of your company, how it works, and what its needs are. Therefore, you cannot defer the decision to the domain expert.\",\"index\":728,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Finally, be clear in your own mind about your expectations for this person upon joining your company. What will this person do in the first thirty days? What do you expect their motivation to be for joining? Do you want them to build a large organization right away or hire only one or two people over the next year?\",\"index\":729,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"Step 1 is undeniably crucial in the hiring process, yet it often gets overlooked. Tony Robbins aptly states, “If you don’t know what you want, the chances that you’ll get it are extremely low.” Before diving into candidate interviews, recognize your lack of knowledge about the role and resist using interviews as your sole educational tool. Falling into traps like hiring based on look and feel, seeking a candidate who fits an idealized mold, or valuing lack of weaknesses over actual strengths is common. Instead, truly understanding what you want involves actually performing the role yourself. This firsthand experience is indispensable for recognizing the requisite knowledge and skills, as I’ve realized through my roles as acting VP of HR, CFO, and VP of sales. Additionally, consult domain experts to align their insights with your company's specific needs, but remember, you cannot leave the final decision to them. Be explicitly clear about your expectations for the new hire's first thirty days, their motivation for joining, and their organizational goals.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**STEP 2. RUN A PROCESS THAT FIGURES OUT THE RIGHT MATCH**\",\"index\":730,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"In order to find the right executive, you must now take the knowledge that you have gathered and translate it into a process that yields the right candidate. Here is the process that I like to use.\",\"index\":731,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**Write down the strengths you want and the weaknesses that you are willing to tolerate.**\",\"index\":732,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"In order to ensure completeness, I find it useful to include criteria from the following subdivisions when hiring executives:\",\"index\":733,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"* Will the executive be world-class at running the function?\\n\\n* Is the executive outstanding operationally?\\n\\n* Will the executive make a major contribution to the strategic direction of the company? This is the “are they smart enough?” criterion.\\n\\n* Will the executive be an effective member of the team? *Effective* is the key word. It’s possible for an executive to be well liked and totally ineffective with respect to the other members of the team. It’s also possible for an executive to be highly effective and profoundly influential while being totally despised. The latter is far better.\",\"index\":734,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"These functions do not carry equal weight for all positions. Make sure that you balance them appropriately. Generally, operational excellence is far more important for a VP of engineering or a VP of sales than for a VP of marketing or a CFO.\",\"index\":735,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"When hiring executives, it's crucial to evaluate them based on several key criteria: their capability to excel at running the function, operational prowess, contribution to the company’s strategic direction (the “are they smart enough?” criterion), and effectiveness as a team member. While being well-liked is nice, being effective and influential is far more valuable, even if it means being unpopular. These criteria don't hold the same weight across all positions. For instance, operational excellence is typically more critical for a VP of Engineering or Sales than for a VP of Marketing or a CFO, so balance these factors accordingly.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**Develop questions that test for the criteria (see the appendix).**\",\"index\":736,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"This effort is important even if you never ask the candidate any of the pre-prepared questions. By writing down questions that test for what you want, you will get to a level of specificity that will be extremely difficult to achieve otherwise. (See the appendix for an example of questions that I wrote for running the enterprise sales function and operational excellence.) Assemble an appropriate interview team and conduct the interviews.\",\"index\":737,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"This effort is important even if you never ask the candidate any of the pre-prepared questions. By writing down questions that test for what you want, you will get to a level of specificity that will be extremely difficult to achieve otherwise. (See the appendix for an example of questions that I wrote for running the enterprise sales function and operational excellence.) Assemble an appropriate interview team and conduct the interviews.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**Assemble the interview team.**\",\"index\":738,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"In assembling the team, you should keep two questions in mind:\",\"index\":739,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"**1.** Who will best help you figure out whether the candidate meets the criteria? These may be internal or external people. They can be board members, other executives, or just experts.\",\"index\":740,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"**2.** Who do you need to support the decision once the executive is on board? This group is just as important as the first. No matter how great an executive is, they will have trouble succeeding if the people around them sabotage everything they do. The best way to avoid that is to understand any potential issues before the person is hired.\",\"index\":741,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Clearly, some people will be in both groups one and two. The opinions of both groups will be very important: Group one will help you determine the best candidate and group two will help you gauge how easily each candidate will integrate into your company. Generally, it’s best to have group two interview finalist candidates only.\",\"index\":742,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Next, assign questions to interviewers based on their talents. Specifically, make sure that the interviewer who asks the questions deeply understands what a good answer will sound like.\",\"index\":743,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"As you conduct the interviews, be sure to discuss each interview with the interviewer. Use this time to drive to a common understanding of the criteria, so that you will get the best information possible.\",\"index\":744,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"When assembling a hiring team, keep two key questions in mind: who will best help determine if the candidate meets the criteria and who will support the decision once the executive joins. The first group may include board members, executives, or experts to help evaluate the candidate's fit. The second group is crucial to avoid any potential sabotage and ensure a smooth integration. Some individuals will belong to both groups, with group one focusing on selecting the best candidate and group two on assessing integration ease. Generally, have group two interview only the finalists. Assign questions based on interviewers' expertise, ensuring they understand what constitutes a good answer. Discuss each interview with the interviewer to agree on the criteria and gather the best information.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**Backdoor and front-door references.**\",\"index\":745,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"For the final candidates, it’s critically important that the CEO conduct the reference checks herself. The references need to be checked against the same hiring criteria that you tested for during the interview process. Backdoor reference checks (checks from people who know the candidate, but were not referred by the candidate) can be an extremely useful way to get an unbiased view. However, do not discount the front-door references. While they clearly have committed to giving a positive reference (or they wouldn’t be on the list), you are not looking for positive or negative with them. You are looking for fit with your criteria. Often, the front-door references will know the candidate best and will be quite helpful in this respect.\",\"index\":746,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"For the final candidates, it’s critically important that the CEO conduct the reference checks herself. The references need to be checked against the same hiring criteria that you tested for during the interview process. Backdoor reference checks (checks from people who know the candidate, but were not referred by the candidate) can be an extremely useful way to get an unbiased view. However, do not discount the front-door references. While they clearly have committed to giving a positive reference (or they wouldn’t be on the list), you are not looking for positive or negative with them. You are looking for fit with your criteria. Often, the front-door references will know the candidate best and will be quite helpful in this respect.\",\"type\":\"section\"}],\"summary\":\"When hiring executives, it's essential to assess their ability to run their function, operational skills, strategic contribution, and effectiveness as team members. While popularity is nice, effectiveness and influence are what truly matter, even if they make the candidate unpopular. These criteria vary in importance depending on the role; for instance, operational excellence is crucial for a VP of Engineering or Sales but less so for a VP of Marketing or CFO. Crafting specific questions beforehand helps you pinpoint desired qualities. Assemble an interview team that can evaluate the candidate’s fit and support the decision post-hiring. This team may include board members, executives, or experts. Have group one focus on candidate selection and group two on integration, with only finalists being interviewed by group two. Tailor questions to interviewers’ strengths and debrief with them to align on criteria. For finalists, the CEO should personally conduct reference checks, comparing them against the same criteria used in interviews. Utilize both backdoor and front-door references to get an unbiased and comprehensive view of the candidate's fit.\",\"type\":\"section\"}],\"summary\":\"To find the right executive, transform the knowledge you've acquired into an effective hiring process. Key steps include assessing the candidate's ability to manage their function, operational competency, strategic contribution, and teamwork effectiveness. While likability is secondary, effectiveness and influence are paramount. Criteria importance varies by role; operational excellence is vital for a VP of Engineering or Sales but less so for a VP of Marketing or CFO. Develop specific questions to highlight these qualities. Form an interview team with members capable of evaluating fit and supporting the hire post-selection, such as board members or experts. Divide them into two groups: one for selection, the other focusing on candidate integration, with only finalists meeting the latter. Tailor questions to each interviewer’s strengths and debrief to ensure alignment. For finalists, the CEO should personally conduct thorough reference checks using a mix of backdoor and front-door references to get an unbiased, detailed view of the candidate.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**STEP 3: MAKE A LONELY DECISION**\",\"index\":747,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Despite many people being involved in the process, the ultimate decision should be made solo. Only the CEO has comprehensive knowledge of the criteria, the rationale for the criteria, all of the feedback from interviewers and references, and the relative importance of the various stakeholders. Consensus decisions about executives almost always sway the process away from strength and toward lack of weakness. It’s a lonely job, but somebody has to do it.\",\"index\":748,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"\",\"index\":749,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\" \",\"index\":750,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"Despite many people being involved in the process, the ultimate decision should be made solo. Only the CEO possesses the comprehensive knowledge of the criteria, the rationale behind them, all the feedback from interviewers and references, and the relative importance of various stakeholders. Consensus decisions about executives almost always push the process away from strength and toward lack of weakness. It’s a lonely job, but somebody has to do it.\",\"type\":\"section\"}],\"summary\":\"Step 1 of the hiring process is critical yet often neglected. As Tony Robbins wisely notes, knowing what you want is crucial for success. Before starting interviews, acknowledge your knowledge gaps about the role and avoid using interviews to fill those gaps. Avoid common pitfalls like hiring based on look and feel, seeking an ideal candidate mold, or prioritizing lack of weaknesses over actual strengths. Truly understand the role by performing it yourself, much like I did when acting as VP of HR, CFO, and VP of Sales. Consult domain experts to align their insights with your company's needs, but the final decision remains yours. Be explicit about expectations for the new hire's first thirty days, their motivations, and their organizational goals. \\n\\nTransform your insights into an effective hiring process by assessing candidates' ability to manage their function, operational competency, strategic contribution, and teamwork effectiveness. Prioritize effectiveness and influence over likability. Tailor the importance of criteria to the role, with operational excellence crucial for positions like VP of Engineering or Sales. Form an interview team with members capable of evaluating fit and supporting the hire, dividing them into selection and candidate integration groups. Tailor interview questions and debrief to ensure alignment. For finalists, the CEO should conduct thorough reference checks using backdoor and front-door references. Ultimately, the CEO alone should make the final decision, as only they have a comprehensive understanding of the criteria, the feedback, and the importance of each stakeholder’s input. Consensus decisions often dilute strengths, and it’s the CEO’s responsibility to make the tough call.\",\"type\":\"section\"}],\"summary\":\"The biggest difference between being a great functional manager and a great general manager or CEO is the necessity to hire and manage people who excel in roles where you might lack expertise, such as HR, engineering, sales, marketing, finance, or legal. To effectively hire without personal experience in these areas, start by clearly defining what you want, recognizing your knowledge gaps, and avoiding interviews to fill those gaps. Avoid common hiring pitfalls such as choosing candidates based on look and feel, an ideal mold, or prioritizing lack of weaknesses over strengths. Gain a practical understanding of the role and consult domain experts to tailor insights to your company’s needs, though the final decision is yours. Establish clear expectations for the new hire’s initial 30 days, motivations, and organizational goals. Create an effective hiring process by evaluating candidates' management ability, operational competency, strategic contribution, and teamwork, prioritizing effectiveness over likability. Assemble an interview team for both selection and integration, ensuring alignment with tailored questions and debriefs. Conduct thorough reference checks on finalists, both backdoor and front-door, and ultimately, the CEO should make the final hiring decision. This approach ensures a comprehensive and strategic hiring process, crucial for effective leadership and organizational success.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**[WHEN EMPLOYEES MISINTERPRET MANAGERS]()**\",\"index\":751,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Early on at Loudcloud, many people would do crazy things backed up by “Ben said.” Often I didn’t say any of it, but I definitely didn’t say it in the way they used it. The management principles I share here are connected to many of those experiences.\",\"index\":752,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"When I ran Opsware, we had the nonlinear quarter problem also known affectionately as the hockey stick. The hockey stick refers to the shape of the revenue graph over the course of a quarter. Our hockey stick was so bad that one quarter, we booked 90 percent of our new bookings on the last day of the quarter. Sales patterns like this make it difficult to plan the business and are particularly harrowing when you are, as we were, a public company.\",\"index\":753,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Naturally, I was determined to straighten out the hockey stick and bring some sanity to the business. I designed an incentive for salespeople to close deals in the first two months of the quarter by issuing bonuses for deals in those months. As a result, the next quarter became slightly more linear, and slightly smaller than anticipated—deals just moved from the third month to the first two of the following quarter.\",\"index\":754,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"When I ran a large engineering group at Netscape, I measured one of our engineering products on schedule, quality, and features. The team shipped a product with all the required features, on time and with very few bugs. Unfortunately, the product was mediocre, because none of the features were that great.\",\"index\":755,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"When I was at HP, we ran all the businesses by the numbers with extremely strict revenue and margin targets. Some divisions made their numbers, but did so by underfunding R&D. They dramatically weakened their long-term competitive position and set themselves up for future disaster.\",\"index\":756,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"In all three cases, managers got what we asked for, but not what we wanted. How did this happen? Let’s take a look.\",\"index\":757,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**FLATTENING OUT THE HOCKEY STICK: THE WRONG GOAL**\",\"index\":758,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"In retrospect, I should never have asked the team to flatten the quarters. If that is what I wanted, I had to be willing to—at least temporarily—accept smaller quarters. We had a fixed number of salespeople who were maximizing the size of each quarter. In order to deliver linear quarters, they had to modify their behavior and adjust their priorities. Unfortunately, I liked the old priority of maximizing revenue better.\",\"index\":759,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Given the situation, I was actually pretty lucky. Sun Tzu, in his classic work *The Art of War*, warns that giving the team a task that it cannot possibly perform is called crippling the army. In my case, I did not cripple the team, but I screwed up my priorities. The right thing to do would have been to make the hard decision up front, about what was more important, maximizing each quarter or increasing predictability. The instruction only made sense if the answer was the second one.\",\"index\":760,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"In retrospect, asking the team to flatten the quarters was a mistake on my part. I should have been prepared to temporarily accept smaller quarters if I truly wanted to achieve this. Our fixed number of salespeople were focused on maximizing the size of each quarter, and altering their behavior to deliver linear quarters required a shift in priorities. Unfortunately, I preferred the old priority of maximizing revenue. Reflecting on Sun Tzu's *The Art of War*, which warns against assigning unachievable tasks to the team, I realize I didn't cripple the team, but I did mismanage my priorities. I should have made the tough decision upfront about what was more important: maximizing each quarter or increasing predictability. The instruction only made sense if increasing predictability was the priority.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**FOCUSING TOO MUCH ON THE NUMBERS**\",\"index\":761,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"In the second example, I managed the team to a set of numbers that did not fully capture what I wanted. I wanted a great product that customers would love with high quality and on time—in that order.\",\"index\":762,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Unfortunately, the metrics that I set did not capture those priorities. At a basic level, metrics are incentives. By measuring quality, features, and schedule and discussing them at every staff meeting, my people focused intensely on those metrics to the exclusion of other goals. The metrics did not describe the real goals and I distracted the team as a result.\",\"index\":763,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Interestingly, I see this same problem play out in many consumer Internet startups. I often see teams that maniacally focus on their metrics around customer acquisition and retention. This usually works well for customer acquisition, but not so well for retention. Why?\",\"index\":764,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"For many products, metrics often describe the customer acquisition goal in enough detail to provide sufficient management guidance. In contrast, the metrics for customer retention do not provide enough color to be a complete management tool. As a result, many young companies overemphasize retention metrics and do not spend enough time going deep enough on the actual user experience. This generally results in a frantic numbers chase that does not end in a great product. It’s important to supplement a great product vision with a strong discipline around the metrics, but if you substitute metrics for product vision, you will not get what you want.\",\"index\":765,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"In my experience managing a team, I focused on metrics that did not align with my real priorities: creating a high-quality product that customers love and delivering it on time. Metrics act as incentives, and by emphasizing quality, features, and schedule in every staff meeting, my team became fixated on those numbers rather than our actual goals. This issue is common in many consumer Internet startups, where teams often focus excessively on metrics for customer acquisition and retention. While these metrics can effectively guide customer acquisition, they fall short in capturing customer retention's nuances, leading to an unhealthy obsession with numbers at the expense of improving the user experience. To build a great product, it's crucial to balance a clear product vision with disciplined metrics, but never let the metrics replace the vision.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**MANAGING STRICTLY BY NUMBERS IS LIKE PAINTING BY NUMBERS**\",\"index\":766,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Some things that you want to encourage will be quantifiable, and some will not. If you report on the quantitative goals and ignore the qualitative ones, you won’t get the qualitative goals, which may be the most important ones. Management purely by numbers is sort of like painting by numbers—it’s strictly for amateurs.\",\"index\":767,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"At HP, the company wanted high earnings now and in the future. By focusing entirely on the numbers, HP got them now by sacrificing the future.\",\"index\":768,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Note that there were many numbers as well as more qualitative goals that would have helped:\",\"index\":769,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"* Was our competitive win rate increasing or declining?\\n\\n* Was customer satisfaction rising or falling?\\n\\n* What did our own engineers think of the products?\",\"index\":770,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"By managing the organization as though it were a black box, some divisions at HP optimized the present at the expense of their downstream competitiveness. The company rewarded managers for achieving short-term objectives in a manner that was bad for the company. It would have been better to take into account the white box. The white box goes beyond the numbers and gets into how the organization produced the numbers. It penalizes managers who sacrifice the future for the short term and rewards those who invest in the future even if that investment cannot be easily measured.\",\"index\":771,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"Encouraging both quantifiable and qualitative goals is essential, as ignoring qualitative goals can undermine long-term success. At HP, a focus purely on immediate high earnings led to sacrificing future viability. Important metrics were overlooked, such as competitive win rates, customer satisfaction, and internal feedback from engineers, which could have provided a more balanced view of success. Managing with a \\\"black box\\\" approach, HP ultimately rewarded short-term gains at the expense of future competitiveness. Adopting a \\\"white box\\\" approach, which looks beyond numbers to understand how they were achieved, and rewarding managers who invest in the future, would have been a more sustainable strategy.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**CLOSING THOUGHT**\",\"index\":772,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"It is easy to see that there are many ways for leaders to be misinterpreted. To get things right, you must recognize that anything you measure automatically creates a set of employee behaviors. Once you determine the result you want, you need to test the description of the result against the employee behaviors that the description will likely create. Otherwise, the side-effect behaviors may be worse than the situation you were trying to fix.\",\"index\":773,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"\",\"index\":774,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\" \",\"index\":775,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"It's crucial for leaders to understand that any measurement they set can inadvertently shape employee behaviors. To ensure desired outcomes, first identify the specific result you want. Then, critically evaluate how your description of this result may influence employee actions. This step is essential to avoid unintended side-effect behaviors that could end up exacerbating the very issues you're aiming to resolve.\",\"type\":\"section\"}],\"summary\":\"In retrospect, asking the team to flatten the quarters was a mistake; I should have temporarily accepted smaller quarters for this goal. Our salespeople were fixed on maximizing quarterly sizes, and switching them to linear quarters required a priority shift that I failed to manage properly. Reflecting on Sun Tzu's *The Art of War*, which cautions against assigning unachievable tasks, I realize my mismanagement of priorities. I needed to decide upfront whether maximizing each quarter or increasing predictability was more important. In my management experience, I focused on metrics rather than the true priority: delivering a high-quality product on time. Misaligned metrics became incentives, causing the team to fixate on numbers instead of real goals—a common issue in startups overly focused on customer acquisition and retention metrics, which can detract from improving user experience. Achieving a balanced product vision requires disciplined metrics but without letting them override the vision itself. Encouraging qualitative and quantitative goals is crucial; ignoring qualitative goals can undermine long-term success, as seen with HP's emphasis on short-term gains over future viability. Leaders must understand that metrics shape employee behaviors, so it's vital to identify desired outcomes first and craft measurements carefully to avoid unintended consequences.\",\"type\":\"section\"}],\"summary\":\"At Loudcloud, I often found myself misquoted as saying things I didn’t, leading to unintended actions by the team. Similarly, at Opsware, our sales followed a severe \\\"hockey stick\\\" pattern, booking 90% of deals last-minute, making it tough for a public company to plan effectively. Attempting to reshape this by incentivizing early-quarter deals resulted in only slightly more linear revenues and lower-than-expected sales, moving the problem rather than solving it. At Netscape, focusing on schedule, quality, and features led to an on-time, bug-free product that was still mediocre because the features weren’t impressive. At HP, strict revenue and margin targets caused divisions to underfund R&D, weakening their long-term competitiveness. In all these instances, what managers asked for translated to what we got, but not what we truly wanted. Reflecting on these, I realized the importance of not just setting metrics but ensuring they align with the desired outcomes. Misaligned priorities and overemphasis on quantitative metrics often lead to short-term gains at the expense of long-term success. It is crucial to balance qualitative and quantitative goals to avoid unintended consequences and ensure a high-quality vision that enhances user experience and long-term viability.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**[MANAGEMENT DEBT]()**\",\"index\":776,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Thanks to Ward Cunningham, the computer programmer who designed the first wiki, the metaphor “technical debt” is now a well-understood concept. While you may be able to borrow time by writing quick and dirty code, you will eventually have to pay it back—with interest. Often this trade-off makes sense, but you will run into serious trouble if you fail to keep the trade-off in the front of your mind. There also exists a less understood parallel concept, which I will call *management debt*.\",\"index\":777,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Like technical debt, management debt is incurred when you make an expedient, short-term management decision with an expensive, long-term consequence. Like technical debt, the trade-off sometimes makes sense, but often does not. More important, if you incur the management debt without accounting for it, then you will eventually go management bankrupt.\",\"index\":778,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"Like technical debt, management debt comes in too many different forms to elaborate entirely, but a few salient examples will help explain the concept. Here are three of the more popular types among startups:\",\"index\":779,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"**1.** Putting two in the box\",\"index\":780,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"**2.** Overcompensating a key employee, because she gets another job offer\",\"index\":781,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"**3.** No performance management or employee feedback process\",\"index\":782,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"type\":\"clump\",\"summary\":\"Like technical debt, management debt comes in too many different forms to elaborate entirely, but a few salient examples will help explain the concept. Here are three of the more popular types among startups: \\n\\n **1.** Putting two in the box \\n\\n **2.** Overcompensating a key employee, because she gets another job offer \\n\\n **3.** No performance management or employee feedback process\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**PUTTING TWO IN THE BOX**\",\"index\":783,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"What do you do when you have two outstanding employees who logically both fit in the same place on the organizational chart? Perhaps you have a world-class architect who is running engineering, but she does not have the experience to scale the organization to the next level. You also have an outstanding operational person who is not great technically. You want to keep both in the company, but you only have one position. So you get the bright idea to put “two in the box” and take on a little management debt. The short-term benefits are clear: you keep both employees, you don’t have to develop either because they will theoretically help each other develop, and you instantly close the skill set gap. Unfortunately, you will pay for those benefits with interest and at a very high rate.\",\"index\":784,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"For starters, by doing this you will make every engineer’s job more difficult. If an engineer needs a decision made, which boss should she go to? If that boss decides, will the other boss be able to override it? If it’s a complex decision that requires a meeting, does she have to schedule both heads of engineering for the meeting? Who sets the direction for the organization? Will the direction actually get set if doing so requires a series of meetings?\",\"index\":785,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"In addition, you have removed all accountability. If schedules slip, who is accountable? If engineering throughput becomes uncompetitive, who is responsible? If the operational head is responsible for the schedule slip and the technical head is responsible for throughput, what happens if the operational head thrashes the engineers to make the schedule and kills throughput? How would you know that she did that? The really expensive part about both of these things is that they tend to get worse over time. In the very short term you might mitigate their effects with extra meetings or by attempting to carve up the job in a clear way. However, as things get busy, those once-clear lines will fade and the organization will degenerate. Eventually, you’ll either make a lump-sum payment by making the hard decision and putting one in the box or your engineering organization will suck forever.\",\"index\":786,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"When faced with the dilemma of having two outstanding employees suited for the same role, you might consider putting \\\"two in the box,\\\" essentially sharing the position. This approach offers short-term benefits: retaining both employees, avoiding the need to develop them further, and bridging skill set gaps immediately. However, this comes at a high cost, leading to confusion and inefficiency. Engineers will struggle with unclear decision-making channels and overlapping responsibilities, and accountability issues will arise with no one clearly in charge of schedules or performance. Over time, these problems will worsen, leading to organizational chaos. Eventually, you'll be forced to make a tough decision to put only one person in the role or risk long-term dysfunction in your engineering team.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**OVERCOMPENSATING A KEY EMPLOYEE BECAUSE SHE GETS ANOTHER JOB OFFER**\",\"index\":787,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"An excellent engineer decides to leave the company because she gets a better offer. For various reasons, you were undercompensating her, but the offer from the other company pays more than any engineer in your company and the engineer in question is not your best engineer. Still, she is working on a critical project and you cannot afford to lose her. So you match the offer. You save the project, but you pile on the debt.\",\"index\":788,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Here’s how the payment will come due. You probably think that your counteroffer was confidential because you’d sworn her to secrecy. Let me explain why it was not. She has friends in the company. When she got the offer from the other company, she consulted with her friends. One of her best friends advised her to take the offer. When she decided to stay, she had to explain to him why she disregarded his advice or else lose personal credibility. So she told him and swore him to secrecy. He agreed to honor the secret but was incensed that she had to threaten to quit in order to get a proper raise. Furthermore, he was furious that you overcompensated her. So he told the story to a few of his friends, but kept her name confidential to preserve the secret. And now everyone in engineering knows that the best way to get a raise is to generate an offer from another company and then threaten to quit. It’s going to take a while to pay off that debt.\",\"index\":789,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"An excellent engineer, though not your best, receives a higher-paying offer from another company and decides to leave. You had been undercompensating her, but to keep her on the critical project, you match the offer, even though it surpasses the pay of any engineer at your company. You think the counteroffer is confidential because she agreed to keep it secret, but she confides in a close friend for advice. This friend, upset by the circumstances, shares the story with others, maintaining her anonymity. Now, the entire engineering team knows the best way to get a raise is to secure an outside offer and threaten to quit. This will create lasting issues and take considerable time to resolve.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**NO PERFORMANCE MANAGEMENT OR EMPLOYEE FEEDBACK PROCESS**\",\"index\":790,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Your company now employs twenty-five people and you know that you should formalize the performance management process, but you don’t want to pay the price. You worry that doing so will make it feel like a “big company.” Moreover, you do not want your employees to be offended by the feedback, because you can’t afford to lose anyone right now. And people are happy, so why rock the boat? Why not take on a little management debt?\",\"index\":791,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"The first noticeable payments will be due when somebody performs below expectations:\",\"index\":792,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"CEO: “He was good when we hired him; what happened?”\",\"index\":793,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Manager: “He’s not doing the things that we need him to do.”\",\"index\":794,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"CEO: “Did we clearly tell him that?”\",\"index\":795,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Manager: “Maybe not clearly . . .”\",\"index\":796,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"type\":\"clump\",\"summary\":\"The first noticeable payments will be due when somebody performs below expectations: \\n\\n CEO: “He was good when we hired him; what happened?” \\n\\n Manager: “He’s not doing the things that we need him to do.” \\n\\n CEO: “Did we clearly tell him that?” \\n\\n Manager: “Maybe not clearly . . .”\"},{\"content\":\"However, the larger payment will be a silent tax. Companies execute well when everybody is on the same page and everybody is constantly improving. In a vacuum of feedback, there is almost no chance that your company will perform optimally across either dimension. Directions with no corrections will seem fuzzy and obtuse. People rarely improve weakness they are unaware of. The ultimate price you will pay for not giving feedback: systematically crappy company performance.\",\"index\":797,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"Your company now employs twenty-five people, and while you recognize the need to formalize the performance management process, you hesitate due to concerns about cost and creating a \\\"big company\\\" atmosphere. You also worry that employees might be offended by feedback, risking turnover when you can't afford to lose anyone. However, the real issue arises when someone underperforms: the CEO questions what happened, and the manager admits that expectations weren't clearly communicated. Eventually, the lack of feedback becomes a silent tax, hindering performance and continuous improvement. Without clear feedback, employees remain unaware of their weaknesses, preventing optimal company performance and resulting in systematically subpar results.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**IN THE END**\",\"index\":798,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Every really good, really experienced CEO I know shares one important characteristic: They tend to opt for the hard answer to organizational issues. If faced with giving everyone the same bonus to make things easy or with sharply rewarding performance and ruffling many feathers, they’ll ruffle the feathers. If given the choice of cutting a popular project today, because it’s not in the long-term plans or you’re keeping it around for morale purposes and to appear consistent, they’ll cut it today. Why? Because they’ve paid the price of management debt, and they would rather not do that again.\",\"index\":799,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"\",\"index\":800,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\" \",\"index\":801,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"Every exceptional, experienced CEO I know shares one crucial trait: they choose the tough solutions to organizational problems. When faced with the option of giving everyone the same bonus for the sake of simplicity or sharply rewarding performance and causing a stir, they’ll choose to ruffle feathers. If given the choice to cut a popular but short-sighted project today, or keep it for morale and consistency, they’ll cut it today. Why? They’ve experienced the cost of management debt and prefer to avoid it in the future.\",\"type\":\"section\"}],\"summary\":\"When faced with having two outstanding employees suited for the same role, \\\"two in the box\\\" might seem like a quick fix, retaining both talents and avoiding immediate skill gaps. However, this leads to confusion, inefficiency, and unclear accountability, eventually forcing a tough decision to maintain long-term functionality. Additionally, when an excellent yet underpaid engineer receives a higher offer and you match it to retain her, believing it's confidential, the news can leak and trigger a broader issue, with everyone pursuing outside offers for raises. Formalizing performance management in a growing company is crucial, despite concerns about cost and creating a \\\"big company\\\" atmosphere. Overlooked feedback leads to underperformance and unawareness of weaknesses, systematically dragging down company performance. Exceptional CEOs always opt for tough solutions, such as rewarding performance distinctively or cutting popular but ineffective projects, to avoid the hidden costs of management debt.\",\"type\":\"section\"}],\"summary\":\"Thanks to Ward Cunningham, the programmer who designed the first wiki, the concept of \\\"technical debt\\\" is well-known. While you can temporarily save time by writing quick code, you'll eventually need to address it, often at a higher cost. Similarly, there's the concept of *management debt*, where short-term managerial decisions lead to long-term consequences. If not managed carefully, this debt can lead to \\\"management bankruptcy.\\\" Examples include \\\"putting two in the box\\\" where two employees fill one role, resulting in inefficiency and unclear accountability, overcompensating a key employee to match an external offer, which can lead to company-wide pay discrepancies, and neglecting performance management, which causes underperformance and lack of awareness of weaknesses. Exceptional CEOs confront these issues head-on, ensuring sustainable growth and avoiding the pitfalls of management debt.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**[MANAGEMENT QUALITY ASSURANCE]()**\",\"index\":802,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Everyone in the technology industry seems to agree that people are paramount, yet nobody seems to be on the same page with what the people organization—human resources—should look like.\",\"index\":803,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"The problem is that when it comes to HR, most CEOs don’t really know what they want. In theory, they want a well-managed company with a great culture. Instinctively they know that an HR organization probably can’t deliver that. As a result, CEOs usually punt on the issue and implement something that’s suboptimal, if not worthless.\",\"index\":804,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Ironically one of the first things you learn when you run an engineering organization is that a good quality assurance organization cannot build a high-quality product, but it can tell you when the development team builds a low quality product. Similarly, a high quality human resources organization cannot make you a well-managed company with a great culture, but it can tell you when you and your managers are not getting the job done.\",\"index\":805,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**THE EMPLOYEE LIFE CYCLE**\",\"index\":806,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"The best way to approach management quality assurance is through the lens of the employee life cycle. From hire to retire, how good is your company? Is your management team world-class in all phases? How do you know?\",\"index\":807,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"A great HR organization will support, measure, and help improve your management team. Some of the questions they will help you answer:\",\"index\":808,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**Recruiting and Hiring**\",\"index\":809,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"* Do you sharply understand the skills and talents r