k's continuous innovation. Such mechanisms must resonate with core values, as seen with Square under Jack Dorsey, where the commitment to beautiful design outweighs frugality, unlike Amazon. Startups often try different tactics to stand out, but elements like yoga sessions or pets in cubicles, while offering benefits, don't define core values that sustain the business. True culture extends beyond perks to embody core values and vision. In *How to Evaluate CEOs* (page 235), I describe the CEO's role as knowing what to do and ensuring the company executes the vision, underscoring that a well-designed culture is vital for long-term alignment with objectives.\",\"type\":\"section\"}],\"summary\":\"Ask ten founders what company culture means and you'll get ten different answers—office design, employee screening, values, fun, alignment, like-minded folks, or even being cultlike. But what truly defines culture, and does it matter?\\n\\nFirst, any tech startup must create a product ten times better than existing solutions, corral the market swiftly to avoid being overshadowed by competitors, and only then will culture hold significance. If you don’t achieve these, culture won’t save you; there are many bankrupt companies lauded for their culture. So, why culture? It aids in hitting objectives, preserves core values as you scale, and ensures you want to remain in the environment you worked so hard to build.\\n\\nMy take on culture includes creating a work environment that distinguishes you from competitors, ensuring values like delighting customers or designing beautiful products stay intact, and hiring mission-aligned individuals. A strong culture germinates from founders’ behaviors, and emphasizing impactful cultural elements is critical. Jim Collins in *Built to Last* praised seemingly cult-like cultures for their effectiveness. It's about behavioral change; consider Jeff Bezos’s frugality at Amazon symbolized by door desks, or Marc and my punctuality fines at Andreessen Horowitz, or Zuckerberg’s Facebook ethos of *Move fast and break things*. These aren’t just quirks but core values in action.\\n\\nInstances like Square’s emphasis on design over frugality demonstrate how culture reflects essential principles. Yoga sessions and pets in offices are nice, but they don’t define a company. True culture goes beyond perks, embodying core values and vision. A CEO’s role, as detailed in *How to Evaluate CEOs*, involves ensuring the company knows what to do and executes its vision, affirming that a well-conceived culture is essential for long-term alignment and success.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**[TAKING THE MYSTERY OUT OF SCALING A COMPANY]()**\",\"index\":1024,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"If you want to build an important company, then at some point you have to scale. People in startup land often talk about the magic of how few people built the original Google or the original Facebook, but today’s Google employs twenty thousand people and today’s Facebook employs more than fifteen hundred people. So, if you want to do something that matters, then you are going to have to learn the black art of scaling a human organization.\",\"index\":1025,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"Often board members give entrepreneurs two bits of advice regarding scale:\",\"index\":1026,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"**1.** Get a mentor.\",\"index\":1027,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"**2.** Find some “been there, done that” executives who already know how to scale.\",\"index\":1028,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"type\":\"clump\",\"summary\":\"Often board members give entrepreneurs two bits of advice regarding scale: \\n\\n **1.** Get a mentor. \\n\\n **2.** Find some “been there, done that” executives who already know how to scale.\"},{\"content\":\"These answers, while fine as far as they go, have some important limitations. First, if you don’t know anything about scaling an organization, then it will be very difficult for you to evaluate people for that job. Imagine trying to find a killer engineer if you’d never written a single program. Second, many investor-board members don’t know anything about scaling a company, either, and can be suckers for people who have the experience but not the skills. If you’ve ever worked in a large organization, you know that there are plenty of people with experience running them but none of the requisite skills to run them well.\",\"index\":1029,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"This advice is still good, but the right way to pick both the best mentors and best employees is by first learning the basics; then you can apply the myriad of scaling techniques in the management literature depending on the context.\",\"index\":1030,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**THE BASIC IDEA: GIVE GROUND GRUDGINGLY**\",\"index\":1031,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"When an organization grows in size, things that were previously easy become difficult. Specifically, the following things that cause no trouble when you are small become big challenges as you grow:\",\"index\":1032,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"* Communication\\n\\n* Common knowledge\\n\\n* Decision making\",\"index\":1033,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"type\":\"clump\",\"summary\":\"When an organization grows in size, things that were previously easy become difficult. Specifically, the following things that cause no trouble when you are small become big challenges as you grow: \\n\\n * Communication\\n\\n* Common knowledge\\n\\n* Decision making\"},{\"content\":\"In order to get a clear understanding of the problem, let’s start with the boundary condition. Imagine a company of one employee. That employee writes and tests all the code, does all the marketing and sales, and manages herself. She has complete knowledge of everything in the company, makes all the decisions, needn’t communicate with anyone, and is totally aligned with herself. As the company grows, things will only get worse in each dimension.\",\"index\":1034,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"On the other hand, if the company doesn’t expand, then it will never be much of a company, so the challenge is to grow but degrade as slowly as possible.\",\"index\":1035,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"There is a great analogue to this concept in American football. An offensive lineman’s job is to protect the quarterback from onrushing defensive linemen. If the offensive lineman attempts to do this by holding his ground, the defensive lineman will easily run around him and crush the quarterback. As a result, offensive linemen are taught to lose the battle slowly or *to give ground grudgingly*. They are taught to back up and allow the defensive lineman to advance, but just a little at a time.\",\"index\":1036,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"When you scale an organization, you will also need to give ground grudgingly. Specialization, organizational structure, and process all complicate things and implementing them will feel like you are moving away from common knowledge and quality communication. It is very much like the offensive lineman taking a step backward. You will lose ground, but you will prevent your company from descending into chaos.\",\"index\":1037,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"As an organization grows, previously simple tasks become challenging, specifically regarding communication, common knowledge, and decision-making. Imagine a company with only one employee who handles everything independently, facing no communication issues and making all decisions alone. As the company expands, these dimensions become increasingly difficult to manage. However, not growing isn't an option if the company wants to thrive. The key is to grow while minimizing the degradation. This concept is akin to an offensive lineman in American football, who protects the quarterback by losing ground slowly and grudgingly, allowing defensive linemen to advance only slightly. Similarly, as you scale your organization, introducing specialization, organizational structure, and processes will feel like compromising, but it's essential to prevent descending into chaos.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**HOW TO DO IT**\",\"index\":1038,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"At the point when adding people into the company feels like more work than the work that you can offload to the new employees, the defensive lineman has run around you and you probably need to start giving ground grudgingly.\",\"index\":1039,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"At the point when adding people into the company feels like more work than the work that you can offload to the new employees, the defensive lineman has run around you and you probably need to start giving ground grudgingly.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**SPECIALIZATION**\",\"index\":1040,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"The first scale technique to implement is specialization. In startups, everybody starts out as a jack-of-all-trades. For example, engineers write code, manage the build system, test the product, and, increasingly, deploy it and operate it. This works well in the beginning because everybody knows everything and the need to communicate is minimized; there are no complicated handoffs, because there is nobody to hand anything to. As the company grows, it becomes increasingly difficult to add new engineers, because the learning curve starts to get super-steep. Getting a new engineer up to speed starts to become more difficult than doing the work yourself. At this point, you need to specialize.\",\"index\":1041,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"By dedicating people and teams to such tasks as the build environment, the test environment, and operations, you will create some complexity—handoffs across groups, potentially conflicting agendas, and specialized rather than common knowledge. In order to mitigate these issues, you will need to consider other scale techniques like *organizational design* and *process*.\",\"index\":1042,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"The first scale technique to implement is specialization. Initially, in startups, everyone acts as a jack-of-all-trades, with engineers writing code, managing the build system, testing, deploying, and operating the product. This works well in the beginning as it minimizes communication needs and eliminates handoffs. However, as the company grows, onboarding new engineers becomes challenging due to a steep learning curve, making it harder than doing the work yourself. At this stage, specialization becomes necessary. By dedicating teams to tasks like the build environment, test environment, and operations, you introduce complexity such as handoffs, conflicting agendas, and specialized knowledge. To address these issues, other scale techniques like organizational design and process must be considered.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**ORGANIZATIONAL DESIGN**\",\"index\":1043,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"The first rule of organizational design is that all organizational designs are bad. With any design, you will optimize communication among some parts of the organization at the expense of other parts. For example, if you put product management in the engineering organization, you will optimize communication between product management and engineering at the expense of communication between product management and marketing. As a result, as soon as you roll out the new organization, people will find fault with it and they will be right.\",\"index\":1044,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Nonetheless, at some point the monolithic design of one huge organization runs out of gas and you will need to split things into smaller subgroups. At the most basic level, you’ll want to consider giving the groups that you’ve specialized their own managers as they grow. You may want a QA manager, for example. After that, things become more complex. Do client engineering and server engineering have their own groups or do you organize by use cases and include all technical components? When you get really big, you’ll need to decide whether to organize the entire company around functions (for example, sales, marketing, product management, engineering) or around missions—self-contained business units that contain multiple functions.\",\"index\":1045,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Your goal is to choose the least of all evils. Think of the organizational design as the communications architecture for your company. If you want people to communicate, the best way to accomplish that is to make them report to the same manager. By contrast, the further away people are in the organizational chart, the less they will communicate. The organizational design is also the architecture for how the company communicates with the outside world. For example, you might want to organize your sales force by product to maximize communication with the relevant product groups and maximize the product competency of the sales force. If you do that, then you will do so at the expense of simplicity for customers who buy multiple products and will now have to deal with multiple salespeople.\",\"index\":1046,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"With this in mind, here are the basic steps to organizational design:\",\"index\":1047,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"**1.** *Figure out what needs to be communicated.* Start by listing the most important knowledge and who needs to have it. For example, knowledge of the product architecture must be understood by engineering, QA, product management, marketing, and sales.\",\"index\":1048,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"**2.** *Figure out what needs to be decided.* Consider the types of decisions that must get made on a frequent basis: feature selection, architectural decisions, how to resolve support issues. How can you design the organization to put the maximum number of decisions under the domain of a designated manager?\",\"index\":1049,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"**3.** *Prioritize the most important communication and decision paths.* Is it more important for product managers to understand the product architecture or the market? Is it more important for engineers to understand the customer or the architecture? Keep in mind that these priorities will be based on today’s situation. If the situation changes, then you can reorganize.\",\"index\":1050,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"**4.** *Decide who’s going to run each group.* Notice that this is the fourth step, not the first. You want to optimize the organization for the people—for the people doing the work—not for the managers. Most large mistakes in organizational design come from putting the individual ambitions of the people at the top of the organization ahead of the communication paths for the people at the bottom of the organization. Making this step four will upset your managers, but they will get over it.\",\"index\":1051,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"**5.** *Identify the paths that you did not optimize.* As important as picking the communication paths that you will optimize is identifying the ones that you will not. Just because you deprioritized them doesn’t mean they are unimportant. If you ignore them entirely, they will surely come back to bite you.\",\"index\":1052,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"**6.** *Build a plan for mitigating the issues identified in step five.* Once you’ve identified the likely issues, you will know the processes you will need to build to patch the impending cross-organizational challenges.\",\"index\":1053,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"type\":\"clump\",\"summary\":\"With this in mind, here are the basic steps to organizational design: \\n\\n **1.** *Figure out what needs to be communicated.* Start by listing the most important knowledge and who needs to have it. For example, knowledge of the product architecture must be understood by engineering, QA, product management, marketing, and sales. \\n\\n **2.** *Figure out what needs to be decided.* Consider the types of decisions that must get made on a frequent basis: feature selection, architectural decisions, how to resolve support issues. How can you design the organization to put the maximum number of decisions under the domain of a designated manager? \\n\\n **3.** *Prioritize the most important communication and decision paths.* Is it more important for product managers to understand the product architecture or the market? Is it more important for engineers to understand the customer or the architecture? Keep in mind that these priorities will be based on today’s situation. If the situation changes, then you can reorganize. \\n\\n **4.** *Decide who’s going to run each group.* Notice that this is the fourth step, not the first. You want to optimize the organization for the people—for the people doing the work—not for the managers. Most large mistakes in organizational design come from putting the individual ambitions of the people at the top of the organization ahead of the communication paths for the people at the bottom of the organization. Making this step four will upset your managers, but they will get over it. \\n\\n **5.** *Identify the paths that you did not optimize.* As important as picking the communication paths that you will optimize is identifying the ones that you will not. Just because you deprioritized them doesn’t mean they are unimportant. If you ignore them entirely, they will surely come back to bite you. \\n\\n **6.** *Build a plan for mitigating the issues identified in step five.* Once you’ve identified the likely issues, you will know the processes you will need to build to patch the impending cross-organizational challenges.\"},{\"content\":\"These six steps should get you pretty far. When we examine advanced organizational design, we’ll also need to consider trade-offs such as speed versus cost, how to roll out organizational changes, and how often you should reorganize.\",\"index\":1054,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"The first rule of organizational design is that all designs are inherently flawed, optimizing communication in some areas at the expense of others. For instance, placing product management within engineering improves communication between these departments but hampers their interaction with marketing. Despite inevitable faults, a monolithic design becomes impractical over time, necessitating a split into smaller subgroups with specialized managers. Complex decisions arise, like whether to separate client and server engineering or organize by use cases. As the company grows, you must decide between structuring around functions (sales, marketing, engineering) or missions (self-contained business units). Aim for the least damaging design by considering it as the communication architecture of your company, where proximity in the organizational chart fosters better communication. Understand that prioritizing certain communication paths will inevitably lead to trade-offs. To navigate these complexities, follow these steps: ascertain essential communications, determine decision-making needs, prioritize key communication and decision paths, assign capable group leaders, identify non-optimized paths, and develop mitigation plans for these paths. By adhering to these steps, you'll navigate the inherent drawbacks of organizational design, balancing speed, cost, and adaptability.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**PROCESS**\",\"index\":1055,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"The purpose of process is communication. If there are five people in your company, you don’t need process, because you can just talk to each other. You can hand off tasks with a perfect understanding of what’s expected, you pass important information from one person to another, and you can maintain high-quality transactions with no bureaucratic overhead. With four thousand people, communication becomes more difficult. Ad hoc, point-to-point communication no longer works. You need something more robust—a communication bus or, to use the conventional term for human communication buses, a process.\",\"index\":1056,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"A process is a formal, well-structured communication vehicle. It can be a heavily engineered Six Sigma process or it can be a well-structured regular meeting. The size of the process should be scaled up or down to meet the needs of the communication challenge that it facilitates.\",\"index\":1057,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"When communication in an organization spans across organizational boundaries, processes will help ensure that the communication happens and that it happens with quality. If you are looking for the first process to implement in your company, consider the interview process. It usually runs across organizational boundaries (the hiring group, human resources—or wherever the recruiter lives, and supporting groups), involves people from outside the company (the candidate), and is critically important to the success of the company.\",\"index\":1058,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Who should design a process? The people who are already doing the work in an ad hoc manner. They know what needs to be communicated and to whom. Naturally they will be the right group to formalize the existing process and make it scalable.\",\"index\":1059,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"When should you start implementing processes? While that varies depending on your situation, keep in mind that it’s much easier to add new people to old processes than new processes to old people. Formalize what you are doing to make it easy to onboard new people.\",\"index\":1060,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"Much has been written about process design, so I won’t repeat that here. I have found the “The Basics of Production,” the first chapter of Andy Grove’s *High Output Management*, to be particularly helpful. For new companies, here are a few things to keep in mind:\",\"index\":1061,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"* *Focus on the output first.* What should the process produce? In the case of the interview process, an outstanding employee. If that’s the goal, what’s the process to get there?\\n\\n* *Figure out how you’ll know if you are getting what you want at each step.* Are you getting enough candidates? Are you getting the right candidates? Will your interview process find the right person for the job? Once you select the person, will they accept the job? Once they accept the job, will they become productive? Once they become productive, will they stay with your company? How will you measure each step?\\n\\n* *Engineer accountability into the system.* Which organization and which individual is responsible for each step? What can you do to increase the visibility of their performance?\",\"index\":1062,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"type\":\"clump\",\"summary\":\"Much has been written about process design, so I won’t repeat that here. I have found the “The Basics of Production,” the first chapter of Andy Grove’s *High Output Management*, to be particularly helpful. For new companies, here are a few things to keep in mind: \\n\\n * *Focus on the output first.* What should the process produce? In the case of the interview process, an outstanding employee. If that’s the goal, what’s the process to get there?\\n\\n* *Figure out how you’ll know if you are getting what you want at each step.* Are you getting enough candidates? Are you getting the right candidates? Will your interview process find the right person for the job? Once you select the person, will they accept the job? Once they accept the job, will they become productive? Once they become productive, will they stay with your company? How will you measure each step?\\n\\n* *Engineer accountability into the system.* Which organization and which individual is responsible for each step? What can you do to increase the visibility of their performance?\"}],\"summary\":\"The primary purpose of process is to facilitate communication. In a small company with just five people, direct conversation suffices to coordinate tasks and share information. However, as the company grows to four thousand people, this informal method becomes impractical, necessitating a more robust system—a formal process. Processes serve as structured communication vehicles and can range from complex Six Sigma methodologies to regular, well-structured meetings, scalable to the communication needs they address. Implementing processes across organizational boundaries ensures effective and quality communication. The interview process is a prime example, involving multiple organizational parts and external candidates, and is crucial for company success. The best designers of these processes are those already handling the tasks informally, as they understand the necessary communications. Implementing processes early helps streamline new hires into existing systems. A useful reference is Andy Grove’s *High Output Management*, particularly focusing on producing desired outcomes, monitoring steps for success, and incorporating accountability. For emerging companies, it's essential to concentrate on output, measure each step's effectiveness, and assign clear responsibilities to enhance transparency and performance.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**FINAL THOUGHT**\",\"index\":1063,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"The process of scaling a company is not unlike the process of scaling a product. Different sizes of company impose different requirements on the company’s architecture. If you address those requirements too early, your company will seem heavy and sluggish. If you address those requirements too late, your company may melt down under the pressure. Be mindful of your company’s true growth rate as you add architectural components. It’s good to anticipate growth, but it’s bad to overanticipate growth.\",\"index\":1064,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"\",\"index\":1065,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\" \",\"index\":1066,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"Scaling a company mirrors scaling a product, requiring different architectures at various stages. Tackling these needs prematurely can make your company cumbersome, while delaying can lead to breakdowns under pressure. Stay attuned to your company's actual growth, striking a balance between anticipating future needs and avoiding over-preparation.\",\"type\":\"section\"}],\"summary\":\"As an organization grows, tasks that were once simple become complex, especially in communication, shared knowledge, and decision-making. Initially, a single employee faces no communication issues and makes solo decisions, but with expansion, these aspects become more challenging to manage. Growth is essential for thriving, and the key lies in minimizing the degradation during this expansion, akin to an offensive lineman in American football who loses ground slowly and grudgingly. When adding new employees feels more cumbersome than beneficial, it's time to introduce specialization, organizational design, and processes to prevent chaos. Initially, everyone in a startup may serve as a jack-of-all-trades, but as the size increases, specialization is necessary despite introducing complexity. Organizational design is inherently flawed and requires balancing communication priorities, while process implementation ensures robust, scalable communication. Processes, ranging from simple structured meetings to complex methodologies, facilitate effective communication across expanding teams. Essentially, scaling an organization mirrors scaling a product; both need appropriate architectures at different growth stages. Striking a balance between anticipating future needs and avoiding over-preparation is crucial for sustainable growth.\",\"type\":\"section\"}],\"summary\":\"If you want to build an impactful company, scaling is crucial. While it's inspiring how few people initially built giants like Google and Facebook, these companies now employ thousands. To scale effectively, you must master the complex art of growing a human organization. Common board advice includes getting a mentor and hiring experienced executives, but these suggestions have limitations. Without understanding scaling, you can't properly evaluate candidates for these roles, and many investor-board members lack scaling expertise themselves. Therefore, it's essential to first learn the basics of scaling. As organizations grow, simple tasks become complex, particularly in communication and decision-making. Initially, communication is straightforward and decisions are individual, but expansion introduces challenges. Growth is necessary, and minimizing operational degradation is key, much like a disciplined offensive lineman in football. When adding employees feels more burdensome than beneficial, it's time to incorporate specialization, organizational design, and processes to maintain order. Startups initially operate with generalists, but specialization becomes vital as they grow, despite its complexities. Organizational design requires balancing communication priorities, while processes ensure scalable communication, ranging from structured meetings to complex methodologies. Scaling an organization is akin to scaling a product, needing appropriate architectures at different stages of growth. The crucial balance lies in foreseeing future needs without over-preparing, fostering sustainable growth.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**[THE SCALE ANTICIPATION FALLACY]()**\",\"index\":1067,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"The other day I was talking to a couple of friends of mine, one a VC and the other a CEO. During the meeting, we discussed one of the executives at the CEO’s company. The executive in question performs exceptionally but lacks experience managing at larger scale. My friend the VC innocently advised the CEO to carefully consider whether the executive would scale to meet the company’s needs in the future. I responded swiftly, aggressively, and loudly, saying, “That’s a horrible idea and makes no sense at all.” Both of my friends were startled at my outburst. Normally I am disciplined enough to refrain from letting my feelings pass straight through my mouth without stopping at my brain for review. Why the outburst? Here is my answer.\",\"index\":1068,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"As CEO, you must constantly evaluate all the members of your team. However, evaluating people against the future needs of the company based on a theoretical view of how they will perform is counterproductive, for the following reasons:\",\"index\":1069,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"* *Managing at scale is a learned skill rather than a natural ability.* Nobody comes out of the womb knowing how to manage a thousand people. Everybody learns at some point.\\n\\n* *It’s nearly impossible to make the judgment in advance.* How do you tell in advance if an executive can scale? Was it obvious that Bill Gates would learn how to scale when he was a Harvard dropout? How do you go about making that decision?\\n\\n* *The act of judging people in advance will retard their development.* If you make a judgment that someone is incapable of doing something such as running a larger organization, will it make sense to teach them those skills or even point out the anticipated deficiencies? Probably not. You’ve already decided they can’t do it.\\n\\n* *Hiring scalable execs too early is a bad mistake.* There is no such thing as a great executive. There is only a great executive for a specific company at a specific point in time. Mark Zuckerberg is a phenomenal CEO for Facebook. He would not be a good CEO for Oracle. Similarly, Larry Ellison does a terrific job at Oracle but he would not be the right person to manage Facebook. If you judge your team in advance and have a high sense of urgency, you will bring in executives who can manage at high scale in advance of needing them. Unfortunately, you will probably ignore their ability to do the job for the next twelve months, which is the only relevant measure. As a result, you will swap out good executives for worse ones.\\n\\n* *You still have to make the judgment at the actual point in time when you hit the higher level of scale.* Even if you avoid the trap of hiring a scalable executive too early or retarding the new executive’s development, you still haven’t actually bought yourself anything by making the prejudgment. Regardless of what you decided at point in time A, you still have to evaluate the situation with far better data at point in time B.\\n\\n* *It’s no way to live your life or run an organization.* Deciding (with woefully incomplete data) that someone who works their butt off, does a terrific job, and loyally contributes to your mission won’t be with you three years from now takes you to a dark place. It’s a place of information hiding, dishonesty, and stilted communication. It’s a place where prejudice substitutes for judgment. It’s a place where judgment replaces teaching. It’s a place where teamwork becomes internal warfare. Don’t go there.\\\\\\n        So, if you don’t prejudge people’s ability to scale, how do you make the judgment? You should evaluate your team at least once a quarter on all dimensions. Two keys can help you avoid the scale anticipation trap:\\n\\n* *Don’t separate scale from the rest of the evaluation.* The relevant question isn’t whether an executive can scale; it’s whether the executive can do the job at the current scale. You should evaluate holistically and this will prevent you from separating out scale, which often leads to an unwise prediction of future performance.\\n\\n* *Make the judgment on a relative rather than an absolute scale.* Asking yourself whether an executive is great can be extremely difficult to answer. A better question: For this company at this exact point in time, does there exist an executive who I can hire who will be better? If my biggest competitor hires that person, how will that impact our ability to win?\\\\\\n       Predicting whether an executive can scale corrupts your ability to manage, is unfair, and doesn’t work.\",\"index\":1070,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"I recently had a spirited debate with friends, one a VC and the other a CEO, about an executive at the CEO’s company. The executive excels but lacks experience managing on a larger scale. The VC suggested evaluating the executive's potential to scale with the company, which prompted a vocal outburst from me. I believe this approach is flawed for several reasons. Managing at scale is a learned skill, not an inherent trait, making it almost impossible to judge someone’s future scaling capabilities accurately. Prejudging can hinder their development, and bringing in scalable execs prematurely might lead to swapping out good executives unnecessarily. Evaluating team members should focus on their current performance rather than speculative future abilities. As a CEO, one should regularly evaluate the team holistically and on a relative basis to avoid the pitfalls of scaling anticipation. This method ensures fair management and effective team development without resorting to unproductive prejudgment.\",\"type\":\"section\"}],\"summary\":\"In all my years in business, corporate politics is a persistent challenge often stemming from the CEO's actions, even if unintentional. Rewarding behaviors not directly tied to business performance can encourage political maneuvering, so CEOs must align hiring, performance evaluations, and compensation strictly with the company's success. A company's success hinges on senior managers optimizing for company success (global optimization) rather than personal gain (local optimization). Titles can foster collaboration if managed well but can lead to the Peter Principle and the \\\"Law of Crappy People\\\" if mismanaged. When hiring senior executives, prioritize specific expertise and ensure cultural fit to balance the positive impact on the company. One-on-ones are vital for essential feedback and upward information flow, solidifying communication architecture within the company. Culture matters as it impacts achieving objectives and preserving core values, distilled from leader behaviors and values. Scaling a company requires mastering organizational growth, balancing specialization, and maintaining communication efficacy. Lastly, evaluating team members should focus on current performance and regular holistic assessments to avoid unproductive prejudgment about future scalability.\",\"type\":\"section\"}],\"summary\":\"During a staff meeting in the Loudcloud/Opsware days, an employee raised concerns about excessive profanity in the workplace. As the main offender, I faced the dilemma squarely, recognizing that while the tech industry's culture often tolerates such language, banning it outright would be unrealistic and possibly limit our talent pool. Instead, I clarified that profanity was allowed but must not be used to intimidate or harass, which eliminated complaints and kept our environment comfortable and productive. This clarity created a good work environment and maintained low attrition. Essentially, a company’s best policies are those the CEO can follow. As the company grows, necessary changes must be embraced to keep it from falling apart. Corporate politics, often stemming from a CEO's actions, can be mitigated by aligning hiring, performance evaluations, and compensation with company success. Senior managers should prioritize the company's success over personal gain. Titles can foster collaboration but must be managed to avoid the Peter Principle and the \\\"Law of Crappy People.\\\" When hiring senior executives, focus on expertise and cultural fit. One-on-ones are vital for feedback and effective communication. Company culture, shaped by leader behaviors and values, is crucial in achieving objectives and preserving core values. Scaling a company requires balance between specialization and effective communication, and team evaluations should focus on current performance with regular holistic assessments to avoid unproductive prejudgment.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**[— CHAPTER 7 —]()**\",\"index\":1071,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"**[HOW TO LEAD EVEN WHEN YOU DON’T KNOW WHERE YOU ARE GOING]()**\",\"index\":1072,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"type\":\"clump\",\"summary\":\"**[— CHAPTER 7 —]()** \\n\\n **[HOW TO LEAD EVEN WHEN YOU DON’T KNOW WHERE YOU ARE GOING]()**\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"“This for every ghetto in the hood\",\"ind