\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"By far the most difficult skill I learned as CEO was the ability to manage my own psychology. Organizational design, process design, metrics, hiring, and firing were all relatively straightforward skills to master compared with keeping my mind in check. I thought I was tough going into it, but I wasn’t tough. I was soft.\",\"index\":1095,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Over the years, I’ve spoken to hundreds of CEOs, all with the same experience. Nonetheless, very few people talk about it and I have never read anything on the topic. It’s like the fight club of management: The first rule of the CEO psychological meltdown is don’t talk about the psychological meltdown.\",\"index\":1096,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"At the risk of violating the sacred rule, I will attempt to describe the condition and prescribe some techniques that helped me. In the end, this is the most personal and important battle that any CEO will face.\",\"index\":1097,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**IF I’M DOING A GOOD JOB, WHY DO I FEEL SO BAD?**\",\"index\":1098,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Generally, someone doesn’t become a CEO unless she has a high sense of purpose and cares deeply about the work she does. In addition, a CEO must be accomplished enough or smart enough that people will want to work for her. Nobody sets out to be a bad CEO, run a dysfunctional organization, or create a massive bureaucracy that grinds her company to a screeching halt. Yet no CEO ever has a smooth path to a great company. Along the way, many things go wrong and all of them could have and should have been avoided.\",\"index\":1099,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"The first problem is that everybody learns to be a CEO by being a CEO. No training as a manager, general manager, or in any other job actually prepares you to run a company. The only thing that prepares you to run a company is running a company. This means that you will face a broad set of things that you don’t know how to do that require skills you don’t have. Nevertheless, everybody will expect you to know how to do them, because, well, you are the CEO. I remember when I first became CEO, an investor asked me to send him the “cap table.” I had a vague idea of what he meant, but I didn’t actually know what the format was supposed to look like or what should be included or excluded. It was a silly little thing and I had much bigger things to worry about, but everything is hard when you don’t actually know what you are doing. I wasted quite a bit of time sweating over that stupid spreadsheet.\",\"index\":1100,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Even if you know what you are doing, things go wrong. Things go wrong because building a multifaceted human organization to compete and win in a dynamic, highly competitive market turns out to be really hard. If CEOs were graded on a curve, the mean on the test would be 22 out of 100. This kind of mean can be psychologically challenging for a straight-A student. It is particularly challenging because nobody tells you that the mean is 22.\",\"index\":1101,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"If you manage a team of ten people, it’s quite possible to do so with very few mistakes or bad behaviors. If you manage an organization of one thousand people, it is quite impossible. At a certain size, your company will do things that are so bad that you never imagined that you’d be associated with that kind of incompetence. Seeing people fritter away money, waste each other’s time, and do sloppy work can make you feel bad. If you are the CEO, it may well make you sick.\",\"index\":1102,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"And to rub salt into the wound and make matters worse, it’s your fault.\",\"index\":1103,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"Becoming a CEO requires a deep sense of purpose and a passion for the work, along with the intelligence or accomplishments to inspire others to follow. No one aims to be a poor CEO or run a dysfunctional organization, yet the journey to building a successful company is fraught with unavoidable challenges and mistakes. The unique challenge is that you only learn to be a CEO by actually being one, which means navigating situations and tasks you’ve never encountered before, all while everyone expects you to know exactly what to do. For example, when I first became a CEO, I struggled with something as simple as preparing a “cap table” for an investor because I didn’t know what it should include. Running a company involves dealing with a broad range of unknowns and inevitable errors because running a complex human organization in a competitive market is inherently difficult. Managing larger teams only compounds these challenges, leading to mistakes and inefficiencies that can be demoralizing. Moreover, as CEO, you bear the responsibility for everything that goes wrong, amplifying the psychological burden of the role.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**NOBODY TO BLAME**\",\"index\":1104,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"“You can’t blame Jazz musicians\",\"index\":1105,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"or David Stern with his NBA fashion issues.”\",\"index\":1106,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"**—NAS, “HIP HOP IS DEAD”**\",\"index\":1107,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"type\":\"clump\",\"summary\":\"“You can’t blame Jazz musicians \\n\\n or David Stern with his NBA fashion issues.” \\n\\n **—NAS, “HIP HOP IS DEAD”**\"},{\"content\":\"When people in my company would complain about one thing or another being broken, such as the expense reporting process, I would joke that it was all my fault. The joke was funny, because it wasn’t really a joke. Every problem in the company was indeed my fault. As the founding CEO, every hire and every decision that the company ever made happened under my direction. Unlike a hired gun who comes in and blames all of the problems on the prior regime, there was literally nobody for me to blame.\",\"index\":1108,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"If someone was promoted for all the wrong reasons, that was my fault. If we missed the quarterly earnings target, that was my fault. If a great engineer quit, that was my fault. If the sales team made unreasonable demands on the product organization, that was my fault. If the product had too many bugs, that was my fault. It kind of sucked to be me.\",\"index\":1109,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Being responsible for everything and getting a 22 on the test starts to weigh on your consciousness.\",\"index\":1110,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"When people in my company complained about issues such as the expense reporting process, I would joke that it was all my fault. The humor lay in its truth. As the founding CEO, every hire and every decision fell to me, so every problem was indeed my responsibility. Unlike a hired executive who can blame predecessors, I had no one else to blame. Whether it was a mispromotion, missing quarterly earnings, losing a great engineer, unreasonable demands from the sales team, or a buggy product, it was all my fault. It kind of sucked to be me. Bearing responsibility for everything and facing continuous scrutiny starts to weigh on your consciousness.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**TOO MUCH BROKEN STUFF**\",\"index\":1111,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"Given this stress, CEOs often make one of the following two mistakes:\",\"index\":1112,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"**1.** They take things too personally.\",\"index\":1113,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"**2.** They do not take things personally enough.\",\"index\":1114,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"type\":\"clump\",\"summary\":\"Given this stress, CEOs often make one of the following two mistakes: \\n\\n **1.** They take things too personally. \\n\\n **2.** They do not take things personally enough.\"},{\"content\":\"In the first scenario, the CEO takes every issue incredibly seriously and personally and urgently moves to fix it. Given the volume of the issues, this motion usually results in one of two scenarios. If the CEO is outwardly focused, she ends up terrorizing the team to the point where nobody wants to work at the company anymore. If the CEO is inwardly focused, she ends up feeling so sick from all the problems that she can barely make it to work in the morning.\",\"index\":1115,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"In the second scenario, in order to dampen the pain of the rolling disaster that is the company, the CEO takes a Pollyannaish attitude: It’s not so bad. In this view, none of the problems is actually that bad and they needn’t be dealt with urgently. By rationalizing away the issues, the CEO feels better about herself. The problem is that she doesn’t actually fix any of the problems and the employees eventually become quite frustrated that the chief executive keeps ignoring the most basic problems and conflicts. Ultimately, the company turns to crap.\",\"index\":1116,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Ideally, the CEO will be urgent yet not insane. She will move aggressively and decisively without feeling emotionally culpable. If she can separate the importance of the issues from how she feels about them, she will avoid demonizing her employees or herself.\",\"index\":1117,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"CEOs under stress often fall into one of two traps: taking things too personally or not personally enough. In the first scenario, CEOs who take everything seriously risk either terrorizing their team or becoming so overwhelmed that they can hardly function. Outwardly focused CEOs may create a toxic work environment, while inwardly focused ones may become paralyzed by stress. In the second scenario, to avoid constant anxiety, some CEOs adopt a Pollyannaish attitude, downplaying issues and failing to address them, leading to employee frustration and the eventual decline of the company. The ideal CEO balances urgency with sanity, addressing problems decisively without emotional turmoil, thereby avoiding the pitfalls of both overreacting and underreacting.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**IT’S A LONELY JOB**\",\"index\":1118,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"In your darkest moments as CEO, discussing fundamental questions about the viability of your company with your employees can have obvious negative consequences. On the other hand, talking to your board and outside advisers can be fruitless. The knowledge gap between you and them is so vast that you cannot actually bring them fully up to speed in a manner that’s useful in making the decision. You are all alone.\",\"index\":1119,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"At Loudcloud, when the dot-com bubble burst and subsequently sent most of our customers into bankruptcy, it crippled our business and devastated our balance sheet. Or rather, that was one interpretation. Another interpretation, and necessarily the official story for the company, was that we still had plenty of money in the bank and were signing up traditional enterprise customers at an impressive rate. Which interpretation was closer to the truth? In the absence of someone to talk to, that’s a question that I asked myself about three thousand times. (As an aside, asking oneself anything three thousand times turns out to be a bad idea.) In this case, I had two specific difficult questions:\",\"index\":1120,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"**1.** What if the official interpretation was wrong? What if I was misleading everyone from investors to employees? In that case, I should be removed from my position immediately.\",\"index\":1121,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"**2.** What if the official interpretation was right? What if I was grinding my brain into sawdust for no reason at all? What if I was taking the company off track by questioning my own direction? In that case, I should be removed from my position immediately.\",\"index\":1122,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"type\":\"clump\",\"summary\":\"At Loudcloud, when the dot-com bubble burst and subsequently sent most of our customers into bankruptcy, it crippled our business and devastated our balance sheet. Or rather, that was one interpretation. Another interpretation, and necessarily the official story for the company, was that we still had plenty of money in the bank and were signing up traditional enterprise customers at an impressive rate. Which interpretation was closer to the truth? In the absence of someone to talk to, that’s a question that I asked myself about three thousand times. (As an aside, asking oneself anything three thousand times turns out to be a bad idea.) In this case, I had two specific difficult questions: \\n\\n **1.** What if the official interpretation was wrong? What if I was misleading everyone from investors to employees? In that case, I should be removed from my position immediately. \\n\\n **2.** What if the official interpretation was right? What if I was grinding my brain into sawdust for no reason at all? What if I was taking the company off track by questioning my own direction? In that case, I should be removed from my position immediately.\"},{\"content\":\"As is usually the case, there was no way to know which interpretation was right until much later. It turned out that neither was actually right. The new customers didn’t save us, but we figured out another way to survive and ultimately succeed. The key to getting to the right outcome was to keep from getting married to either the positive or the dark narrative.\",\"index\":1123,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"My friend Jason Rosenthal took over as CEO of Ning in 2010. As soon as he became CEO, he faced a cash crisis and had to choose among three difficult choices: (1) radically reduce the size of the company, (2) sell the company, or (3) raise money in a highly dilutive way.\",\"index\":1124,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"Think about those choices:\",\"index\":1125,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"**1.** Lay off a large set of talented employees whom he worked very hard to recruit and, as a result, likely severely damage the morale of the remaining people.\",\"index\":1126,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"**2.** Sell out all of the employees whom he had been working side by side with for the past several years (Jason was promoted into the position) by selling the company without giving them a chance to perform or fulfill their mission.\",\"index\":1127,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"**3.** Drastically reduce the ownership position of the employees and make their hard work economically meaningless.\",\"index\":1128,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"type\":\"clump\",\"summary\":\"Think about those choices: \\n\\n **1.** Lay off a large set of talented employees whom he worked very hard to recruit and, as a result, likely severely damage the morale of the remaining people. \\n\\n **2.** Sell out all of the employees whom he had been working side by side with for the past several years (Jason was promoted into the position) by selling the com