isition, I internally questioned if I was misleading everyone or doubting a true trend. The reality was that while new customers didn’t save us, we found alternative paths to survival and success. This taught me not to get overly attached to either positive or negative viewpoints. Similarly, Jason Rosenthal, after becoming CEO of Ning in 2010 amid a cash crisis, faced difficult choices: reducing company size, selling, or raising funds, each severely affecting morale and ownership. He sought advice but ultimately bore the responsibility alone, deciding to reduce staff, which bolstered revenue and morale. Ning was later sold to Glam, and Jason moved to Lytro. Such moments underscore that CEOs must endure dire scenarios, as almost every company encounters life-threatening 'We’re Fucked, It’s Over' moments, which often feel worse than they are, especially for the CEO.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**TECHNIQUES TO CALM YOUR NERVES**\",\"index\":1132,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"The problem with psychology is that everybody’s is different. With that as a caveat, over the years I developed a few techniques for dealing with myself. I hope you find them useful, too.\",\"index\":1133,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"*Make some friends.* Although it’s nearly impossible to get high-quality advice on the tough decisions that you make, it is extremely useful from a psychological perspective to talk to people who have been through similarly challenging decisions.\",\"index\":1134,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"*Get it out of your head and onto paper.* When I had to explain to my board that, since we were a public company, I thought that it would be best if we sold all of our customers and all of our revenue and changed business, it was messing with my mind. In order to finalize that decision, I wrote down a detailed explanation of my logic. The process of writing that document separated me from my own psychology and enabled me to make the decision swiftly.\",\"index\":1135,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"*Focus on the road, not the wall.* When someone learns to drive a race car, one of the first lessons taught is that when you are going around a curve at 200 mph, do not focus on the wall; focus on the road. If you focus on the wall, you will drive right into it. If you focus on the road, you will follow the road. Running a company is like that. There are always a thousand things that can go wrong and sink the ship. If you focus too much on them, you will drive yourself nuts and likely crash your company. Focus on where you are going rather than on what you hope to avoid.\",\"index\":1136,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"The problem with psychology is that everybody's is different. With that caveat, I've developed a few techniques for dealing with myself over the years, which I hope you find useful too. First, *make some friends*. While it's tough to get high-quality advice on challenging decisions, it's psychologically beneficial to talk to people who have faced similar challenges. Second, *get it out of your head and onto paper*. When I had to make a drastic business decision, writing down a detailed explanation of my logic helped clear my mind and finalize the decision. Lastly, *focus on the road, not the wall*. Just like learning to drive a race car, where focusing on the road prevents you from crashing into the wall, running a company requires focusing on your goals rather than potential failures to avoid driving yourself nuts and crashing your company.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**DON’T PUNK OUT AND DON’T QUIT**\",\"index\":1137,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"As CEO, there will be many times when you feel like quitting. I have seen CEOs try to cope with the stress by drinking heavily, checking out, and even quitting.