g a company involves handling a myriad of unknowns and errors because managing a complex human organization in a competitive market is inherently tough. This responsibility amplifies, especially during complaints, as every decision—good or bad—is ultimately your responsibility. CEOs often deal with stress by either taking things too personally, risking overwhelm or toxicity, or not personally enough, leading to a dangerous Pollyannaish attitude. The key is balancing urgency with sanity, addressing problems decisively but without emotional turmoil. During crises, tough, solitary decisions are inevitable. For example, during the dot-com bust, despite publicly presenting a robust image, internal doubt persisted, teaching me not to get attached to viewpoints. Similarly, Jason Rosenthal at Ning faced tough choices amid a cash crisis, ultimately making painful but necessary decisions. To cope, I recommend making friends for psychological support, writing out detailed decisions, and focusing on goals rather than potential failures. Great CEOs endure immense challenges and stress without quitting, facing sleepless nights and \\\"the torture,\\\" as Alfred Chuang calls it. Successful CEOs attribute their resilience to simply not giving up, distinguishing them from the average.\",\"type\":\"section\"}],\"summary\":\"As a CEO, mastering my own psychology was the toughest skill to learn, even more so than organizational and process design, metrics, hiring, and firing. Initially, I didn't realize how challenging it would be to keep my mind in check, but over time, I discovered that it's a common struggle among CEOs, even though it's rarely discussed. Managing a complex organization in a competitive market presents unique and stressful challenges, including making tough and solitary decisions during crises. To balance the personal and professional pressures, CEOs must handle stress without getting overwhelmed or developing a Pollyannaish attitude. Techniques that helped me includ