 past decade, technological advancements have significantly reduced the financial barriers to starting a new company. However, the courage required to build a great company remains as high as ever. \",\"type\":\"section\"}],\"summary\":\"As a CEO, making difficult decisions is particularly challenging due to the unique insights and pressures involved, especially when experienced board members and employees are divided. For example, a CEO (Hamlet) faced a lucrative acquisition offer but, despite strong opposition from his team, rejected it, believing in future market opportunities. The team quickly aligned with Hamlet once the decision was made, illustrating how group dynamics can influence judgment and stressing the importance of steadfastness in leadership. During my tenure at Loudcloud and Opsware, I often felt terrified making tough decisions, but I learned to push through these feelings as part of a *courage development process*. CEOs face amplified consequences, making the choice between the easy, wrong path and the difficult, right one even more critical. Excuses for poor decisions abound, but each correct choice builds courage, shaping not just the leader but the entire company. Despite technological advancements reducing financial barriers to starting a company, the courage needed to create a great one remains as high as ever.\",\"type\":\"section\"}],\"summary\":\"I often remind my kids that heroes and cowards both feel fear, but heroes face it with discipline. As a CEO, I've realized that courage often outweighs intelligence. The clear right decision can be overshadowed by pressures, making courage essential. When evaluating entrepreneurs, we value brilliance and decisiveness. For example, founders who share leadership roles without clear decision-making authority often signal future challenges. My pointed questions usually expose the need for clear leadership. It’s crucial to have a single decision maker to streamline processes for employees. Founders often hesitate to appoint one, leading to cumbersome dual approvals. Decisions grow more daunting as companies scale; when we took Loudcloud public with only $2 million in revenue to avoid bankruptcy, it was a terrifying yet necessary choice. CEOs face immense pressures, as shown by one who rejected a lucrative acquisition offer, ultimately winning team alignment. My experiences have taught me that making tough decisions is part of a *courage development process*, essential for leadership. Each correct decision builds courage, shaping both leader and company. While starting a company has become financially easier, the courage to build a great one remains as demanding as ever.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**[ONES AND TWOS]()**\",\"index\":1179,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Jim Collins, in his bestselling book *Good to Great*, demonstrates through massive research and comprehensive analysis that when it comes to CEO succession, internal candidates dramatically outperform external candidates. The core reason is knowledge. Knowledge of technology, prior decisions, culture, personnel, and more tends to be far more difficult to acquire than the skills required to manage a larger organization. Collins does not, however, explain why internal candidates sometimes fail as well. I will attempt to do so here. I will focus the discussion on two core skills for running an organization: First, knowing what to do. Second, getting the company to do what you know. While being a great CEO requires both skills, most CEOs tend to be more comfortable with one or the other. I call managers who are happier setting the direction of the company *Ones* and those who more enjoy making the company perform at the highest level *Twos.*\",\"index\":1180,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**WHAT ONES LIKE AND DON’T LIKE**\",\"index\":1181,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Ones like spending most of their time gathering information from a broad variety of sources, from employees to customers to competitors. Ones love making decisions. Although they prefer to have comprehensive information when they make a decision, they comfortably make decisions with very little information when necessary. Ones have great strategic minds and enjoy nothing more than a good game of eight-dimensional chess against their best competitors.\",\"index\":1182,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Ones sometimes get bored with many of the important execution details required to run a company, such as process design, goal setting, structured accountability, training, and performance management.\",\"index\":1183,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Most founding CEOs tend to be Ones. When founding CEOs fail, a significant reason is that they never invested the time to be competent enough in the Two tasks to direct those activities effectively. The resulting companies become too chaotic to reach their full potential and the CEO ends up being replaced.\",\"index\":1184,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"Ones spend most of their time gathering information from various sources including employees, customers, and competitors. They love making decisions and can do so comfortably even with minimal information when necessary. With great strategic minds, they enjoy engaging in complex competitive scenarios like eight-dimensional chess. However, Ones often get bored with crucial execution details required to run a company, such as process design, goal setting, structured accountability, training, and performance management. Most founding CEOs are Ones, and when they fail, it’s often because they didn't invest enough time in Two tasks, leading to companies that are too chaotic to reach their full potential, resulting in the CEO being replaced.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**WHAT TWOS LIKE AND DON’T LIKE**\",\"index\":1185,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Twos, on the other hand, thoroughly enjoy the process of making the company run well. They insist upon super-clear goals and strongly prefer not to change goals or direction unless absolutely necessary.\",\"index\":1186,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Twos like to participate in strategic discussions but often have difficulty with the strategic thinking process itself. Where a One might be perfectly comfortable spending one day a week reading, studying, and thinking, doing so would make a Two very nervous, because it would not feel like work to them. A Two would get antsy at the thought of all the processes that might be improved, people who might be held accountable to achieving the standard, or sales calls that could be made while he was wasting time just thinking about strategy.\",\"index\":1187,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Big decisions worry Twos much more than they worry Ones. Circumstances often force both Ones and Twos to make critical decisions with insufficient data, but Ones generally feel fine about doing that and do not get overly anxious about the consequences. Twos, by contrast, can become highly agitated about such things and sometimes overcomplicate the decision-making process in order to provide a false feeling of thoroughness about the choice.\",\"index\":1188,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"CEOs who are Twos, despite their love of action, can sometimes bring decision making in a company to a halt.\",\"index\":1189,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"Twos thoroughly enjoy making the company run smoothly, insisting on clear goals and avoiding changes unless absolutely necessary. While they like strategic discussions, they struggle with the strategic thinking process itself. Unlike Ones, who can comfortably spend time reading and thinking, Twos would feel uneasy, as it doesn’t feel like productive work to them. They get restless thinking about the processes to be improved, the people to hold accountable, or sales calls to make, instead of just strategizing. Big decisions worry Twos far more than Ones, who can navigate with insufficient data without much anxiety. Twos, however, become agitated and often overcomplicate decisions to create a false sense of thoroughness. This tendency can sometimes halt decision-making in companies led by Twos, despite their love for action.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**YOU NEED BOTH CHARACTERISTICS TO BE A GOOD CEO**\",\"index\":1190,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"While people tend to be Ones or Twos, with discipline and hard work natural Twos can be competent at One tasks and Ones can be competent at Two tasks. If a CEO ignores the dimension of management she doesn’t like, she generally fails. Ones end up in chaos and Twos fail to pivot when necessary.\",\"index\":1191,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"While people tend to be Ones or Twos, with discipline and hard work natural Twos can be competent at One tasks and Ones can be competent at Two tasks. If a CEO ignores the dimension of management she doesn’t like, she generally fails. Ones end up in chaos and Twos fail to pivot when necessary.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**FUNCTIONAL ONES**\",\"index\":1192,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Often Two executives act as Ones for their functions, but Twos as members of the executive team. For example, the head of sales might easily make all the decisions that are local to the sales organization but prefer to take direction with respect to the overall company plans. This is the best kind of multilayer leadership possible, because directions are clear and decisions are made rapidly with precision.\",\"index\":1193,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"Often Two executives act as Ones for their functions, but Twos as members of the executive team. For example, the head of sales might easily make all the decisions that are local to the sales organization but prefer to take direction with respect to the overall company plans. This is the best kind of multilayer leadership possible, because directions are clear and decisions are made rapidly with precision.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**HOW ORGANIZATIONS TEND TO BE CONSTRUCTED**\",\"index\":1194,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"The primary purpose of the organizational hierarchy in a company is decision-making efficiency. It follows that most CEOs tend to be Ones. If the person at the top of the decision-making hierarchy doesn’t like making extremely complex decisions, the company’s processes will be slow and unwieldy.\",\"index\":1195,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"If you’re a One, it can be counterproductive to have another One on your staff, because she will want to set her own direction rather than follow yours. This kind of strategic contention can confuse the organization and send employees in opposing directions. As a result, many great One CEOs employ primarily Twos and Functional Ones on their staff.\",\"index\":1196,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"The primary purpose of the organizational hierarchy in a company is to ensure decision-making efficiency, which is why most CEOs tend to be Ones. If a CEO dislikes making complex decisions, the company's processes can become slow and unwieldy. For One CEOs, having another One on staff can be counterproductive, as it may lead to strategic contention and confuse the organization. To avoid this, many successful One CEOs employ mainly Twos and Functional Ones, who help in executing the set direction without causing conflicting strategies.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**WHAT HAPPENS AT SUCCESSION?**\",\"index\":1197,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"This brings us to the question of succession. Since most organizations are run by Ones and have a team of Twos (sometimes Functional Ones) reporting to them, replacing the CEO can be extremely tricky. Do you promote someone from the executive staff even though they are likely a Two? Microsoft did this in 2000 when they replaced Bill Gates, a prototypical One, with Steve Ballmer, literally his number two. Or do you reach deep into the organization and pull a One from a level lower where they are likely to exist? General Electric famously did this with Jack Welch in 1981. It was an incredibly bold move by GE—not only did they promote an executive two levels down in the organizational chart past all of his superiors, but in doing so they named the youngest CEO in the history of GE. It’s difficult for most board members to even conceive of the possibility that there is a One deep in the organization who is more qualified to run the company than anyone on the executive staff.\",\"index\":1198,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Both methods can be problematic. The first approach leaves the company in the charge of a Two. As the company faces forks in the road, decision making may slow down and the company may lose its edge. In addition, the natural Ones (in Microsoft’s case, stellar executives such as Paul Maritz and Brad Silverberg) will eventually leave.\",\"index\":1199,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"In scenario two, by promoting someone past everyone on the executive team and making them CEO (as GE did), you will likely cause massive turnover of the executive staff. In fact, in very short order, almost none of the original GE executives remained under Welch. In a diversified conglomerate like GE, this kind of rough transition is possible. For companies in the highly dynamic technology business, the super-high-turnover scenario is more dangerous.\",\"index\":1200,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"Succession in organizations, particularly when replacing the CEO, presents significant challenges. Typically, organizations are led by Ones with Twos reporting to them. Promoting from within the executive staff, as Microsoft did in 2000 by replacing Bill Gates with Steve Ballmer, risks appointing a Two, which may slow decision-making and cause natural Ones to leave. The other option is to promote a One from deeper within the organization, bypassing the executive team, as GE did with Jack Welch in 1981. This bold move can lead to high executive turnover, which a diversified conglomerate like GE might manage, but poses greater risks for companies in the fast-paced technology sector. Both methods carry potential drawbacks and significant impacts on organizational stability and effectiveness.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**THE BIG CONCLUSION**\",\"index\":1201,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"The big conclusion will be a big disappointment for those looking for an answer. The answer is there is no easy answer. CEO transition is hard. If you bring people in from the outside, you lower your chances for success. If you promote from within, you must deal with the One-Two phenomenon. Ideally, you’ll promote a One and the rest of the executive team will be glad you did. Too bad things are rarely ideal.\",\"index\":1202,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"\",\"index\":1203,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\" \",\"index\":1204,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"The conclusion might be disappointing for those seeking a clear solution: there is no easy answer. CEO transitions are tough. Hiring from outside lowers your chances of success, while promoting from within can trigger the One-Two phenomenon. Ideally, you’ll promote a One and the executive team will support the decision. Unfortunately, things are rarely that ideal.\",\"type\":\"section\"}],\"summary\":\"Ones thrive on gathering information, making decisions swiftly even with minimal data, and strategizing in complex scenarios. They often find operational details, such as process design and performance management, tedious, which can lead to organizational chaos if neglected. Most founding CEOs are Ones, and their downfall usually stems from ignoring these critical details. On the other hand, Twos excel in ensuring smooth operations, setting clear goals, and avoiding changes unless necessary. They struggle with strategic thinking and become anxious over big decisions. Twos can sometimes slow decision-making due to their need for perceived thoroughness. Despite natural tendencies, Ones can learn Two tasks and vice versa with discipline, but both must balance these roles to avoid failure. Effective organizational hierarchy usually has Ones as CEOs with Twos or Functional Ones supporting them to execute strategies without causing conflicting directions. Succession challenges are significant; promoting Twos can slow decisions and drive away natural Ones, while promoting Ones from deeper within can disrupt the executive team. Both internal promotions and external hires carry risks, and ideal transitions where a One is promoted and the executive team supports the decision are rare. In essence, CEO transitions are inherently difficult with no simple solutions.\",\"type\":\"section\"}],\"summary\":\"In *Good to Great*, Jim Collins shows that internal CEO candidates tend to outperform external ones due to their ingrained knowledge of the company’s technology, culture, and personnel. However, he doesn’t address why internal candidates sometimes fail. Addressing this gap, I argue that running an organization requires two core skills: knowing what to do and getting the company to do it. CEOs often lean towards one of these skills. I label those who thrive on direction-setting as *Ones* and those excellent at operational execution as *Twos.* Ones excel in decision-making and strategy but may neglect operational details, leading to chaos, while Twos maintain smooth functioning with clear goals but struggle with strategic decisions. Each can learn the other's tasks with discipline but must balance to avoid failure. Typically, successful organizations place Ones as CEOs with Twos or Functional Ones in supportive roles to ensure strategies are executed effectively. Succession is tricky; promoting Twos can slow decision-making and repel Ones, while promoting Ones disrupts the executive team. Ideal transitions, where promotions and team support align smoothly, are rare, making CEO transitions inherently complex and fraught with risks.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**[FOLLOW THE LEADER]()**\",\"index\":1205,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"There is no prototype for the perfect CEO. Radically different styles—think Steve Jobs, Bill Campbell, and Andy Grove—can all lead to great outcomes. Perhaps the most important attribute required to be a successful CEO is leadership. So what is leadership and how do we think about it in the context of the CEO job? Are great leaders born or made?\",\"index\":1206,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Most people define leadership in the same way that Supreme Court justice Potter Stewart famously defined pornography when he said, “I know it when I see it.” For our purposes, we can generalize this to be the measure of the quality of a leader: the quantity, quality, and diversity of people who want to follow her.\",\"index\":1207,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"So what makes people want to follow a leader? We look for three key traits:\",\"index\":1208,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"* The ability to articulate the vision\\n\\n* The right kind of ambition\\n\\n* The ability to achieve the vision\",\"index\":1209,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"type\":\"clump\",\"summary\":\"So what makes people want to follow a leader? We look for three key traits: \\n\\n * The ability to articulate the vision\\n\\n* The right kind of ambition\\n\\n* The ability to achieve the vision\"},{\"content\":\"Let’s take these in order.\",\"index\":1210,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**THE ABILITY TO ARTICULATE THE VISION: THE STEVE JOBS ATTRIBUTE**\",\"index\":1211,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Can the leader articulate a vision that’s interesting, dynamic, and compelling? More important, can the leader do this when things fall apart? More specifically, when the company gets to a point when it does not make financial sense for any employee to continue working there, will the leader be able to articulate a vision that’s compelling enough to make people stay?\",\"index\":1212,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"I believe Jobs’s greatest achievement as a visionary leader was in getting so many super-talented people to continue following him at NeXT, long after the company lost its patina, and in getting the employees of Apple to buy into his vision when the company was weeks away from bankruptcy. It’s difficult to imagine any other leader being so compelling that he could accomplish these goals back-to-back, and this is why we call this one the Steve Jobs attribute.\",\"index\":1213,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"Can the leader articulate a vision that’s interesting, dynamic, and compelling, especially when things fall apart? More critically, can they do this when it's not financially viable for employees to stay? I believe Jobs’s greatest achievement as a visionary leader lies in his ability to retain incredibly talented people at NeXT even after the company lost its shine and in convincing Apple employees to embrace his vision when the company was on the brink of bankruptcy. It’s hard to imagine another leader being so compelling to achieve these feats consecutively, which is why we refer to this as the Steve Jobs attribute.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**THE RIGHT KIND OF AMBITION: THE BILL CAMPBELL ATTRIBUTE**\",\"index\":1214,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"One of the biggest misperceptions in our society is that a prerequisite for becoming a CEO is to be selfish, ruthless, and callous. In fact, the opposite is true and the reason is obvious. The first thing that any successful CEO must do is get really great people to work for her. Smart people do not want to work for people who do not have their interests in mind and in heart.\",\"index\":1215,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Most of us have experienced this in our careers: a bright, ambitious, hardworking executive whom nobody good wants to work for and who, as a result, delivers performance far worse than one might imagine.\",\"index\":1216,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Truly great leaders create an environment where the employees feel that the CEO cares more about the employees than she cares about herself. In this kind of environment, an amazing thing happens: A huge number of employees believe it’s *their* company and behave accordingly. As the company grows large, these employees become quality control for the entire organization. They set the work standard that all future employees must live up to. As in, “Hey, you need to do a better job on that data sheet—you are screwing up my company.”\",\"index\":1217,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"I call this characteristic the Bill Campbell attribute after the man who is the best I’ve ever seen at this. If you talk to people who worked in any of the many organizations that Bill has run, they refer to those organizations as “my organization” or “my company.” A huge part of why he has been so remarkably strong in this dimension of leadership is that he’s completely authentic. He would happily sacrifice his own economics, fame, glory, and rewards for his employees. When you talk to Bill, you get the feeling that he cares deeply about you and what you have to say, because he does. And all of that shows up in his actions and follow-through.\",\"index\":1218,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"One of the biggest misperceptions is that becoming a CEO requires being selfish, ruthless, and callous. The truth is, successful CEOs need to attract great people, and smart employees won't work for someone who doesn't have their interests at heart. We've all seen bright executives deliver poor performance because no one good wants to work for them. Great leaders create environments where employees feel genuinely cared for, which makes them more invested and behave as if it's their company. This ensures high work standards for the entire organization. I refer to this as the Bill Campbell attribute, named after the best example of this kind of leadership I've ever seen. Bill's authenticity and willingness to sacrifice his own gains for his employees make people feel truly valued, and this shows in his consistent actions and follow-through.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**THE ABILITY TO ACHIEVE THE VISION: THE ANDY GROVE ATTRIBUTE**\",\"index\":1219,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"The final leg of our leadership stool is competence, pure and simple. If I buy into the vision and believe that the leader cares about me, do I think she can actually achieve the vision? Will I follow her into the jungle with no map forward or back and trust that she will get me out of there?\",\"index\":1220,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"I like to refer to this as the Andy Grove attribute. Andy Grove will always be my model of CEO competence. He earned a Ph.D. in electrical engineering, wrote the best management book I’ve ever read (*High Output Management*), and tirelessly refined his craft. Not only did he write exceptional books on management, but he taught management classes at Intel throughout his tenure.\",\"index\":1221,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"In his classic book *Only the Paranoid Survive*, Grove tells how he led Intel through the dramatic transition from the memory business to the microprocessor business. In making that change he walked away from nearly all his revenue. He humbly credits others in the company with coming to the strategic conclusion before he did, but the credit for swiftly and successfully leading the company through the transition goes to Dr. Grove. Changing your primary business as a sixteen-year-old large, public company raises a lot of questions.\",\"index\":1222,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Andy describes an incident with one of his employees: “One of them attacked me aggressively, asking, ‘Does it mean that you can conceive of Intel without being in the memory business?’ I swallowed hard and said, ‘Yes, I guess I can.’ All hell broke loose.”\",\"index\":1223,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Despite shocking many of his best employees with this radical strategy, ultimately the company trusted Andy. They trusted him to rebuild their company around an entirely new business. That trust turned out to be very well placed.\",\"index\":1224,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"The final leg of our leadership stool is competence. After believing in the vision and feeling cared for by the leader, the next question is: can she achieve the vision? This is what I call the Andy Grove attribute. Andy Grove is my model of a competent CEO. With a Ph.D. in electrical engineering, he wrote the best management book I've read, *High Output Management*, and consistently honed his skills. Grove taught management at Intel and led the company through a massive transition from the memory business to the microprocessor business, a move he detailed in his book *Only the Paranoid Survive*. Despite initial resistance from employees, Grove successfully guided Intel through this radical change, earning their trust and proving his competence.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**SO, ARE GREAT LEADERS BORN OR MADE?**\",\"index\":1225,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Let’s look at this one attribute at a time:\",\"index\":1226,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"* **Articulating the vision** There is no question that some people are much better storytellers than others. However, it is also true that anybody can greatly improve in this area through focus and hard work. All CEOs should work on the vision component of leadership.\\n\\n* **Alignment of interests** I am not sure if the Bill Campbell attribute is impossible to learn, but I am pretty sure that it is impossible to teach. Of the three, this one most fits the bill “born not made.”\\n\\n* **Ability to achieve the vision** This attribute can absolutely be learned; perhaps this is why Andy Grove’s tolerance for incompetence was legendarily low. Indeed, the enemy of competence is sometimes confidence. A CEO should never be so confident that she stops improving her skills.\",\"index\":1227,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"In the end, some attributes of leadership can be improved more than others, but every CEO should work on all three. Furthermore, each attribute enhances all three. If people trust you, they will listen to your vision even if it is less articulate. If you are super-competent, they will trust you and listen to you. If you can paint a brilliant vision, people will be patient with you as you learn the CEO skills and give you more leeway with respect to their interests.\",\"index\":1228,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"\",\"index\":1229,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\" \",\"index\":1230,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"Each CEO must focus on three crucial attributes to excel in leadership: articulating the vision, aligning interests, and achieving the vision. While some people are naturally better storytellers, anyone can improve their vision articulation through hard work. Aligning interests, a trait observed in Bill Campbell, may be more innate and challenging to teach. In contrast, the ability to achieve the vision can be learned, which is why leaders like Andy Grove had low tolerance for incompetence, emphasizing that confidence should never replace continuous skill improvement. Ultimately, CEOs should enhance all three attributes as they collectively reinforce each other: trust can make up for less articulate visions, competence can build trust and attention, and a well-crafted vision can earn patience and flexibility from others.\",\"type\":\"section\"}],\"summary\":\"Can the leader articulate a vision that's interesting, dynamic, and compelling, especially when things fall apart? More critically, can they do this when it's not financially viable for employees to stay? Jobs's greatest achievement as a visionary leader lies in his ability to retain incredibly talented people at NeXT even after the company lost its shine and in convincing Apple employees to embrace his vision when the company was on the brink of bankruptcy. It’s hard to imagine another leader being so compelling to achieve these feats consecutively, which is why we call this the Steve Jobs attribute.\\n\\nOne of the biggest misperceptions is that becoming a CEO requires being selfish, ruthless, and callous. Successful CEOs need to attract great people, and smart employees won't work for someone who doesn't have their interests at heart. We've all seen bright executives deliver poor performance because no one good wants to work for them. Great leaders create environments where employees feel genuinely cared for, making them more invested and causing them to behave as if it's their company, ensuring high work standards for the entire organization. This is the Bill Campbell attribute. Bill's authenticity and willingness to sacrifice his own gains for his employees make people feel truly valued, as shown in his consistent actions and follow-through.\\n\\nThe final leg of our leadership stool is competence. After believing in the vision and feeling cared for by the leader, the next question is: can she achieve the vision? This is what I call the Andy Grove attribute. Andy Grove is my model of a competent CEO. With a Ph.D. in electrical engineering, he wrote the best management book I've read, *High Output Management*, and consistently honed his skills. Grove taught management at Intel and led the company through a massive transition from the memory business to the microprocessor business, a move he detailed in his book *Only the Paranoid Survive*. Despite initial resistance from employees, Grove successfully guided Intel through this radical change, earning their trust and proving his competence.\\n\\nEach CEO must focus on three crucial attributes to excel in leadership: articulating the vision, aligning interests, and achieving the vision. While some people are naturally better storytellers, anyone can improve their vision articulation through hard work. Aligning interests, a trait observed in Bill Campbell, may be more innate and challenging to teach. In contrast, the ability to achieve the vision can be learned, which is why leaders like Andy Grove had low tolerance for incompetence, emphasizing that confidence should never replace continuous skill improvement. Ultimately, CEOs should enhance all three attributes as they collectively reinforce each other: trust can make up for less articulate visions, competence can build trust and attention, and a well-crafted vision can earn patience and flexibility from others.\",\"type\":\"section\"}],\"summary\":\"There is no prototype for the perfect CEO; diverse styles like those of Steve Jobs, Bill Campbell, and Andy Grove can all lead to great success. The key attribute for a successful CEO is leadership, which is often defined by the quality, quantity, and diversity of people who want to follow the leader. Effective leadership comprises three crucial traits: the ability to articulate an engaging and compelling vision (such as Jobs's retention of talent at NeXT and Apple), the ambition to achieve and align it with the interests of employees (exemplified by Campbell’s genuine care for his team), and the competence to achieve the vision (demonstrated by Grove's leadership at Intel during major transitions). While some aspects of leadership can be innate, others can be developed through hard work. Each CEO must focus on articulating the vision, aligning interests, and achieving the vision, as these attributes reinforce each other and collectively contribute to effective leadership.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**[PEACETIME CEO/WARTIME CEO]()**\",\"index\":1231,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Bill Campbell always used to say to me, “Ben, you’re the best CEO that I work with.” This always seemed crazy to me, because he was working with Steve Jobs, Jeff Bezos, and Eric Schmidt at the time while my company was going straight into the wall. One day I called him on it and said, “Bill, why would you say that? Do results not count?” He said, “There are lots of good peacetime CEOs and lots of good wartime CEOs, but almost no CEOs that can function in both peacetime and in wartime. You’re a peacetime/wartime CEO.”\",\"index\":1232,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"By my calculation, I was a peacetime CEO for three days and wartime CEO for eight years. I still have a hard time shaking the wartime flashbacks. I’m not the only one who has experienced this. Dennis Crowley, the founder of Foursquare, told me that he thinks about this tension—between wartime and peacetime—every day. The same goes for a lot of tech companies.\",\"index\":1233,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"For instance, when Eric Schmidt stepped down as CEO of Google and founder Larry Page took over, much of the news coverage focused on Page’s ability to be the “face of Google” since Page is far more shy and introverted than the gregarious and articulate Schmidt. While an interesting issue, this analysis misses the main point. Schmidt was much more than Google’s front man; as Google’s *peacetime* chief executive, he led the greatest technology business expansion in the last ten years. Larry Page, in contrast, seems to have determined that Google is moving into war and he clearly intends to be a *wartime* CEO. This has been a profound change for Google and the entire high-tech industry.\",\"index\":1234,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**DEFINITIONS AND EXAMPLES**\",\"index\":1235,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Peacetime in business means those times when a company has a large advantage over the competition in its core market, and its market is growing. In times of peace, the company can focus on expanding the market and reinforcing the company’s strengths.\",\"index\":1236,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"In wartime, a company is fending off an imminent existential threat. Such a threat can come from a wide range of sources, including competition, dramatic macroeconomic change, market change, supply chain change, and so forth. The great wartime CEO Andy Grove marvelously describes the forces that can take a company from peacetime to wartime in his book *Only the Paranoid Survive*.\",\"index\":1237,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"A classic peacetime mission is Google’s effort to make the Internet faster. Google’s position in the search market is so dominant that they determined that anything that makes the Internet faster accrues to their benefit since it enables users to do more searches. As the clear market leader, they focus more on expanding the market than dealing with their search competitors. In contrast, a classic wartime mission was Andy Grove’s drive to get out of the memory business in the mid-1980s due to an irrepressible threat from the Japanese semiconductor companies. In this mission, the competitive threat—which could have bankrupted the company—was so great that Intel had to exit its core business, which employed 80 percent of its staff.\",\"index\":1238,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"My greatest management discovery through the transition was that peacetime and wartime require radically different management styles. Interestingly, most management books describe peacetime CEO techniques and very few describe wartime. For example, a basic principle in most management books is that you should never embarrass an employee in a public setting. On the other hand, in a room filled with people, Andy Grove once said to an employee who entered the meeting late, “All I have in this world is time, and you are wasting my time.” Why such different approaches to management?\",\"index\":1239,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"In peacetime, leaders must maximize and broaden the current opportunity. As a result, peacetime leaders employ techniques to encourage broad-based creativity and contribution across a diverse set of possible objectives. In wartime, by contrast, the company typically has a single bullet in the chamber and must, at all costs, hit the target. The company’s survival in wartime depends upon strict adherence and alignment to the mission.\",\"index\":1240,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"When Steve Jobs returned to Apple, the company was weeks away from bankruptcy—a classic wartime scenario. He needed everyone to move with precision and follow his exact plan; there was no room for individual creativity outside the core mission. In stark contrast, as Google achieved dominance in the search market, Google’s management fostered peacetime innovation by enabling and even requiring every employee to spend 20 percent of their time on their own new projects.\",\"index\":1241,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Peacetime and wartime management techniques can both be highly effective when employed in the right situations, but they are very different. The peacetime CEO does not resemble the wartime CEO.\",\"index\":1242,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"Peacetime in business occurs when a company holds a dominant position in a growing market, allowing it to focus on expansion and strengthening its core advantages. Wartime, however, arises from existential threats like competitive pressures, economic changes, or supply chain disruptions, necessitating a more aggressive and survival-focused management approach. Andy Grove's book *Only the Paranoid Survive* illustrates how companies navigate these transitions, using Intel's strategic pivot from the memory business under Japanese threat as a prime example. In peacetime, like Google's efforts to speed up the Internet, management fosters broad-based innovation and creativity. Conversely, in wartime, exemplified by Steve Jobs' urgent turnaround of Apple, strict adherence and alignment to the mission are crucial for survival. Understanding these radically different management styles is essential, as peacetime CEOs often focus on maximizing opportunities while wartime CEOs aim to ensure the organization's immediate survival.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**PEACETIME CEO/WARTIME CEO**\",\"index\":1243,\"t