 both peacetime and wartime?\",\"index\":1261,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"One could easily argue that I failed as a peacetime CEO but succeeded as a wartime one. John Chambers had a great run as peacetime CEO of Cisco but has struggled as Cisco has moved into war with Juniper, HP, and a range of new competitors. Steve Jobs, who employed a classical wartime management style, removed himself as CEO of Apple in the 1980s during their longest period of peace before coming back to Apple for a spectacular run more than a decade later, during their most intense war period.\",\"index\":1262,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"I believe that the answer is yes, but it’s hard. Mastering both wartime and peacetime skill sets means understanding the many rules of management and knowing when to follow them and when to violate them.\",\"index\":1263,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Be aware that management books tend to be written by management consultants who study successful companies during their times of peace. As a result, the resulting books describe the methods of peacetime CEOs. In fact, other than the books written by Andy Grove, I don’t know of any management books that teach you how to manage in wartime like Steve Jobs or Andy Grove.\",\"index\":1264,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"Yes, a CEO can develop the necessary skill sets to lead effectively in both peacetime and wartime, but it’s challenging. Take my experience: I struggled as a peacetime CEO but thrived in wartime. John Chambers excelled as Cisco's peacetime CEO but faced difficulty as competition intensified. Steve Jobs exemplified wartime leadership, stepping aside during Apple's peacetime in the 1980s only to return and shine during its most fierce competitive era over a decade later. Mastering both skill sets requires knowing the many rules of management and understanding when to follow or break them. Management literature typically focuses on successful companies in peaceful times, leaving a gap in guidance for wartime management—exceptions being the works of Andy Grove and other rare examples.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**BACK TO THE BEGINNING**\",\"index\":1265,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"It turned out that a little wartime was just what the doctor ordered for Google. Page’s precise and exacting leadership has led to brilliant execution in integrating identity across Google’s broad product line, from the rise of Android to brilliant new products like Google Glass. Sometimes you need to go to war.\",\"index\":1266,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"\",\"index\":1267,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\" \",\"index\":1268,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"A little wartime was just what the doctor ordered for Google. Under Page’s precise and exacting leadership, the company has executed brilliantly in integrating identity across its broad product line, resulting in the rise of Android and innovative products like Google Glass. Sometimes, you need to go to war.\",\"type\":\"section\"}],\"summary\":\"In business, peacetime occurs when a company holds a dominant position in a growing market, allowing focus on expansion and core strengths. Wartime arises from existential threats necessitating aggressive, survival-focused management. Andy Grove's *Only the Paranoid Survive* highlights these transitions, using Intel's shift from the memory business under Japanese threat as an example. In peacetime, management fosters innovation, such as Google's efforts to speed up the Internet. Conversely, wartime requires strict adherence to the mission, as shown by Steve Jobs' turnaround at Apple. A peacetime CEO focuses on protocol, culture, and scalable systems, while a wartime CEO breaks rules, focuses on survival, and tolerates no deviation. Wartime CEOs, like Steve Jobs, thrive in crises but may struggle in stable periods, while peacetime leaders, like John Chambers of Cisco, may falter under competitive pressure. Effective leadership in both contexts entails understanding when to follow or break management rules. Google's success under Larry Page's precise wartime leadership illustrates that sometimes going to war is necessary for progress.\",\"type\":\"section\"}],\"summary\":\"Bill Campbell used to tell me, “Ben, you’re the best CEO I work with,” which baffled me since he was also advising giants like Steve Jobs, Jeff Bezos, and Eric Schmidt while my company seemed doomed. When I questioned him about it, he explained, “There are lots of good peacetime CEOs and lots of good wartime CEOs, but almost no CEOs that can function in both peacetime and in wartime. You’re a peacetime/wartime CEO.” In my experience, I was a peacetime CEO for only three days but a wartime CEO for eight years, with lasting wartime flashbacks. Many tech founders, like Dennis Crowley of Foursquare, grapple with this peacetime-wartime dichotomy daily. When Eric Schmidt stepped down as Google’s CEO for Larry Page, the focus on Page’s introversion overlooked the more crucial shift: Schmidt was a peacetime leader who oversaw significant growth, while Page aimed to lead Google through its wartime. Peacetime is marked by market dominance and expansion focus, while wartime demands aggressive, survival-oriented leadership. Andy Grove’s *Only the Paranoid Survive* describes how Intel shifted from memory to microprocessors under threat, epitomizing this transition. Peacetime CEOs foster innovation and scalable systems; wartime CEOs break rules and focus on survival. Steve Jobs excelled in crises but struggled in stable periods, while John Chambers of Cisco thrived in peacetime but faltered under pressure. Leadership effectiveness hinges on discerning when to adhere to or break management rules, with Larry Page’s wartime leadership demonstrating the necessity of strategic aggression for progress.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**[MAKING YOURSELF A CEO]()**\",\"index\":1269,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"The other day, a friend of mine asked me whether CEOs were born or made. I said, “That’s kind of like asking if Jolly Ranchers are grown or made. CEO is an unnatural job.” The surprised look on his face made me realize that perhaps it wasn’t as obvious as I’d originally thought.\",\"index\":1270,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Most people actually assume the opposite—CEOs are born, not made. I often listen as other venture capitalists and board members rapidly evaluate a founder and conclude that she’s not “CEO material.” I am not sure how they figure these things out so fast. It generally takes years for a founder to develop the CEO skill set and it is usually extremely difficult for me to tell whether she will make it.\",\"index\":1271,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"In athletics, some things, like becoming a sprinter, can be learned relatively quickly because they start with a natural motion and refine it. Others, like boxing, take much longer to master because they require lots of unnatural motions and lots of specific technique. For example, as I mentioned earlier, when going backward in boxing it’s critically important to pick up your back foot first, because if you get hit while walking backward the natural way—picking up your front foot first—it often leads to getting knocked cold. Learning to make this unnatural motion feel natural takes a great deal of practice. If you do what feels most natural as a CEO, you may also get knocked cold.\",\"index\":1272,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Being CEO requires lots of unnatural motion. From an evolutionary standpoint, it is natural to do things that make people like you. It enhances your chances for survival. Yet to be a good CEO, in order to be liked in the long run, you must do many things that will upset people in the short run. Unnatural things.\",\"index\":1273,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Even the most basic CEO building blocks will feel unnatural at first. If your buddy tells you a funny story, it would feel quite weird to evaluate her performance. It would be totally unnatural to say, “Gee, I thought that story really sucked. It had potential, but you were underwhelming on the buildup and then you totally flubbed the punch line. I suggest that you go back, rework it, and present it to me again tomorrow.”\",\"index\":1274,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Doing so would be quite bizarre, but evaluating people’s performances and constantly giving feedback is precisely what a CEO must do. If she doesn’t, the more complex motions such as writing reviews, taking away territory, handling politics, setting compensation, and firing people will be either impossible or handled rather poorly.\",\"index\":1275,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Giving feedback turns out to be the unnatural atomic building block atop which the unnatural skill set of management gets built. But how does one master the unnatural?\",\"index\":1276,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**THE SHIT SANDWICH**\",\"index\":1277,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"A popular and sometimes effective technique for feedback beginners is something that experienced managers call the *Shit Sandwich*. The technique is marvelously described in the classic management text *The One Minute Manager*. The basic idea is that people open up to feedback far more if you start by complimenting them (slice of bread number one), then you give them the difficult message (the shit), then wrap up by reminding them how much you value their strengths (slice of bread number two). The shit sandwich also has the positive side effect of focusing the feedback on the behavior rather than the person, because you establish up front that you really value the person. This is a key concept in giving feedback.\",\"index\":1278,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"The shit sandwich can work well with junior employees but has the following challenges:\",\"index\":1279,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"* It tends to be overly formal. Because you have to preplan and script the sandwich to make it come out correctly, the process can feel formal and judgmental to the employee.\\n\\n* After you do it a couple of times, it will lack authenticity. The employee will think, “Oh boy, she’s complimenting me again. I know what’s coming next, the shit.”\\n\\n* More senior executives will recognize the shit sandwich immediately and it will have an instant negative effect.\",\"index\":1280,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Early in my career, I attempted to deliver a carefully crafted shit sandwich to a senior employee and she looked at me like I was a little kid and said, “Spare me the compliment, Ben, and just tell me what I did wrong.” At that point, I thought that I was definitely not born to be a CEO.\",\"index\":1281,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"A popular technique for giving feedback, especially for beginners, is known as the *Shit Sandwich*, as detailed in the classic management text *The One Minute Manager*. This method involves starting with a compliment (the first slice of bread), then delivering the difficult message (the shit), and concluding with positive reinforcement (the second slice of bread). This approach helps focus on behavior rather than the individual, making feedback more palatable. However, it has notable drawbacks: it can feel overly formal and scripted, leading to a lack of authenticity, and more seasoned employees may recognize and discount it immediately. Early in my career, I faced this challenge when a senior employee bluntly asked me to skip the compliment and get to the point, leaving me doubting my potential as a CEO.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**THE KEYS**\",\"index\":1282,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"To become elite at giving feedback, you must elevate yourself beyond a basic technique like the shit sandwich. You must develop a style that matches your own personality and values. Here are the keys to being effective:\",\"index\":1283,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"* *Be authentic.* It’s extremely important that you believe in the feedback that you give and not say anything to manipulate the recipient’s feelings. You can’t fake the funk.\\n\\n* *Come from the right place.* It’s important that you give people feedback because you want them to succeed and not because you want them to fail. If you really want someone to succeed, then make her feel it. Make her feel you. If she feels you and you are in her corner, then she will listen to you.\\n\\n* *Don’t get personal.* If you decide to fire somebody, fire her. Don’t prepare her to get fired. Prepare her to succeed. If she doesn’t take the feedback, that’s a different conversation.\\n\\n* *Don’t clown people in front of their peers.* While it’s okay to give certain kinds of feedback in a group setting, you should strive never to embarrass someone in front of their peers. If you do so, then your feedback will have little impact other than to cause the employee to be horribly ashamed and to hate your guts.\\n\\n* *Feedback is not one-size-fits-all.* Everybody is different. Some employees are extremely sensitive to feedback while others have particularly thick skin and often thick skulls. Stylistically, your tone should match the employee’s personality, not your mood.\\n\\n* *Be direct, but not mean.* Don’t be obtuse. If you think somebody’s presentation sucks, don’t say, “It’s really good, but could use one more pass to tighten up the conclusion.” While it may seem harsh, it’s much better to say, “I couldn’t follow it and I didn’t understand your point and here are the reasons why.” Watered-down feedback can be worse than no feedback at all because it’s deceptive and confusing to the recipient. But don’t beat them up or attempt to show your superiority. Doing so will defeat your purpose because when done properly, feedback is a dialogue, not a monologue.\",\"index\":1284,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"To excel in giving feedback, move beyond basic techniques like the \\\"shit sandwich\\\" and develop a style that reflects your personality and values. The keys to effective feedback include being authentic, as sincerity is critical; ensuring your intentions are to help the recipient succeed; refraining from personal attacks and focusing on their potential for success; avoiding public embarrassment, which undermines impact; tailoring your feedback to each individual’s sensitivity; and being straightforward but kind. Be direct about issues without being mean, as watered-down feedback can be misleading. Remember, feedback should be a constructive dialogue aimed at improvement.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**FEEDBACK IS A DIALOGUE, NOT A MONOLOGUE**\",\"index\":1285,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"You may be the CEO and you may be telling somebody about something that you don’t like or disagree with, but that doesn’t mean you’re right. Your employee should know more about her function than you. She should have more data than you. You may be wrong.\",\"index\":1286,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"As a result, your goal should be for your feedback to open up rather than close down discussion. Encourage people to challenge your judgment and argue the point to conclusion. Culturally, you want high standards thoroughly discussed. You want to apply tremendous pressure to get the highest-quality thinking yet be open enough to find out when you are wrong.\",\"index\":1287,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"As a CEO, just because you dislike or disagree with something doesn’t mean you’re right; your employees likely know more about their functions and have more data. Your feedback should aim to open up discussions, not close them down. Encourage your team to challenge your judgment and debate the issues thoroughly. Culturally, strive for high standards by fostering comprehensive discussions, applying pressure to achieve top-notch thinking, and being open to recognizing when you're wrong.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**HIGH-FREQUENCY FEEDBACK**\",\"index\":1288,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Once you’ve mastered the keys, you should practice what you’ve mastered all the time. As CEO, you should have an opinion on absolutely everything. You should have an opinion on every forecast, every product plan, every presentation, and even every comment. Let people know what you think. If you like someone’s comment, give her the feedback. If you disagree, give her the feedback. Say what you think. Express yourself.\",\"index\":1289,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"This will have two critically important positive effects:\",\"index\":1290,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"* *Feedback won’t be personal in your company.* If the CEO constantly gives feedback, then everyone she interacts with will just get used to it. Nobody will think, “Gee, what did she really mean by that comment? Does she not like me?” Everybody will naturally focus on the issues, not an implicit random performance evaluation.\\n\\n* *People will become comfortable discussing bad news.* If people get comfortable talking about what *each other* are doing wrong, then it will be very easy to talk about what *the company* is doing wrong. High-quality company cultures get their cue from data networking routing protocols: Bad news travels fast and good news travels slowly. Low-quality company cultures take on the personality of the Wicked Witch of the West in *The Wiz*: “Don’t nobody bring me no bad news.”\",\"index\":1291,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"Once you’ve mastered the keys, continuously practice what you’ve learned. As CEO, it’s critical to have an opinion on everything—forecasts, product plans, presentations, and comments. Express your thoughts clearly, whether you agree or disagree, and give feedback directly. \\n\\nThis approach has two key benefits: \\n\\n1. **Feedback in your company won’t be personal.** When giving constant feedback, people grow accustomed to it and focus on the issues rather than interpreting each comment as a personal judgment.\\n  \\n2. **Comfort in discussing bad news.** When people regularly talk about individual mistakes, they find it easier to address the company’s issues. High-quality cultures allow bad news to spread quickly, facilitating rapid problem-solving, unlike low-quality cultures that avoid bad news entirely.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**MAKING THE CEO**\",\"index\":1292,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Being CEO also requires a broad set of more advanced skills, but the key to reaching the advanced level and feeling like you were born to be CEO is mastering the unnatural.\",\"index\":1293,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"If you are a founder CEO and you feel awkward or incompetent when doing some of these things and believe there is no way that you’ll be able to do it when your company is one hundred or one thousand people, welcome to the club. That’s exactly how I felt. So did every CEO I’ve ever met. This is the process. This is how you get made.\",\"index\":1294,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"\",\"index\":1295,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\" \",\"index\":1296,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"Being a CEO requires mastering advanced and often unnatural skills. If you're a founder CEO feeling awkward or incompetent in certain aspects, and doubting your ability to manage a much larger company, know that this is completely normal. Every CEO, including myself and those I've met, has felt this way. This challenging journey is how you grow into the role.\",\"type\":\"section\"}],\"summary\":\"To give effective feedback, move beyond basic techniques like the \\\"Shit Sandwich\\\" and develop a style that mirrors your personality and values. Authenticity is essential, and your intention should always be to help the recipient improve. Focus on behavior instead of personal traits, avoid public criticism, and tailor your feedback to individual sensitivities. Being straightforward but kind helps avoid diluted messages. As a CEO, your feedback should foster open discussions and debates rather than shut them down. Promote high standards through in-depth discussions and be self-aware to recognize when you're wrong. Practice giving clear, direct feedback on various aspects of the business, as it benefits by removing personal judgments and cultivating ease in discussing bad news, thereby fostering a high-quality culture. If you’re feeling awkward or doubting your capabilities as a CEO, understand that this feeling is part of the growth process and is experienced by many.\",\"type\":\"section\"}],\"summary\":\"Being a CEO is an unnatural job, much like making Jolly Ranchers rather than growing them. While many people believe CEOs are born, the reality is that developing a CEO skill set takes years and involves mastering many unnatural actions. Just as boxing requires the unnatural motion of lifting the back foot first when moving backward to avoid getting knocked out, CEOs must learn to perform uncomfortable tasks like evaluating performance despite personal connections. Effective feedback is crucial, and it goes beyond techniques like the \\\"Shit Sandwich\\\"; it should reflect your true personality, focus on behavior rather than traits, and avoid public criticism. Tailor your feedback to individual sensitivities and always strive for clarity and kindness to ensure the message is received without being diluted. Encourage open discussions and debates to maintain high standards, and be ready to acknowledge your mistakes. Clear, direct communication helps eliminate personal judgments and facilitates addressing bad news, which fosters a high-quality organizational culture. Remember, the awkwardness and self-doubt you may feel as a CEO is part of the growth process, and it's something many go through.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**[HOW TO EVALUATE CEOs]()**\",\"index\":1297,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"No position in a company is more important than the CEO and, as a result, no job gets more scrutiny. The job is so poorly defined that you can end up doing all kinds of nutty things (especially if you listen to some people who say things like “the CEO should be the number-one salesperson”).\",\"index\":1298,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"Sadly, little of this analysis that’s been done benefits CEOs, since most of the discussions happen behind their backs. Here I want to take a step in the opposite direction. By describing how I evaluate CEOs, I am at the same time describing what I think the job of the CEO is. Here are the key questions we ask:\",\"index\":1299,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"**1.** Does the CEO know what to do?\",\"index\":1300,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"**2.** Can the CEO get the company to do what she knows?\",\"index\":1301,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"**3.** Did the CEO achieve the desired results against an appropriate set of objectives?\",\"index\":1302,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"type\":\"clump\",\"summary\":\"Sadly, little of this analysis that’s been done benefits CEOs, since most of the discussions happen behind their backs. Here I want to take a step in the opposite direction. By describing how I evaluate CEOs, I am at the same time describing what I think the job of the CEO is. Here are the key questions we ask: \\n\\n **1.** Does the CEO know what to do? \\n\\n **2.** Can the CEO get the company to do what she knows? \\n\\n **3.** Did the CEO achieve the desired results against an appropriate set of objectives?\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**1. DOES THE CEO KNOW WHAT TO DO?**\",\"index\":1303,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"One should interpret this question as broadly as possible. Does the CEO know what to do in all matters all the time? This includes matters of personnel, financing, product strategy, goal sizing, and marketing. At a macro level, does the CEO set the right strategy for the company and know its implications in every detail of the company?\",\"index\":1304,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"I evaluate two distinct facets of knowing what to do:\",\"index\":1305,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"* **Strategy** In good companies, the *story* and the *strategy* are the same thing. As a result, the proper output of all the strategic work is *the story*.\\n\\n* **Decision making** At the detailed level, the output of *knowing what to do* is *the speed and quality of the CEO’s* *decisions*.\",\"index\":1306,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**The strategy and the story**\",\"index\":1307,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"The CEO must set the context within which every employee operates. The context gives meaning to the specific work that people do, aligns interests, enables decision making, and provides motivation. Well-structured goals and objectives contribute to the context, but they do not provide the whole story. More to the point, they are not *the story*. The story of the company goes beyond quarterly or annual goals and gets to the hard-core question of *why*. *Why* should I join this company? *Why* should I be excited to work here? *Why* should I buy its product? *Why* should I invest in the company? *Why* is the world better off as a result of this company’s existence?\",\"index\":1308,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"When a company clearly articulates its story, the context for everyone—employees, partners, customers, investors, and the press—becomes clear. When a company fails to tell its story, you hear phrases like\",\"index\":1309,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"* These reporters don’t get it.\\n\\n* Who is responsible for the strategy in this company?\\n\\n* We have great technology, but need marketing help.\",\"index\":1310,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"type\":\"clump\",\"summary\":\"When a company clearly articulates its story, the context for everyone—employees, partners, customers, investors, and the press—becomes clear. When a company fails to tell its story, you hear phrases like \\n\\n * These reporters don’t get it.\\n\\n* Who is responsible for the strategy in this company?\\n\\n* We have great technology, but need marketing help.\"},{\"content\":\"The CEO doesn’t have to be the creator of the vision. Nor does she have to be the creator of the story. But she must be the keeper of the vision and the story. As such, the CEO ensures that the company story is clear and compelling.\",\"index\":1311,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"The story is not the mission statement; the story does not have to be succinct. It is the story. Companies can take as long as they need to tell it, but they must tell it and it must be compelling. A company without a story is usually a company without a strategy.\",\"index\":1312,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Want to see a great company story? Read Jeff Bezos’s three-page letter he wrote to shareholders in 1997. In telling Amazon’s story in this extended form—not as a mission statement, not as a tagline—Jeff got all the people who mattered on the same page as to what Amazon was about.\",\"index\":1313,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"The CEO must set the context for every employee, providing meaning, alignment, and motivation. Well-structured goals help, but the true power lies in the company's story, answering essential \\\"why\\\" questions that drive engagement and investment. A clearly articulated story aligns everyone—employees, partners, customers, investors, and the press. If the story is unclear, confusion and misalignment arise. The CEO doesn't have to create the vision or story but must be its guardian, ensuring it is clear and compelling. The story isn't a mission statement or tagline; it’s a narrative that can take time to tell fully. A company without a story often lacks strategy. For an exemplary company story, look at Jeff Bezos’s 1997 shareholder letter, which effectively united stakeholders around Amazon’s purpose.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**Decision making**\",\"index\":1314,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Some employees make products, some make sales; the CEO makes decisions. Therefore, a CEO can most accurately be measured by the speed and quality of those decisions. Great decisions come from CEOs who display an elite mixture of intelligence, logic, and courage.\",\"index\":1315,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"As already noted, courage is particularly important, because every decision that a CEO makes is based on incomplete information. At the time of any given decision, the CEO will generally have less than 10 percent of the information typically present in the post hoc Harvard Business School case study. As a result, the CEO must have the courage to bet the company on a direction even though she does not know if the direction is right. The most difficult decisions (and often the most important) are difficult precisely because they will be deeply unpopular with the CEO’s most important constituencies (employees, investors, and customers).\",\"index\":1316,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"The best decision that I made in my career—to sell the Loudcloud business to EDS and become Opsware—would have lost by a landslide had I put it to a vote with my employees, my investors, or my customers.\",\"index\":1317,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"As CEO, there is never enough time to gather all information needed to make a decision. You must make hundreds of decisions big and small in the course of a typical week. You cannot simply stop all other activities to gather comprehensive data and do exhaustive analysis to make that single decision. Knowing this, you must continuously and systematically gather knowledge in the company’s day-to-day activities so that you will have as much information as possible when the decision point arrives.\",\"index\":1318,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"In order to prepare to make any decision, you must systematically acquire the knowledge of everything that might impact any decision that you might make. Questions such as:\",\"index\":1319,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"* What are the competitors likely to do?\\n\\n* What’s possible technically and in what time frame?\\n\\n* What are the true capabilities of the organization and how can you maximize them?\\n\\n* How much financial risk does this imply?\\n\\n* What will the issues be, given your current product architecture?\\n\\n* Will the employees be energized or despondent about this promotion?\",\"index\":1320,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"type\":\"clump\",\"summary\":\"In order to prepare to make any decision, you must systematically acquire the knowledge of everything that might impact any decision that you might make. Questions such as: \\n\\n * What are the competitors likely to do?\\n\\n* What’s possible technically and in what time frame?\\n\\n* What are the true capabilities of the organization and how can you maximize them?\\n\\n* How much financial risk does this imply?\\n\\n* What will the issues be, given your current product architecture?\\n\\n* Will the employees be energized or despondent about this promotion?\"},{\"content\":\"Great CEOs build exceptional strategies for gathering the required information continuously. They embed their quest for intelligence into all of their daily actions from staff meetings to customer meetings to one-on-ones. Winning strategies are built on comprehensive knowledge gathered in every interaction the CEO has with an employee, a customer, a partner, or an investor.\",\"index\":1321,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"A CEO's effectiveness is measured by the speed and quality of their decisions, relying heavily on intelligence, logic, and especially courage since decisions must often be made with incomplete information. This courage is crucial because pivotal and sometimes unpopular decisions can shape the company's future, such as selling Loudcloud to EDS and transforming it into Opsware, a decision that was largely opposed by employees, investors, and customers. Given the constant need for decision-making and the impossibility of halting operations for exhaustive data collection, a CEO must continuously and systematically gather relevant knowledge every day. This involves understanding competitors, technical capabilities, organizational strengths, financial risks, potential issues, and employee morale. Effective CEOs incorporate this intelligence-gathering into their daily routines, building strategies based on comprehensive information collected through interactions with employees, customers, partners, and investors.\",\"type\":\"section\"}],\"summary\":\"A CEO's effectiveness hinges on their ability to know what to do in all areas, from personnel and financing to product strategy and marketing. At a macro level, the CEO must set a clear strategy that permeates through every detail of the company. Two vital components of this are strategy and decision-making. A coherent story, which aligns with the strategy, provides meaning, alignment, and motivation for all stakeholders. This narrative should answer crucial \\\"why\\\" questions and ensure everyone understands the company’s purpose, as seen in Jeff Bezos’s 1997 shareholder letter for Amazon. At the micro level, the CEO's decision-making is judged by the speed and quality of their choices, which requires intelligence, logic, and particularly courage, given that decisions often need to be made with incomplete information. Effective decision-making necessitates ongoing and systematic information gathering on competitors, technical capabilities, organizational strengths, financial risks, potential issues, and employee morale. This continuous vigilance enables the CEO to create strategies based on a full understanding of the internal and external dynamics affecting the company.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**2. CAN THE CEO GET THE COMPANY TO DO WHAT SHE KNOWS?**\",\"index\":1322,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"If the CEO paints a compelling vision and makes fast, high-quality decisions, can she then get the company to execute her vision? The first ingredient in being able to do this is leadership, as I outlined in the section “Follow the Leader.”\",\"index\":1323,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},