bility is the quality of the team. It’s important to note that team quality is tightly tied to the specific needs of the company in the challenges it faces at the point in time it faces them. As a result, it’s quite possible that the executive team changes several times, but the team is high quality the entire way and there is no attrition problem.\",\"index\":1329,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"As the CEO, you hold the responsibility for the executive team and the fundamental interview and hiring processes for all employees. It's crucial to source the best candidates and ensure the screening processes yield individuals with the right talent and skills. The quality of your team is at the core of running the company successfully. Great CEOs continuously assess and build the best team to meet the company's specific needs at any given time. This means the executive team may change multiple times, yet consistently be of high quality without facing attrition issues.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**Is it easy for employees to contribute to the mission?**\",\"index\":1330,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"The second part of the evaluation determines whether the CEO can effectively run the company. To test this, I like to ask this question: “How easy is it for any given individual contributor to get her job done?”\",\"index\":1331,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"In well-run organizations, people can focus on their work (as opposed to politics and bureaucratic procedures) and have confidence that if they get their work done, good things will happen both for the company and for them personally. By contrast, in a poorly run organization, people spend much of their time fighting organizational boundaries and broken processes.\",\"index\":1332,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"While it may be quite easy to describe, building a well-run organization requires a high level of skill. The skills required range from organizational design to performance management. They involve the incentive structure and the communication architecture that drive and enable every individual employee. When a CEO “fails to scale,” it’s usually along this dimension. In practice, very few CEOs get an A on this particular test.\",\"index\":1333,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Netflix’s CEO, Reed Hastings, put great effort into designing a system that enables employees to be maximally effective. His presentation of this design is called Reference Guide on Our Freedom and Responsibility Culture. It walks through what Netflix values in their employees, how they screen for those values during the interview process, how they reinforce those values, and how they scale this system as the number of employees grows.\",\"index\":1334,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"The second part of the evaluation assesses whether the CEO can run the company effectively, which I gauge by asking, \\\"How easy is it for any individual contributor to get her job done?\\\" In well-run organizations, employees focus on their work without being bogged down by politics and bureaucracy, confident that their efforts benefit both them and the company. Conversely, poorly run organizations force employees to navigate through organizational barriers and broken processes. Despite sounding straightforward, creating such a well-functioning organization demands a high level of skill in areas like organizational design, performance management, incentive structures, and communication architecture. CEOs often falter here, with few excelling. Reed Hastings of Netflix exemplifies success in this area through his \\\"Reference Guide on Our Freedom and Responsibility Culture,\\\" which details how Netflix values, screens, reinforces, and scales the effectiveness of its employees.\",\"type\":\"section\"}],\"summary\":\"As the CEO, you are responsible for the executive team and the hiring processes, ensuring you source the best candidates with the right talent and skills. The quality of your team is crucial for running the company successfully, which involves continuously assessing and building the right team for the company's needs, even if it means changing the executive team multiple times. Evaluating your ability to run the company effectively involves asking, \\\"How easy is it for any individual contributor to get her job done?\\\" In well-managed organizations, employees focus on their work without being hampered by politics and bureaucracy, confident that their efforts benefit both them and the company. Creating such an environment requires skill in organizational design, performance management, incentive structures, and communication architecture—areas where many CEOs struggle but a few, like Reed Hastings of Netflix, excel through principles like those in the \\\"Reference Guide on Our Freedom and Responsibility Culture.\\\"\",\"type\":\"section\"}],\"summary\":\"To ensure the company executes the CEO's vision, it requires both strong leadership and a broad set of operational skills. Larger organizations need even more elaborate skill sets. Execution hinges on two key factors: the company must have the capacity, meaning the right talent in key positions, and it must be an environment where employees can effectively get things done. This involves motivated staff, strong communication, expansive common knowledge, and clear context. As CEO, your responsibilities include managing the executive team and hiring processes to source top talent. Continuously assessing and building the right team, potentially changing the executive team as needed, is crucial. A well-managed company allows employees to focus on their work without being bogged down by politics or bureaucracy, ensuring efforts benefit both individuals and the company. Achieving this requires skill in organizational design, perfor