r Jurvetson . . . and Google, one of our great colleagues. Then a year later, in 2005, the company went public. The ideal price was $27 \\\\[the stock’s initial offer price\\\\] and it closed on the first day at $122. It was great for many of the Baidu employees and for all of the Baidu investors. It was a very miserable thing for me because when I decided to take the company public, I was only prepared to deliver financial results that match the price of $27 or maybe a little higher, $30, $40. But I was really shocked to see that the price went to $122 on the first day. So that meant I needed to deliver real results that matched an expectation much, much higher than what I had prepared to do. But in any case, I thought I had no choice. So I put my head down and focused on operations, focused on technology, focused on the user’s experience, and I delivered.*\",\"index\":1338,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Once we’ve taken all of this into account, we see that the results against objectives or “black box” results are a *lagging* indicator. And as they say in the mutual fund prospectuses, “past performance is no guarantee of future results.” The white-box CEO evaluation criteria—“Does the CEO know what to do?” and “Can the CEO get the company to do it?”—will do a much better job of predicting the future.\",\"index\":1339,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"When measuring results against objectives, it's crucial to ensure those objectives are set correctly. CEOs can manipulate outcomes by setting low objectives, while others might fail by aiming too high. Early-stage companies often face uncertain opportunities, making it essential to set appropriate goals. It’s also important to evaluate CEOs based on their specific company’s opportunity rather than comparing them to different businesses. For example, Robin Li, CEO of Baidu, experienced unexpected pressure when Baidu’s IPO stock price soared beyond his initial expectations. Despite his initial shock, he focused on delivering results that matched the higher value. This story underscores that results against objectives are a lagging indicator and not always predictive of future performance. More reliable criteria for evaluating a CEO include their knowledge of what to do and their ability to execute strategies effectively.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**CLOSING THOUGHT**\",\"index\":1340,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"CEO evaluation need not be a byzantine, unarticulated art. All people, including CEOs, will perform better on a test if they know the questions ahead of time.\",\"index\":1341,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"CEO evaluation need not be a byzantine, unarticulated art. All people, including CEOs, will perform better on a test if they know the questions ahead of time.\",\"type\":\"section\"}],\"summary\":\"A CEO's effectiveness hinges on knowing what to do across all company areas, from personnel and finance to product strategy and marketing. At a macro level, setting a clear strategy and decision-making process is crucial, creating a coherent story that provides meaning, alignment, and motivation for all stakeholders. This narrative should answer critical \\\"why\\\" questions, ensuring everyone understands the company’s purpose, much like Jeff Bezos’s 1997 shareholder letter for Amazon. Decision-making at the micro level, judged by speed and quality, requires intelligence, logic, and particularly courage, often with incomplete information. Continuous and systematic information gathering on competitors, technical capabilities, organizational strengths, financial risks, issues, and employee morale is essential for effective strategies.\\n\\nExecution relies on strong leadership and operational skills, especially in larger organizations. This requires having the right talent in key positions and an environment conducive to productivity. This entails motivated staff, strong communication, common knowledge, and clear context. A CEO must manage the executive team and hiring processes, continuously assessing and ensuring the right team, adapting as necessary. Organizational design, performance management, incentive structures, and communication are vital, as demonstrated by Reed Hastings of Netflix with guiding principles like the \\\"Reference Guide on Our Freedom and Responsibility Culture.\\\"\\n\\nWhen measuring results against objectives, it's important to set appropriate goals, particularly in early-stage companies facing uncertain opportunities. CEOs must be evaluated based on their specific company’s opportunity, not compared to different businesses. For instance, Robin Li of Baidu adapted to the unexpected pressure of a soaring IPO stock price by focusing on delivering results aligned with the company’s higher value. This highlights that results against objectives are lagging indicators and not always predictive of future performance. More reliable criteria for evaluating a CEO include their knowledge of what to do and their ability to execute strategies effectively. Effective CEO evaluation should be straightforward, ensuring clarity on what is being assessed.\",\"type\":\"section\"}],\"summary\":\"No position in a company is more scrutinized than the CEO, whose role is so poorly defined that it can lead to doing all kinds of impractical things. Despite substantial behind-the-scenes analysis, this information rarely benefits CEOs directly. To remedy this, I propose evaluating CEOs through three key questions: Do they know what to do? Can they get the company to do it? Did they achieve the desired results against appropriate objectives? A CEO must act decisively across all company areas, creating a clear, meaningful strategy that aligns and motivates stakeholders. Effective decision-making must balance speed and quality, requiring intelligence and courage. Execution depends on strong leadership, operational skills, and having the right talent in key roles within a conducive environment. Managing the executive team, organizational design, performance management, and communication are critical, as illustrated by leaders like Reed Hastings of Netflix. Evaluation of results should consider the specific company's context and goals, focusing more on the CEO's knowledge and execution ability than on lagging performance indicators.\",\"type\":\"section\"}],\"summary\":\"As a CEO, developing my own psychology was my toughest challenge, surpassing organizational design, metrics or hiring. Initially underestimating this, I found it's a common but rarely discussed struggle among CEOs. Managing a complex organization in a competitive market involves solitary, high-stress decision-making. To handle stress and avoid being overwhelmed, I leaned on psychological support, detailed decision-making, and goal-oriented focus. Resilience and never giving up are essential, as Alfred Chuang noted. Courage, often more crucial than intelligence, is vital for leadership, especially in crisis situations. Clear decision-making roles are crucial; dual leadership often leads to inefficiency. Faced with daunting decisions, like taking Loudcloud public to avoid bankruptcy with minimal revenue or declining lucrative acquisition offers, I've learned that courage and correct decisions build essential leadership qualities. Jim Collins' *Good to Great* notes internal candidates outperform due to deeper company knowledge but doesn't cover why some fail, which I attribute to imbalances in strategic and operational skills. Effective leadership involves vision, ambition for alignment, and competence, with varied styles like Jobs, Campbell, and Grove proving successful. Legendary advisor Bill Campbell highlighted the rare combination of peacetime and wartime leadership, necessary for navigating periods of stability and crisis. CEOs need to embrace unnatural actions, like giving uncomfortable feedback and developing a unique skill set over years. Clear, kind communication and direct feedback are vital for maintaining high standards and addressing issues. Evaluating a CEO's performance should focus on their knowledge, execution ability, and results, considering the company's context, as illustrated by leaders like Reed Hastings of Netflix.\",\"type\":\"section\"}],\"summary\":\"Our company faced a critical juncture after selling Loudcloud to EDS, which confused investors and tanked our stock to $0.35 per share, risking NASDAQ delisting. Rather than resorting to reverse splits or penny stock status, I, with guidance from Ron Conway, sought investor support, ultimately convincing Herb Allen of Allen & Company to invest, lifting our stock to $3 per share and restoring hope. This pivotal moment underscored focusing on essential success factors rather than past or potential mistakes. As a CEO, my toughest challenge was developing my own psychology amidst stress and solitary decision-making. Psychological support, detailed decision-making, and goal-oriented focus helped me cope, emphasizing resilience, courage, and unwavering tenacity, as stressed by Alfred Chuang. Effective leadership requires clear decision-making roles and a balance between vision, ambition, and competence, with examples from leaders like Steve Jobs, Bill Campbell, and Andy Grove. Advisors like Bill Campbell highlighted the importance of peacetime and wartime leadership. CEOs must embrace uncomfortable actions, ensuring clear, kind communication and direct feedback for high standards. Performance should be evaluated based on knowledge, execution, and results, as seen in leaders like Reed Hastings of Netflix.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**[— CHAPTER 8 —]()**\",\"index\":1342,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"**[FIRST RULE OF ENTREPRENEURSHIP: THERE ARE NO RULES]()**\",\"index\":1343,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"