t me. During that time, the press declared the company dead and shareholders called for my resignation. No, I was not considered to be very good at all.\",\"index\":1505,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"In retrospect, people’s perceptions changed because of the sale to HP and the things that I’ve since written. Once I stopped being CEO, I was granted a freedom that I did not have before. As a venture capitalist, I have had the freedom to say what I want and what I really think without worrying what everybody else thinks. As a CEO, there is no such luxury. As CEO, I had to worry about what everybody else thought. In particular, I could not show weakness in public. It would not have been fair to the employees, the executives, or the public company shareholders. Unrelenting confidence was necessary.\",\"index\":1506,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"When we started Andreessen Horowitz, I could let all that go. Sure, we still have employees, but we do not have public shareholders who live and die on every piece of press. More important, at Andreessen Horowitz I am not really CEO. We invest in companies that have CEOs. The burden of unrelenting confidence lies with them. I can now share my weaknesses, my fears, and my shortcomings. I can say what I want without worrying about offending the wrong people in the power structure. And it’s those fears and controversial opinions that hold the clues to dealing with hard things. Hard things are hard because there are no easy answers or recipes. They are hard because your emotions are at odds with your logic. They are hard because you don’t know the answer and you cannot ask for help without showing weakness.\",\"index\":1507,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"When I first became a CEO, I genuinely thought that I was the only one struggling. Whenever I spoke to other CEOs, they all seemed like they had everything under control. Their businesses were always going “fantastic” and their experience was inevitably “amazing.” I thought that maybe growing up in Berkeley with Communist grandparents might not have been the best background for running a company. But as I watched my peers’ fantastic, amazing businesses go bankrupt and sell for cheap, I realized that I was probably not the only one struggling.\",\"index\":1508,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"As I got further into it, I realized that embracing the unusual parts of my background would be the key to making it through. It would be those things that would give me unique perspectives and approaches to the business. The things that I would bring to the table that nobody else had. It was my borrowing Chico Mendoza’s shocking yet poetic style to motivate and focus the team. It was my understanding of the people underneath the persona and skin color that enabled me to put Jason Rosenthal together with Anthony Wright to save the company. It was even my bringing in to the most capitalistic pursuit imaginable what Karl Marx got right. On my grandfather’s tombstone, you will find his favorite Marx quote: “Life is struggle.” I believe that within that quote lies the most important lesson in entrepreneurship: Embrace the struggle.\",\"index\":1509,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"When I work with entrepreneurs today, this is the main thing that I try to convey. Embrace your weirdness, your background, your instinct. If the keys are not in there, they do not exist. I can relate to what they’re going through, but I cannot tell them what to do. I can only help them find it in themselves. And sometimes they can find peace where I could not.\",\"index\":1510,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Of course, even with all the advice and hindsight in the world, hard things will continue to be hard things. So, in closing, I just say peace to all those engaged in the struggle to fulfill their dreams.\",\"index\":1511,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"I often joke that I am considered a much better CEO now than when I actually held the position. Nowadays, some call me a management guru, but during my time managing Opsware, feedback was far from flattering. Felicia likes to say, “They called you everything but a child of God.” What changed: me or the perception of me? Though I learned a lot and am embarrassed by my early days, I became proficient, evidenced by shifting our business midstream, growing its value from $29 million to $1.65 billion in five years, and achieving a successful acquisition by HP. Many former employees now work with me at Andreessen Horowitz or in our portfolio companies, showing they valued our collaboration. From 2003 to 2007, positive comments about my leadership were rare; the press wrote us off, and shareholders wanted me gone. After selling to HP and stepping down as CEO, I gained the freedom to express my true thoughts, unlike when I managed public scrutiny. As a venture capitalist and co-founder of Andreessen Horowitz, I now share my fears and shortcomings, a stark contrast to my CEO days where confidence was crucial. Initially, I thought I was the only struggling CEO, but seeing others' struggles made me realize my unique background was an asset. Embracing my experiences helped me navigate challenges and offer unique insights. Today, I advise entrepreneurs to value their backgrounds and instincts, understanding that although hard things remain hard, finding peace in the struggle to achieve dreams is essential.\",\"type\":\"section\"}],\"summary\":\"Back in 1999, after securing initial funding for Loudcloud, I faced doubts about my capability as CEO, leading to months of self-doubt. Guided by Bill Campbell's mentorship, I persevered, and Loudcloud thrived. This experience, combined with insights from Marc, led to the creation of Andreessen Horowitz, aimed at helping technical founders grow into their CEO roles. Inspired by Michael Ovitz's CAA model, we built an integrated network connecting partners to key industry players, ensuring robust mentorship. Despite skepticism, we launched with significant PR and hired top marketing talent to feature on a 2009 *Fortune* cover, setting us apart. Early hires, like Scott Kupor and Mark Cranney, were informed by lessons from Loudcloud and Opsware, propelling Andreessen Horowitz into a globally respected VC firm within four years. \\n\\nI often joke about my improved CEO reputation now. Felicia humorously recalls past criticisms. The perception shift: me or others? Though embarrassed by early mistakes, I grew, transforming Opsware from $29 million to $1.65 billion before HP's acquisition. Many former employees chose to join me at Andreessen Horowitz, validating our collaboration. From 2003 to 2007, praise was scarce, with press and shareholders wanting me out. Post-HP sale, I freely express my thoughts, starkly contrasting my constrained CEO days. Now, as a venture capitalist, I share my struggles openly. Initially feeling alone, I realized others' struggles made my unique background an asset. Embracing this, I offer entrepreneurs the advice to trust their instincts and understand that while hard challenges persist, peace in the struggle is key to achieving their dreams.\",\"type\":\"section\"}],\"summary\":\"“We walk the same path, but got on different shoes. Live in the same building, but we got different views.” —Drake, “Right Above It”\\n\\nAfter selling Opsware, I spent a year at HP before contemplating my next move. Should I start another company, become a CEO elsewhere, retire, or try something new? Reflecting on my past, especially on Bill Campbell's mentorship, I wondered why there was so little documented guidance for entrepreneurs. This led me to message Marc Andreessen with the idea of starting a venture capital firm requiring actual entrepreneurial experience to advise new companies. Coincidentally, he had the same thought. In 2009, inspired by Michael Ovitz's CAA model, we launched Andreessen Horowitz, emphasizing mentorship and networking. Despite initial skepticism, strategic hires and substantial PR efforts quickly established us as a prominent VC firm. My journey included growing Opsware significantly before its acquisition, enduring criticism, and eventually being validated by former employees joining Andreessen Horowitz. Now, as a venture capitalist, I openly share my early struggles, recognizing my unique background as an asset. I advise entrepreneurs to trust their instincts, find peace in their challenges, and persist to achieve their dreams.\",\"type\":\"section\"}],\"summary\":\"I recently hosted a barbecue for a hundred friends, including my barbecue enthusiast brother-in-law, Cartheu, where conversations intertwined histories such as my friend Tristan Walker marveling at Nas's roots in Queensbridge and my father recounting distributing communist literature in the same area during his childhood. Raised in a \\\"red-diaper\\\" communist family in Berkeley, I transformed from a shy kid into an entrepreneur thanks to Joel Clark Jr.'s influence. My career journey took me through Silicon Graphics, NetLabs, Lotus, and Netscape, before co-founding Loudcloud, which faced significant highs and lows, eventually selling to EDS. Post-sale, I refocused Opsware, securing its sale to Hewlett-Packard for $1.6 billion by integrating employees deeply and overcoming challenges with transparent communication, collective intelligence, and balancing accountability with creativity. This led to the creation of a new venture capital firm, Andreessen Horowitz, with Marc Andreessen in 2009, based on the CAA model with a focus on mentorship and networking. Despite initial skepticism, our strategic hires and significant PR efforts quickly made us a leading VC firm. Reflecting on my struggles, I now advise entrepreneurs to trust their instincts, find peace in challenges, and persist to achieve their dreams, recognizing my unique background as an asset.\",\"type\":\"section\"}"
